window.MM.med_p2_nephro=[
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the most common cause of intrinsic (intra-renal) acute kidney injury?", "a": "Acute Tubular Necrosis", "b": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis", "c": "Renal Artery Stenosis", "d": "Glomerulonephritis", "ans": "A", "e": "Acute tubular necrosis is the most common cause of intrinsic AKI; ischaemic or nephrotoxic injury to tubular epithelium produces characteristic loss of cell polarity, sloughing, and intratubular obstruction.<br><br>Standard combined with ischaemic causes (sepsis, shock, prolonged pre-renal state) and nephrotoxic causes (aminoglycosides, contrast, cisplatin, amphotericin, myoglobin). Combined with three phases: initiation, maintenance, recovery.<br><br>Acute Interstitial Nephritis (option B) is principally drug-induced hypersensitivity; Renal Artery Stenosis (option C) is pre-renal pattern; Glomerulonephritis (option D) features RBC casts and proteinuria, none being intrinsic AKI most common cause like acute tubular necrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In Acute Tubular Necrosis, the Fractional Excretion of Sodium (FeNa) is typically:", "a": "< 1%", "b": "> 2%", "c": "< 0.1%", "d": "< 0.5%", "ans": "B", "e": "Over 2 percent fractional excretion of sodium characterises acute tubular necrosis; damaged tubules cannot reabsorb filtered sodium producing characteristic high FeNa distinguishing from pre-renal azotemia.<br><br>Standard FeNa = (urine Na x plasma Cr)/(plasma Na x urine Cr) x 100. Combined with FeNa under 1 percent suggesting pre-renal (avid sodium reabsorption).<br><br>< 1% (option A) suggests pre-renal azotemia; < 0.1% (option C) is not principal ATN threshold; < 0.5% (option D) is not principal ATN threshold, none being ATN FeNa like over 2 percent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a classic nephrotoxic cause of Acute Tubular Necrosis?", "a": "Prednisone", "b": "Penicillin", "c": "Vitamin C", "d": "Aminoglycosides", "ans": "D", "e": "Aminoglycosides are classic nephrotoxic cause of ATN; cationic drugs accumulate in proximal tubular cells producing characteristic direct tubular toxicity through lysosomal disruption.<br><br>Standard risk factors: prolonged duration over 7-10 days, concurrent nephrotoxins (loop diuretics, vancomycin, NSAIDs), volume depletion, elderly, pre-existing CKD. Combined with prevention: once-daily dosing, trough monitoring, dose adjustment. Non-oliguric ATN characteristic.<br><br>Prednisone (option A) lacks principal nephrotoxicity; Penicillin (option B) causes AIN (hypersensitivity); Vitamin C (option C) is not principal ATN cause, none being classic ATN nephrotoxin like aminoglycosides.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The presence of \"muddy brown\" granular casts in urine sediment is characteristic of:", "a": "Pre-renal azotemia", "b": "Acute Tubular Necrosis", "c": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis", "d": "Post-renal obstruction", "ans": "B", "e": "Acute tubular necrosis features muddy brown granular casts on urine sediment; sloughed tubular epithelial cells with pigment produce characteristic granular casts.<br><br>Standard other ATN urine findings: tubular epithelial cells, tubular epithelial cell casts, FeNa over 2 percent, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg (isosthenuria), urine sodium over 40 mEq/L. Treatment supportive (fluid/electrolyte management, dialysis if needed).<br><br>Pre-renal azotemia (option A) features hyaline casts and bland sediment; Post-renal obstruction (option D) features bland sediment, none being ATN urinary hallmark like muddy brown granular casts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient develops AKI 48 hours after a CT scan with IV contrast. What is the most likely diagnosis?", "a": "Contrast-Induced Nephropathy", "b": "Pre-renal Azotemia", "c": "Cholesterol Embolization", "d": "Allergic Interstitial Nephritis", "ans": "A", "e": "Contrast-induced nephropathy fits AKI 48 hours after CT scan with IV contrast; characteristic creatinine rise within 24-72 hours after contrast administration peaks at 3-5 days.<br><br>Standard risk factors: pre-existing CKD, diabetes mellitus, volume depletion, NSAIDs, ACE inhibitors, high contrast volume, elderly. Prevention: isotonic saline hydration before and after, minimising contrast volume, avoiding nephrotoxins. N-acetylcysteine not proven.<br><br>Pre-renal Azotemia (option B) responds to fluids; Cholesterol Embolization (option C) features livedo and eosinophilia; Allergic Interstitial Nephritis (option D) features rash with longer drug exposure, none being post-contrast 48-hour AKI like contrast-induced nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a key risk factor for developing pigment-induced ATN?", "a": "Hypotension", "b": "Rhabdomyolysis", "c": "Hypercalcemia", "d": "Low protein diet", "ans": "B", "e": "Rhabdomyolysis is key risk factor for pigment-induced ATN; myoglobin released from damaged muscle produces characteristic direct tubular toxicity and tubular obstruction.<br><br>Standard causes: crush injury, prolonged immobilisation, intense exercise, seizures, drugs (statins, cocaine), alcohol intoxication, heatstroke. Diagnosis: elevated CK over 5000 IU/L, positive urine dipstick for blood without RBCs. Treatment: aggressive isotonic saline, urine alkalinisation.<br><br>Hypotension (option A) causes ischaemic ATN (separate mechanism); Hypercalcemia (option C) causes pre-renal AKI; Low protein diet (option D) is unrelated, none being pigment ATN cause like rhabdomyolysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis (AIN) is most commonly caused by:", "a": "Drug-induced hypersensitivity", "b": "Heavy metal exposure", "c": "Ischemia", "d": "Urinary tract stones", "ans": "A", "e": "Drug-induced hypersensitivity is most common AIN cause; characteristic delayed type IV hypersensitivity reaction to drugs produces interstitial inflammation.<br><br>Standard offenders: antibiotics (penicillins, cephalosporins, sulfonamides, rifampin), NSAIDs (typically without classic triad), PPIs, allopurinol, diuretics. Diagnosis: urinary eosinophils (Hansel stain), WBC casts, biopsy showing interstitial infiltrate with eosinophils. Standard supportive care guides management. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Heavy metal exposure (option B) causes chronic interstitial nephritis; Ischemia (option C) causes ATN; Urinary tract stones (option D) cause post-renal AKI, none being AIN principal cause like drug-induced hypersensitivity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The classic clinical triad of Acute Interstitial Nephritis includes fever, rash, and:", "a": "Polyuria", "b": "Hypertension", "c": "Hematuria", "d": "Eosinophilia", "ans": "D", "e": "Eosinophilia completes the classic AIN triad with fever and rash; characteristic peripheral eosinophilia over 500 cells reflects hypersensitivity reaction to drug or other antigen.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: urinary eosinophils on Hansel stain (specific but not sensitive - absent in NSAID AIN), WBC casts, sterile pyuria, mild proteinuria, haematuria. Treatment: discontinue offending drug, corticosteroids if no improvement within 5-7 days.<br><br>Polyuria (option A) is recovery phase finding; Hypertension (option B) is unrelated; Hematuria (option C) is associated but not classic triad component, none being AIN classic triad component like eosinophilia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which class of drugs is a notorious cause of Acute Interstitial Nephritis?", "a": "Proton Pump Inhibitors", "b": "ACE inhibitors", "c": "Beta-blockers", "d": "Statins", "ans": "A", "e": "Proton pump inhibitors are notorious cause of acute interstitial nephritis; long-term PPI use produces characteristic AIN often without classic triad.<br><br>Standard clinical suspicion in patients on PPIs (omeprazole, esomeprazole, lansoprazole) presenting with unexplained AKI. Diagnosis: urinalysis (WBC casts, mild proteinuria), urinary eosinophils, biopsy confirmation. Treatment: discontinue PPI, corticosteroids for severe or non-resolving disease.<br><br>ACE inhibitors (option B) cause functional pre-renal AKI; Beta-blockers (option C) lack principal AIN association; Statins (option D) cause rhabdomyolysis-induced ATN, none being notorious AIN cause like proton pump inhibitors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In intrinsic AKI like ATN, the urine osmolality is usually:", "a": "0 mOsm/kg", "b": "1000 mOsm/kg", "c": "> 500 mOsm/kg", "d": "< 350 mOsm/kg", "ans": "D", "e": "Under 350 mOsm/kg urine osmolality occurs in intrinsic AKI like ATN; characteristic loss of tubular concentrating ability produces isosthenuria with urine osmolality close to plasma 300 mOsm/kg.<br><br>Standard other ATN markers: FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, muddy brown casts, tubular epithelial cell casts. Pre-renal azotemia features urine osmolality over 500 mOsm/kg (preserved concentrating ability).<br><br>0 mOsm/kg (option A) is impossible; 1000 mOsm/kg (option B) is highly concentrated (pre-renal); > 500 mOsm/kg (option C) suggests pre-renal azotemia, none being ATN urine osmolality like under 350 mOsm/kg.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which finding on urine microscopy is highly suggestive of Acute Interstitial Nephritis?", "a": "Hyaline casts", "b": "Fatty casts", "c": "White blood cell casts and eosinophils", "d": "Red blood cell casts", "ans": "C", "e": "White blood cell casts and eosinophils are highly suggestive of acute interstitial nephritis; characteristic interstitial inflammation with hypersensitivity produces these urinary findings.<br><br>Standard Hansel stain for urinary eosinophils (specific but not sensitive), pyuria with sterile cultures, mild proteinuria, haematuria. Combined with ruling out infection (negative urine culture). Biopsy gold standard if diagnosis unclear.<br><br>Hyaline casts (option A) are non-specific (dehydration, exercise); Fatty casts (option B) suggest nephrotic syndrome; Red blood cell casts (option D) suggest glomerulonephritis, none being AIN urinary findings like white blood cell casts and eosinophils.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the \"gold standard\" for confirming a diagnosis of Acute Interstitial Nephritis?", "a": "24-hour urine protein", "b": "CT Scan", "c": "Renal Ultrasound", "d": "Renal Biopsy", "ans": "D", "e": "Renal biopsy is gold standard for confirming acute interstitial nephritis; characteristic interstitial inflammatory infiltrate with eosinophils confirms diagnosis when clinical features unclear.<br><br>Standard indications: unclear diagnosis, no improvement after drug discontinuation, considering corticosteroid therapy. Treatment: discontinue offending drug (primary management), corticosteroids if no improvement within 5-7 days or biopsy-confirmed severe disease. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>24-hour urine protein (option A) quantifies proteinuria; CT Scan (option B) shows structural pathology; Renal Ultrasound (option C) excludes obstruction, none being AIN definitive diagnosis like renal biopsy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which phase of ATN is associated with the highest risk of life-threatening hyperkalemia?", "a": "Maintenance phase", "b": "Initiation phase", "c": "Diuretic phase", "d": "Recovery phase", "ans": "A", "e": "Maintenance phase carries highest risk of life-threatening hyperkalaemia in ATN; characteristic oliguria with established tubular dysfunction produces potassium retention.<br><br>Standard maintenance phase features: oliguria (under 400 mL/day), elevated creatinine and BUN, hyperkalaemia, metabolic acidosis (high anion gap), hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia, fluid overload. Duration typically 1-2 weeks. Treatment: dialysis for refractory hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Initiation phase (option B) features hours-days of declining urine output; Diuretic phase (option C) features hypokalaemia risk; Recovery phase (option D) features normalising function, none being highest hyperkalaemia risk phase like maintenance phase.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "During the recovery (diuretic) phase of ATN, patients are at risk for:", "a": "Acute hypertension", "b": "Fluid overload", "c": "Encephalopathy", "d": "Dehydration and hypokalemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Dehydration and hypokalaemia occur during the recovery (diuretic) phase of ATN; characteristic restoration of glomerular function before tubular function produces inappropriate diuresis with electrolyte losses.<br><br>Standard diuretic phase features: gradual rise in urine output (often over 3 L/day), continued elevated creatinine initially, normalising over weeks. Management: careful fluid replacement, potassium and magnesium replacement, monitoring electrolytes daily, gradual return to normal function.<br><br>Acute hypertension (option A) is uncommon in diuretic phase; Encephalopathy (option C) is uraemic complication of maintenance phase, none being diuretic phase risk like dehydration and hypokalaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a common metabolic finding in ATN?", "a": "Hypophosphatemia", "b": "High anion gap metabolic acidosis", "c": "Hypercalcemia", "d": "Respiratory alkalosis", "ans": "B", "e": "High anion gap metabolic acidosis is common metabolic finding in ATN; characteristic accumulation of unmeasured anions (urate, phosphate, sulphate, organic acids) from reduced renal clearance.<br><br>Standard ABG showing low pH, low bicarbonate, elevated anion gap (over 12 mEq/L). Combined with other ATN findings (hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia).<br><br>Hypophosphatemia (option A) is not principal ATN finding (hyperphosphataemia occurs); Hypercalcemia (option C) is not principal ATN finding (hypocalcaemia occurs); Respiratory alkalosis (option D) is not principal ATN finding, none being ATN metabolic finding like high anion gap metabolic acidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "\"Isosthenuria\" (urine osmolality equal to plasma) is a feature of:", "a": "Acute Tubular Necrosis", "b": "Diabetes Insipidus", "c": "Pre-renal azotemia", "d": "Hepatorenal syndrome", "ans": "A", "e": "Acute tubular necrosis features isosthenuria with urine osmolality equal to plasma; characteristic loss of tubular concentrating ability produces fixed urine osmolality around 300 mOsm/kg.<br><br>Standard other ATN markers: FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, muddy brown casts, tubular epithelial cell casts, fixed specific gravity around 1.010. Combined with addressing causes (ischaemic, nephrotoxic), supportive management.<br><br>Diabetes Insipidus (option B) features dilute urine with normal plasma osmolality; Hepatorenal syndrome (option D) features concentrated urine, none being isosthenuria disease like acute tubular necrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which laboratory test is most useful to differentiate AIN from ATN when eosinophils are absent?", "a": "Urine Sodium", "b": "Presence of WBC casts without bacteria", "c": "Serum Creatinine", "d": "Serum Potassium", "ans": "B", "e": "Presence of WBC casts without bacteria differentiates AIN from ATN when eosinophils absent; characteristic interstitial inflammation produces WBC casts in sterile urine.<br><br>Standard other distinguishing features: AIN typically has drug exposure history, sometimes fever/rash, mild proteinuria. ATN features muddy brown casts, tubular epithelial cell casts, isosthenuria, FeNa over 2 percent without WBC casts.<br><br>Urine Sodium (option A) is elevated in both AIN and ATN; Serum Potassium (option D) is elevated in both, none being AIN vs ATN distinguishing test like presence of WBC casts without bacteria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of drug-induced Acute Interstitial Nephritis primarily involves:", "a": "Discontinuation of the offending agent", "b": "Long-term antibiotics", "c": "Aggressive hydration", "d": "Immediate dialysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Discontinuation of offending agent is primary management of drug-induced AIN; characteristic removal of triggering antigen allows resolution in most patients.<br><br>Standard monitoring renal function after discontinuation (creatinine should improve within 1-2 weeks). Combined with corticosteroids if no improvement within 5-7 days or biopsy-confirmed severe disease (prednisolone 0.5-1 mg/kg daily tapered over 4-6 weeks).<br><br>Long-term antibiotics (option B) are inappropriate; Aggressive hydration (option C) is supportive only; Immediate dialysis (option D) is reserved for refractory complications, none being AIN primary management like discontinuation of offending agent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In patients with ATN, why does the BUN to Creatinine ratio stay low?", "a": "The liver stops making urea", "b": "Damaged tubules cannot reabsorb urea", "c": "Urea is being overproduced", "d": "Creatinine is not filtered", "ans": "B", "e": "Damaged tubules cannot reabsorb urea in ATN producing low BUN/creatinine ratio; characteristic urea reabsorption is impaired in tubular injury with BUN/Cr ratio under 15.<br><br>Standard differential: pre-renal azotemia features BUN/Cr ratio over 20 (preserved urea reabsorption), ATN features ratio under 15. Combined with other diagnostic markers (FeNa, urine osmolality, urine sediment).<br><br>The liver stops making urea (option A) is incorrect (liver continues urea production); Creatinine is not filtered (option D) is wrong (creatinine is filtered), none being ATN BUN/Cr mechanism like damaged tubules cannot reabsorb urea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a known risk factor for Aminoglycoside-induced ATN?", "a": "Concomitant use of loop diuretics", "b": "Short duration of therapy", "c": "Alkaline urine", "d": "Young age", "ans": "A", "e": "Concomitant use of loop diuretics is known risk factor for aminoglycoside ATN; characteristic potentiation of nephrotoxicity through volume depletion and synergistic tubular toxicity.<br><br>Standard other aminoglycoside ATN risk factors: prolonged duration, divided dosing, concurrent nephrotoxins (vancomycin, NSAIDs, contrast), volume depletion, elderly, pre-existing CKD. Prevention: once-daily dosing, trough monitoring, dose adjustment.<br><br>Short duration of therapy (option B) reduces aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity; Alkaline urine (option C) reduces aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity; Young age (option D) reduces aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity, none being aminoglycoside ATN risk factor like concomitant loop diuretics.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with a history of NSAID use presents with AKI and proteinuria. Biopsy shows interstitial inflammation. Diagnosis?", "a": "Polycystic Kidney Disease", "b": "Pre-renal failure", "c": "Post-renal failure", "d": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis", "ans": "D", "e": "Acute interstitial nephritis fits NSAID user with AKI, proteinuria, and biopsy showing interstitial inflammation; characteristic NSAID AIN often presents without classic triad and with significant proteinuria.<br><br>Standard NSAID AIN features: often heavy proteinuria (can mimic nephrotic syndrome), older patients, longer drug exposure, typically lacks fever and rash, may have minimal change disease pattern on biopsy. Treatment: discontinue NSAID, corticosteroids for severe disease.<br><br>Polycystic Kidney Disease (option A) features cystic kidneys on imaging; Post-renal failure (option C) features hydronephrosis, none being NSAID-induced AKI with interstitial inflammation like acute interstitial nephritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which electrolyte abnormality is most likely to occur in the maintenance phase of ATN?", "a": "Hypernatremia", "b": "Hypomagnesemia", "c": "Hypermagnesemia", "d": "Hypophosphatemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Hypermagnesaemia is most likely electrolyte abnormality in maintenance phase of ATN; characteristic reduced renal clearance produces magnesium accumulation alongside other electrolyte disturbances.<br><br>Standard other maintenance phase abnormalities: hyperkalaemia (most dangerous), high anion gap metabolic acidosis, hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia, hyperuricaemia, fluid overload. Treatment: dialysis for refractory complications. Standard supportive care guides management. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hypernatremia (option A) is not principal maintenance ATN finding; Hypomagnesemia (option B) is opposite; Hypophosphatemia (option D) is opposite (hyperphosphataemia occurs), none being maintenance ATN electrolyte like hypermagnesaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Ethylene glycol poisoning causes ATN through the formation of:", "a": "Calcium oxalate crystals", "b": "Uric acid stones", "c": "Myoglobin casts", "d": "Heme pigments", "ans": "A", "e": "Calcium oxalate crystals form in ATN from ethylene glycol poisoning; characteristic metabolism produces glycolic and oxalic acids which combine with calcium forming nephrotoxic crystals.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: high anion gap metabolic acidosis with osmolar gap, urine showing calcium oxalate crystals (envelope-shaped), elevated ethylene glycol level. Treatment: fomepizole blocks alcohol dehydrogenase, ethanol as alternative, haemodialysis for severe poisoning.<br><br>Uric acid stones (option B) form in tumour lysis syndrome; Myoglobin casts (option C) form in rhabdomyolysis; Heme pigments (option D) form in haemolysis, none being ethylene glycol ATN crystals like calcium oxalate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "If a patient with AIN does not improve after stopping the suspected drug, what is the next step?", "a": "Perform a nephrectomy", "b": "Restart the drug", "c": "Give high-dose Aspirin", "d": "Consider a trial of Corticosteroids", "ans": "D", "e": "Trial of corticosteroids should be considered if AIN patient does not improve after stopping suspected drug; characteristic immunosuppressive effect on persistent interstitial inflammation may improve recovery.<br><br>Standard prednisolone 0.5-1 mg/kg daily tapered over 4-6 weeks. Combined with indications: no improvement within 5-7 days after drug discontinuation, biopsy-confirmed severe disease, persistent AIN.<br><br>Perform a nephrectomy (option A) is inappropriate; Restart the drug (option B) worsens AIN; Give high-dose Aspirin (option C) is harmful (NSAID can cause AIN), none being non-resolving AIN next step like consider trial of corticosteroids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Tumor Lysis Syndrome causes intra-renal AKI primarily due to:", "a": "Hyperuricemia", "b": "Hypercalcemia", "c": "Hypophosphatemia", "d": "Hypokalemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Hyperuricaemia causes intra-renal AKI in tumour lysis syndrome; characteristic rapid cell turnover during chemotherapy releases uric acid which precipitates in tubules.<br><br>Standard TLS features: hyperuricaemia, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia (reciprocal to phosphate). Prevention: aggressive hydration, allopurinol before chemotherapy, rasburicase for high-risk patients. Treatment: continued hydration, addressing electrolyte disturbances. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Hypercalcemia (option B) is opposite (hypocalcaemia occurs); Hypophosphatemia (option C) is opposite (hyperphosphataemia occurs); Hypokalemia (option D) is opposite of TLS findings, none being TLS AKI cause like hyperuricaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of ATN?", "a": "Muddy brown casts", "b": "Urine Sodium > 40 mEq/L", "c": "Low urine osmolality", "d": "FeNa < 1%", "ans": "D", "e": "FeNa under 1 percent is NOT characteristic of ATN; characteristic ATN features FeNa over 2 percent reflecting tubular dysfunction with impaired sodium reabsorption.<br><br>Standard typical ATN features: urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg, muddy brown granular casts, tubular epithelial cell casts. FeNa under 1 percent occurs in pre-renal azotemia (preserved sodium reabsorption).<br><br>Muddy brown casts (option A) ARE characteristic of ATN; Low urine osmolality (option C) IS characteristic of ATN, none being not characteristic of ATN like FeNa under 1 percent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "\"Bence-Jones\" proteins can cause intra-renal AKI in which condition?", "a": "Sarcoidosis", "b": "Amyloidosis", "c": "Multiple Myeloma", "d": "SLE", "ans": "C", "e": "Multiple myeloma causes Bence-Jones protein-induced intra-renal AKI; characteristic free light chains in urine produce cast nephropathy through direct tubular toxicity.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: serum and urine protein electrophoresis (monoclonal spike), free light chain assay, bone marrow biopsy. Treatment: addressing underlying myeloma (bortezomib-based chemotherapy), plasmapheresis for severe AKI, hydration.<br><br>Sarcoidosis (option A) causes granulomatous interstitial nephritis; Amyloidosis (option B) causes nephrotic syndrome but not Bence-Jones principally; SLE (option D) causes lupus nephritis (glomerular), none being Bence-Jones protein AKI condition like multiple myeloma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The primary prevention strategy for Contrast-Induced Nephropathy is:", "a": "Oral Vitamin C", "b": "Mannitol", "c": "Loop diuretics", "d": "Isotonic saline hydration", "ans": "D", "e": "Isotonic saline hydration is primary prevention strategy for contrast-induced nephropathy; characteristic volume expansion before and after contrast reduces nephrotoxicity.<br><br>Standard 0.9 percent saline 1 mL/kg/hour for 6-12 hours before and after contrast. Combined with minimising contrast volume, avoiding nephrotoxins, using iso-osmolar or low-osmolar contrast. N-acetylcysteine and sodium bicarbonate not proven beneficial.<br><br>Oral Vitamin C (option A) lacks proven benefit; Mannitol (option B) worsens volume depletion; Loop diuretics (option C) worsen volume depletion, none being CIN prevention like isotonic saline hydration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Ischemic ATN is most likely to occur following:", "a": "A single dose of Ibuprofen", "b": "Mild exercise", "c": "Prolonged hypotension or shock", "d": "Brief period of thirst", "ans": "C", "e": "Prolonged hypotension or shock causes ischaemic ATN; characteristic sustained renal hypoperfusion produces tubular cell death particularly in S3 proximal tubule and thick ascending limb.<br><br>Standard causes: septic shock, haemorrhagic shock, cardiogenic shock, prolonged surgery. Prevention: prompt fluid resuscitation, vasopressors, addressing underlying cause.<br><br>A single dose of Ibuprofen (option A) does not principally cause ATN; Mild exercise (option B) does not cause ATN; Brief period of thirst (option D) does not cause ATN, none being ischaemic ATN cause like prolonged hypotension or shock.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In AIN, the urine dipstick is often positive for:", "a": "Glucose", "b": "Protein (usually mild) and Blood", "c": "Nitrites", "d": "Bilirubin", "ans": "B", "e": "Protein (usually mild) and blood are often positive on urine dipstick in AIN; characteristic interstitial inflammation produces mild proteinuria and microscopic haematuria.<br><br>Standard other AIN findings: WBC casts, sterile pyuria, eosinophiluria (Hansel stain). Biopsy confirmation in unclear cases. NSAID AIN may produce heavy proteinuria (can mimic nephrotic syndrome). Treatment: discontinue offending drug, corticosteroids if non-resolving.<br><br>Glucose (option A) suggests diabetes mellitus; Nitrites (option C) suggest bacterial UTI; Bilirubin (option D) suggests liver disease, none being AIN dipstick findings like protein and blood.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which part of the nephron is most susceptible to ischemic injury in ATN?", "a": "Proximal tubule and Thick Ascending Limb", "b": "Bowman's capsule", "c": "Glomerulus", "d": "Collecting duct", "ans": "A", "e": "Proximal tubule and thick ascending limb are most susceptible to ischaemic injury in ATN; characteristic high metabolic demand and oxygen consumption in these segments produces vulnerability to hypoxia.<br><br>Standard S3 segment of proximal tubule (outer medulla) particularly vulnerable due to medullary hypoxia at baseline. Combined with thick ascending limb (medullary segment with high ATP demand for active sodium reabsorption).<br><br>Bowman's capsule (option B) is less ischaemia-susceptible; Collecting duct (option D) is less ischaemia-susceptible, none being ATN ischaemia-susceptible segment like proximal tubule and thick ascending limb.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hansel’s stain is specifically used to detect:", "a": "Fungi", "b": "Red blood cells", "c": "Urinary eosinophils", "d": "Bacteria", "ans": "C", "e": "Hansel stain is specifically used to detect urinary eosinophils; characteristic dye distinguishes eosinophils from other leukocytes in urine sediment.<br><br>Standard diagnostic utility: AIN, atheroembolic disease, prostatitis, UTI. Specific for AIN but not sensitive (only 30 percent of AIN patients have eosinophiluria). Combined with biopsy confirmation when clinical features unclear.<br><br>Fungi (option A) require KOH stain; Red blood cells (option B) are seen on routine microscopy; Bacteria (option D) require Gram stain, none being urinary eosinophil-detecting stain like Hansel stain detects urinary eosinophils.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Amotericin B causes AKI through:", "a": "Post-renal obstruction", "b": "Purely pre-renal mechanism", "c": "Glomerular scarring", "d": "Direct tubular toxicity and vasoconstriction", "ans": "D", "e": "Direct tubular toxicity and vasoconstriction cause AKI from amphotericin B; characteristic mechanism involves membrane pore formation and intrarenal vasoconstriction.<br><br>Standard prevention: hydration before infusion, sodium loading, slow infusion rates, monitoring electrolytes (hypokalaemia, hypomagnesaemia common). Combined with dose adjustment, using liposomal amphotericin B (less nephrotoxic), addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>Post-renal obstruction (option A) does not occur; Purely pre-renal mechanism (option B) is incorrect (intrarenal toxicity dominant); Glomerular scarring (option C) is not principal mechanism, none being amphotericin B AKI mechanism like direct tubular toxicity and vasoconstriction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis is considered what type of hypersensitivity reaction?", "a": "Type III", "b": "Type IV (and sometimes Type I)", "c": "Type I", "d": "Type II", "ans": "B", "e": "Type IV (and sometimes type I) hypersensitivity reaction underlies acute interstitial nephritis; characteristic T-cell mediated delayed hypersensitivity is dominant mechanism with occasional IgE involvement.<br><br>Standard histology showing interstitial infiltrate (lymphocytes, plasma cells, eosinophils), tubulitis, oedema, granulomas in some cases. Clinical features (delayed onset days to weeks after drug exposure, often without classic triad).<br><br>Type III (option A) is immune complex (lupus nephritis); Type I (option C) is immediate hypersensitivity (anaphylaxis); Type II (option D) is antibody-mediated cytotoxic (Goodpasture), none being AIN hypersensitivity type like type IV.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which finding distinguishes ATN from pre-renal azotemia?", "a": "Urine sediment with epithelial cell casts", "b": "History of heart failure", "c": "High BUN", "d": "Thirst", "ans": "A", "e": "Urine sediment with epithelial cell casts distinguishes ATN from pre-renal azotemia; characteristic tubular injury produces sloughing of epithelial cells forming casts.<br><br>Standard other ATN distinguishing features: muddy brown granular casts, FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg, BUN/Cr ratio under 15. Pre-renal features: bland sediment with hyaline casts, FeNa under 1 percent.<br><br>History of heart failure (option B) suggests pre-renal; Thirst (option D) suggests volume depletion (pre-renal), none being ATN vs pre-renal distinguishing finding like urine sediment with epithelial cell casts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Risk of ATN increases in the elderly primarily because of:", "a": "High protein intake", "b": "Reduced baseline GFR and comorbidities", "c": "Better tubular regeneration", "d": "Increased thirst", "ans": "B", "e": "Reduced baseline GFR and comorbidities increase ATN risk in elderly; characteristic age-related decline in renal reserve combined with multiple comorbidities (diabetes, hypertension, CHF) reduces tolerance to renal insult.<br><br>Standard age-adjusted dosing of nephrotoxic drugs, avoiding nephrotoxin combinations, careful hydration, addressing modifiable factors (volume status, BP control, glycaemic control). Combined with avoiding contrast when possible.<br><br>High protein intake (option A) is not principal elderly ATN risk factor; Increased thirst (option D) is not principal elderly ATN risk factor, none being elderly ATN risk factor like reduced baseline GFR and comorbidities.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of ATN is largely:", "a": "Curative with surgery", "b": "Ineffective; all patients need transplant", "c": "Based on high-dose immunosuppression", "d": "Supportive, including fluid and electrolyte management", "ans": "D", "e": "Supportive management with fluid and electrolyte management is mainstay of ATN treatment; characteristic absence of specific therapy means addressing complications and removing precipitants.<br><br>Standard addressing causes (volume resuscitation for ischaemic ATN, removal of nephrotoxins), addressing complications (hyperkalaemia, fluid overload, acidosis, uraemia), nutrition support. Dialysis indications: refractory hyperkalaemia, fluid overload (pulmonary oedema), severe acidosis.<br><br>Curative with surgery (option A) is inappropriate for ATN; Ineffective; all patients need transplant (option B) is incorrect; Based on high-dose immunosuppression (option C) is inappropriate, none being ATN management like supportive including fluid and electrolyte management.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is an \"Endogenous\" toxin that causes ATN?", "a": "Radiocontrast", "b": "Myoglobin", "c": "Cisplatin", "d": "Gentamicin", "ans": "B", "e": "Myoglobin is endogenous toxin causing ATN; characteristic release from damaged muscle in rhabdomyolysis produces direct tubular toxicity and obstruction.<br><br>Standard other endogenous nephrotoxins: haemoglobin (haemolysis), uric acid (TLS), free light chains (multiple myeloma), bilirubin (severe jaundice). Diagnosis: elevated CK (over 5000 IU/L), positive urine dipstick for blood without RBCs. Risk factor modification supports outcomes. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Radiocontrast (option A) is exogenous nephrotoxin; Cisplatin (option C) is exogenous nephrotoxin; Gentamicin (option D) is exogenous nephrotoxin, none being endogenous ATN toxin like myoglobin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "AIN can be caused by infections such as:", "a": "Tinea pedis", "b": "Superficial folliculitis", "c": "Legionella or CMV", "d": "Common cold", "ans": "C", "e": "Legionella or CMV infections can cause AIN; characteristic infection-associated AIN reflects bacterial and viral triggers of interstitial inflammation.<br><br>Standard other infectious AIN causes: Streptococcus, Staphylococcus, Mycoplasma, Brucella, Salmonella, Leptospira, Epstein-Barr virus, hantavirus, polyomavirus (BK virus in transplant). Treatment: addressing underlying infection, supportive care, corticosteroids in select cases.<br><br>Tinea pedis (option A) does not principally cause AIN; Superficial folliculitis (option B) does not principally cause AIN; Common cold (option D) does not principally cause AIN, none being AIN infectious causes like Legionella or CMV.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In ATN, the Urine/Plasma Creatinine ratio is typically:", "a": "> 20", "b": "< 20", "c": "100", "d": "> 40", "ans": "B", "e": "Under 20 is typical urine/plasma creatinine ratio in ATN; characteristic tubular dysfunction with reduced concentration of urine produces low U/P creatinine ratio.<br><br>Standard other ATN markers (FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg). Pre-renal azotemia features U/P creatinine ratio over 40 (preserved concentrating ability).<br><br>> 20 (option A) suggests pre-renal azotemia; 100 (option C) suggests pre-renal azotemia; > 40 (option D) suggests pre-renal azotemia, none being ATN U/P creatinine ratio like under 20.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The term \"Pauci-immune\" is usually associated with:", "a": "Small vessel vasculitis causing AKI", "b": "Post-renal obstruction", "c": "ATN", "d": "AIN", "ans": "A", "e": "Small vessel vasculitis causing AKI is associated with pauci-immune term; characteristic absence of significant immune complex deposition on immunofluorescence in ANCA-associated vasculitis.<br><br>Standard ANCA-associated vasculitides: granulomatosis with polyangiitis (c-ANCA/PR3), microscopic polyangiitis (p-ANCA/MPO), eosinophilic GPA (p-ANCA/MPO). Renal involvement (rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis with crescents, RBC casts). Treatment: corticosteroids plus cyclophosphamide or rituximab. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Post-renal obstruction (option B) is not pauci-immune; ATN (option C) is not pauci-immune; AIN (option D) is not pauci-immune, none being pauci-immune disease like small vessel vasculitis causing AKI.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which drug is classic for causing a non-oliguric form of ATN?", "a": "Penicillin", "b": "Aminoglycosides", "c": "Furosemide", "d": "Aspirin", "ans": "B", "e": "Aminoglycosides classically cause non-oliguric form of ATN; characteristic mild to moderate tubular damage preserves some urine output unlike ischaemic ATN.<br><br>Standard monitoring: serum creatinine, drug trough levels (gentamicin under 2 mg/L, vancomycin trough under 15-20 mg/L), urine output. Risk factors: prolonged duration, divided dosing, concurrent nephrotoxins, volume depletion, elderly. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Penicillin (option A) causes AIN; Furosemide (option C) causes pre-renal AKI in volume depletion; Aspirin (option D) causes papillary necrosis (chronic), none being non-oliguric ATN cause like aminoglycosides.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Fractional Excretion of Sodium (FeNa) is most accurate in which setting?", "a": "Chronic Kidney Disease", "b": "Patient on high-dose diuretics", "c": "Oliguric Acute Kidney Injury", "d": "Obstructive uropathy", "ans": "C", "e": "Oliguric acute kidney injury is setting where FeNa is most accurate; characteristic interpretation requires established AKI with oliguria and absence of diuretic use.<br><br>Standard limitations: diuretic use (false elevation), pre-existing CKD baseline FeNa elevation, contrast nephropathy often FeNa under 1 percent, glomerulonephritis often FeNa under 1 percent, HRS often FeNa under 1 percent. FeUrea as alternative in patients on diuretics.<br><br>Chronic Kidney Disease (option A) reduces FeNa accuracy; Obstructive uropathy (option D) reduces FeNa accuracy, none being FeNa accurate setting like oliguric acute kidney injury.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "\"Cast nephropathy\" in Multiple Myeloma is a form of:", "a": "Intrinsic AKI", "b": "Pre-renal AKI", "c": "Post-renal AKI", "d": "Functional AKI", "ans": "A", "e": "Intrinsic AKI describes cast nephropathy in multiple myeloma; characteristic light chain-induced tubular toxicity and obstruction classifies as intrinsic AKI.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: serum and urine protein electrophoresis (monoclonal spike), free light chain assay. Treatment: addressing underlying myeloma (bortezomib-based chemotherapy), plasmapheresis for severe AKI, hydration, avoiding nephrotoxins. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Pre-renal AKI (option B) features hypoperfusion (separate mechanism); Post-renal AKI (option C) features obstruction (separate mechanism); Functional AKI (option D) is not standard classification, none being myeloma cast nephropathy classification like intrinsic AKI.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Patients with ATN often require dialysis if they develop:", "a": "Low urine sodium", "b": "Refractory fluid overload or hyperkalemia", "c": "Mildly elevated BUN", "d": "Mild anemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Refractory fluid overload or hyperkalaemia indicates dialysis in ATN; characteristic life-threatening complications unresponsive to medical management require renal replacement therapy.<br><br>Standard other dialysis indications (AEIOU): Acidosis (pH under 7.2 refractory), Electrolytes (hyperkalaemia refractory), Intoxications (lithium, methanol, ethylene glycol, salicylates), Overload (pulmonary oedema refractory), Uraemia (encephalopathy, pericarditis, bleeding).<br><br>Low urine sodium (option A) is not principal dialysis indication; Mildly elevated BUN (option C) is not principal dialysis indication; Mild anemia (option D) is not principal dialysis indication, none being ATN dialysis indication like refractory fluid overload or hyperkalaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Methotrexate can cause AKI by:", "a": "Enhancing tubular reabsorption", "b": "Efferent vasodilation", "c": "Intratubular crystal precipitation", "d": "Causing BPH", "ans": "C", "e": "Intratubular crystal precipitation causes AKI from methotrexate; characteristic high-dose methotrexate precipitates as crystals in tubular lumen producing obstruction and toxicity.<br><br>Standard prevention: aggressive hydration, urine alkalinisation (sodium bicarbonate to urine pH over 7), monitoring methotrexate levels. Treatment: continued hydration, leucovorin rescue (folinic acid), glucarpidase for severe cases, haemodialysis for severe toxicity.<br><br>Enhancing tubular reabsorption (option A) is not methotrexate AKI mechanism; Efferent vasodilation (option B) is not methotrexate AKI mechanism; Causing BPH (option D) is not methotrexate AKI mechanism, none being methotrexate AKI mechanism like intratubular crystal precipitation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The presence of sterile pyuria (WBCs but no bacteria) should raise suspicion for:", "a": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis", "b": "Cystitis", "c": "Pre-renal failure", "d": "Renal artery stenosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Acute interstitial nephritis should be suspected with sterile pyuria; characteristic WBCs in urine without bacteria suggests interstitial inflammation rather than UTI.<br><br>Standard other sterile pyuria causes: renal TB (most classic), nephrolithiasis, interstitial nephritis (acute and chronic), polycystic kidney disease, partial UTI on antibiotics, urinary tract malignancy. Diagnosis: urine culture (negative), Hansel stain for eosinophils.<br><br>Cystitis (option B) features positive urine culture; Pre-renal failure (option C) features bland sediment; Renal artery stenosis (option D) features hypertension and bruit, none being sterile pyuria AKI cause like acute interstitial nephritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a feature of \"Type 1\" HRS compared to ATN?", "a": "Muddy brown casts", "b": "Improvement with fluids", "c": "Low Urine Sodium (< 10 mEq/L)", "d": "High FeNa", "ans": "C", "e": "Low urine sodium under 10 mEq/L is feature of type 1 hepatorenal syndrome compared to ATN; characteristic intense renal vasoconstriction with avid sodium reabsorption distinguishes HRS from ATN.<br><br>Standard HRS features: cirrhosis with portal hypertension, ascites, low urine sodium, FeNa under 1 percent, no improvement with volume challenge, no parenchymal renal disease. Type 1 HRS: rapid decline.<br><br>Muddy brown casts (option A) are ATN features (not HRS); High FeNa (option D) is ATN feature (not HRS), none being HRS feature like low urine sodium under 10 mEq/L.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "An increase in serum creatinine of 0.3 mg/dL within 48 hours meets the criteria for:", "a": "Stage 3 AKI", "b": "Stage 1 AKI", "c": "End-stage renal disease", "d": "Normal variation", "ans": "B", "e": "Stage 1 AKI is met by increase in serum creatinine of 0.3 mg/dL within 48 hours; characteristic KDIGO definition stratifies AKI severity for management and prognosis.<br><br>Standard KDIGO criteria stage 1: creatinine rise 0.3 mg/dL within 48 hours OR 1.5-1.9 times baseline within 7 days OR urine output under 0.5 mL/kg/hour for 6-12 hours. Stage 2: 2-2.9 times baseline.<br><br>Stage 3 AKI (option A) requires larger creatinine rise; Normal variation (option D) is incorrect (defined AKI), none being AKI 0.3 mg/dL rise like stage 1 AKI.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following describes the prognosis of ATN?", "a": "Always results in permanent dialysis", "b": "Requires kidney transplant in 90% of cases", "c": "Rapidly fatal within 24 hours", "d": "Usually reversible if the underlying cause is corrected", "ans": "D", "e": "Usually reversible if underlying cause corrected describes ATN prognosis; characteristic tubular regeneration enables recovery in most patients with appropriate management.<br><br>Standard prognosis: 60-70 percent recover renal function fully, 20-30 percent partial recovery (CKD), 5-10 percent require permanent dialysis. Mortality 30-60 percent in critically ill ICU patients (often from underlying illness rather than AKI).<br><br>Always results in permanent dialysis (option A) is incorrect; Rapidly fatal within 24 hours (option C) is incorrect, none being ATN prognosis like usually reversible if underlying cause corrected.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 45-year-old male is admitted with severe sepsis. Over 24 hours, his urine output drops to 100 mL, and his creatinine doubles. The urine sediment shows multiple \"muddy brown\" granular casts. What is the most likely Fractional Excretion of Sodium (FeNa)?", "a": "< 0.1%", "b": "> 2%", "c": "< 1%", "d": "< 0.5%", "ans": "B", "e": "Over 2 percent FeNa fits sepsis patient with muddy brown granular casts and doubling creatinine; this characteristic established ATN pattern reflects tubular dysfunction with impaired sodium reabsorption.<br><br>Standard other ATN markers: urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg, BUN/Cr ratio under 15, tubular epithelial cell casts. Treatment: supportive care, addressing sepsis (antibiotics, source control, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors), avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>< 0.1% (option A) is not principal ATN threshold; < 0.5% (option D) suggests pre-renal azotemia, none being established ATN FeNa like over 2 percent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following drugs is characteristically associated with Acute Interstitial Nephritis (AIN) but typically lacks the systemic symptoms of fever and rash?", "a": "NSAIDs", "b": "Phenytoin", "c": "Penicillin", "d": "Sulfonamides", "ans": "A", "e": "NSAIDs cause AIN characteristically without classic systemic symptoms of fever and rash; characteristic mechanism through cyclooxygenase inhibition produces AIN often with heavy proteinuria mimicking nephrotic syndrome.<br><br>Standard NSAID AIN features: longer drug exposure (months), older patients, often heavy proteinuria, may show minimal change disease on biopsy alongside interstitial inflammation. Treatment: discontinue NSAID, corticosteroids for severe or non-resolving disease.<br><br>Phenytoin (option B) produces classic AIN triad; Penicillin (option C) produces classic AIN triad; Sulfonamides (option D) produce classic AIN triad, none being AIN without systemic symptoms like NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Multiple Myeloma develops sudden AKI. Laboratory analysis reveals a \"Bence-Jones\" proteinuria. What is the primary mechanism of injury to the tubules?", "a": "Immune complex deposition in the basement membrane", "b": "Hypersensitivity reaction", "c": "Afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction", "d": "Direct tubular toxicity and cast obstruction", "ans": "D", "e": "Direct tubular toxicity and cast obstruction are primary mechanism of myeloma kidney injury; characteristic Bence-Jones proteins produce direct toxicity and cast formation with Tamm-Horsfall protein.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: serum and urine protein electrophoresis (monoclonal spike), free light chain assay, bone marrow biopsy. Treatment: addressing underlying myeloma (bortezomib-based chemotherapy), plasmapheresis for severe AKI, hydration, avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>Immune complex deposition in the basement membrane (option A) is glomerulonephritis mechanism; Afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction (option C) is pre-renal mechanism, none being myeloma kidney mechanism like direct tubular toxicity and cast obstruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In a patient with suspected drug-induced AIN, what is the most specific finding on Hansel's staining of the urine?", "a": "Hematuria", "b": "Eosinophiluria", "c": "Leukocyte casts", "d": "Isomorphous RBCs", "ans": "B", "e": "Eosinophiluria is most specific Hansel stain finding in suspected drug-induced AIN; characteristic urinary eosinophils support AIN diagnosis although not sensitive.<br><br>Standard limitations: eosinophiluria absent in 70 percent of AIN (especially NSAID AIN), present in other conditions (UTI, prostatitis, atheroembolic disease). Combined with other AIN findings: WBC casts, sterile pyuria, mild proteinuria, haematuria.<br><br>Hematuria (option A) is non-specific; Leukocyte casts (option C) are AIN finding but not Hansel-specific; Isomorphous RBCs (option D) suggest non-glomerular bleeding, none being Hansel stain specific finding like eosinophiluria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 70-year-old female undergoes a CT scan with high-osmolar contrast. Three days later, her creatinine rises. Which of the following is the most important risk factor for this occurrence?", "a": "Female gender", "b": "D) Low protein diet", "c": "Hypertension", "d": "Pre-existing Chronic Kidney Disease (CK", "ans": "D", "e": "Pre-existing chronic kidney disease is most important risk factor for contrast-induced nephropathy in 70-year-old female after CT contrast; characteristic baseline renal dysfunction reduces tolerance to contrast nephrotoxicity.<br><br>Standard other CIN risk factors: diabetes mellitus, volume depletion, advanced age (over 75), heart failure, high contrast volume, intra-arterial contrast, concurrent nephrotoxins. Prevention: hydration, minimising contrast, avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>Female gender (option A) is not principal CIN risk factor; Hypertension (option C) is not principal CIN risk factor, none being CIN principal risk factor like pre-existing chronic kidney disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient in the maintenance phase of ATN develops a serum potassium of 6.8 mEq/L with peaked T-waves on ECG. Which of the following is the most appropriate immediate step to stabilize the cardiac membrane?", "a": "Calcium Gluconate", "b": "Insulin and Glucose", "c": "Furosemide", "d": "Sodium Bicarbonate", "ans": "A", "e": "Calcium gluconate is most appropriate immediate step to stabilise cardiac membrane in ATN patient with potassium 6.8 and peaked T-waves; characteristic membrane stabilisation antagonises hyperkalaemia effects.<br><br>Standard 10 mL of 10 percent calcium gluconate IV over 2-3 minutes. Subsequent steps: insulin plus glucose shifts potassium intracellularly, salbutamol nebulisation, sodium bicarbonate if acidotic, kayexalate or dialysis.<br><br>Insulin and Glucose (option B) shifts potassium but does not stabilise membrane; Sodium Bicarbonate (option D) shifts potassium but slower onset, none being immediate cardiac membrane stabilisation like calcium gluconate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Allergic Interstitial Nephritis (AIN) histology classically demonstrates which of the following?", "a": "Thickening of the efferent arteriole", "b": "Necrosis of the proximal tubular basement membrane", "c": "Interstitial inflammatory infiltrate with eosinophils", "d": "Diffuse glomerular scarring", "ans": "C", "e": "Interstitial inflammatory infiltrate with eosinophils classically demonstrates AIN histology; characteristic findings on renal biopsy confirm diagnosis when clinical features unclear.<br><br>Standard biopsy features: lymphocytes (predominant), eosinophils, plasma cells in interstitium, tubulitis (lymphocytes invading tubules), interstitial oedema, granulomas in some cases (sarcoidosis, drug AIN, infection). Immunofluorescence usually negative.<br><br>Thickening of the efferent arteriole (option A) is non-specific; Necrosis of the proximal tubular basement membrane (option B) suggests ATN; Diffuse glomerular scarring (option D) suggests chronic glomerulonephritis, none being AIN histology like interstitial inflammatory infiltrate with eosinophils.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following lab findings is most consistent with the \"Maintenance Phase\" of ATN?", "a": "Urine Sodium > 40 mEq/L", "b": "Urine Osmolality > 500 mOsm/kg", "c": "BUN:Creatinine ratio > 20:1", "d": "Fractional Excretion of Urea < 35%", "ans": "A", "e": "Urine sodium over 40 mEq/L is most consistent with maintenance phase of ATN; characteristic tubular dysfunction produces impaired sodium reabsorption with high urinary sodium.<br><br>Standard other maintenance phase ATN findings: FeNa over 2 percent, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg (isosthenuria), muddy brown granular casts, tubular epithelial cell casts, oliguria, BUN/Cr ratio under 15.<br><br>Urine Osmolality > 500 mOsm/kg (option B) suggests pre-renal azotemia; Fractional Excretion of Urea < 35% (option D) suggests pre-renal, none being maintenance ATN finding like urine sodium over 40 mEq/L.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 35-year-old man is hospitalized with heatstroke and muscle tenderness. His urine is reddish-brown, and the dipstick is positive for blood, but microscopy shows 0 RBCs. What is the most likely diagnosis?", "a": "Post-renal obstruction", "b": "Acute Glomerulonephritis", "c": "Nephrolithiasis", "d": "Rhabdomyolysis-induced ATN", "ans": "D", "e": "Rhabdomyolysis-induced ATN fits 35-year-old with heatstroke, muscle tenderness, reddish-brown urine, positive dipstick for blood, no RBCs on microscopy; characteristic myoglobinuria produces positive dipstick without RBCs.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: elevated CK (over 5000 IU/L), hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia (early), hyperuricaemia. Treatment: aggressive isotonic saline (target urine output 200-300 mL/hour), urine alkalinisation (sodium bicarbonate to urine pH over 6.5), addressing hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Post-renal obstruction (option A) features hydronephrosis; Acute Glomerulonephritis (option B) features RBCs and RBC casts; Nephrolithiasis (option C) features colicky pain and visible RBCs, none being heat stroke with myoglobinuria like rhabdomyolysis-induced ATN.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the standard management for a patient with drug-induced AIN who does not show improvement within a week of stopping the offending drug?", "a": "High-dose Loop Diuretics", "b": "Trial of Corticosteroids (e.g., Prednisone)", "c": "Plasmapheresis", "d": "Broad-spectrum antibiotics", "ans": "B", "e": "Trial of corticosteroids (prednisone) is standard management for AIN patient not improving within a week of stopping offending drug; characteristic anti-inflammatory effect on persistent interstitial inflammation.<br><br>Standard prednisolone 0.5-1 mg/kg daily tapered over 4-6 weeks. Combined with monitoring response (creatinine, urine sediment), addressing complications of steroid therapy (hyperglycaemia, infection risk, mood changes).<br><br>High-dose Loop Diuretics (option A) lack benefit; Plasmapheresis (option C) is not first-line; Broad-spectrum antibiotics (option D) are inappropriate without infection, none being non-resolving AIN management like trial of corticosteroids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a \"non-oliguric\" cause of ATN?", "a": "Ischemia from shock", "b": "Hemorrhage", "c": "Severe dehydration", "d": "Aminoglycoside (e.g., Gentamicin) toxicity", "ans": "D", "e": "Aminoglycoside toxicity (e.g. gentamicin) is characteristically non-oliguric cause of ATN; characteristic mild tubular damage preserves urine output despite reduced glomerular filtration.<br><br>Standard gentamicin nephrotoxicity (30-80 percent on prolonged therapy). Risk factors: prolonged duration (over 7-10 days), divided dosing, concurrent nephrotoxins, volume depletion, elderly. Prevention: once-daily dosing, trough monitoring (target under 2 mg/L), dose adjustment.<br><br>Ischemia from shock (option A) causes oliguric ischaemic ATN; Hemorrhage (option B) causes oliguric ischaemic ATN; Severe dehydration (option C) causes oliguric ischaemic ATN, none being non-oliguric ATN cause like aminoglycoside toxicity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with leukemia is started on chemotherapy and develops AKI. Labs show hyperuricemia, hyperkalemia, and hyperphosphatemia. What is this syndrome called?", "a": "Goodpasture Syndrome", "b": "Hepatorenal Syndrome", "c": "Tumor Lysis Syndrome", "d": "Nephrotic Syndrome", "ans": "C", "e": "Tumour lysis syndrome describes leukaemia patient post-chemotherapy with hyperuricaemia, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia; characteristic massive cell lysis releases intracellular contents producing electrolyte abnormalities and AKI.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: rapid cell turnover, characteristic electrolyte pattern (Hyper-K, Hyper-P, Hyper-uric, Hypo-Ca reciprocally), often with AKI (uric acid crystal nephropathy). Prevention: aggressive hydration, allopurinol, rasburicase for high-risk patients.<br><br>Goodpasture Syndrome (option A) features anti-GBM antibodies; Hepatorenal Syndrome (option B) is liver disease-related; Nephrotic Syndrome (option D) features proteinuria and oedema, none being chemotherapy electrolyte syndrome like tumour lysis syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In Acute Tubular Necrosis, the urine specific gravity is typically \"fixed\" at:", "a": "1.030", "b": "1.010", "c": "1.025", "d": "1.001", "ans": "B", "e": "1.010 is typical urine specific gravity in ATN; characteristic isosthenuria reflects loss of tubular concentrating ability with fixed specific gravity around plasma value.<br><br>Standard other ATN markers: FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg, muddy brown granular casts, tubular epithelial cell casts. Pre-renal azotemia features concentrated urine over 1.020.<br><br>1.030 (option A) suggests highly concentrated urine (pre-renal); 1.001 (option D) suggests dilute urine (diabetes insipidus, water loading), none being ATN fixed specific gravity like 1.010.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which segment of the renal tubule is most susceptible to ischemic damage?", "a": "Distal convoluted tubule", "b": "Descending loop of Henle", "c": "Collecting duct", "d": "Straight part of the proximal tubule (S3 segment)", "ans": "D", "e": "Straight part of proximal tubule (S3 segment) is most susceptible to ischaemic damage; characteristic high metabolic demand and outer medullary location with marginal oxygenation produces vulnerability.<br><br>Standard thick ascending limb of Henle loop (medullary segment with high ATP demand for active sodium reabsorption) similarly vulnerable. Mechanism: outer medulla has baseline marginal oxygenation due to countercurrent exchange and high oxygen consumption for active transport.<br><br>Distal convoluted tubule (option A) is less ischaemia-susceptible; Collecting duct (option C) is less ischaemia-susceptible, none being most ischaemia-susceptible segment like S3 of proximal tubule.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 55-year-old patient on Omeprazole (PPI) for 3 months presents with fatigue and a serum creatinine of 2.8 mg/dL. Urine shows WBC casts but no bacteria. What should you suspect?", "a": "Drug-induced AIN", "b": "ATN from PPI toxicity", "c": "Pre-renal Azotemia", "d": "Renal Papillary Necrosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Drug-induced AIN should be suspected in 55-year-old on omeprazole 3 months with fatigue, creatinine 2.8, WBC casts without bacteria; characteristic PPI-induced AIN often presents subacutely without classic triad.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: clinical suspicion (PPI exposure), urinalysis (WBC casts, sterile pyuria), Hansel stain for eosinophils, biopsy confirmation if unclear. Treatment: discontinue PPI, corticosteroids if no improvement within 5-7 days.<br><br>ATN from PPI toxicity (option B) is not PPI mechanism; Renal Papillary Necrosis (option D) features sloughed papillae, none being PPI-induced creatinine rise with WBC casts like drug-induced AIN.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with ATN transitions into the \"Recovery/Diuretic Phase.\" What is the primary risk during this stage?", "a": "Hypermagnesemia", "b": "Acute hypertension", "c": "Pulmonary edema", "d": "Hypokalemia and dehydration", "ans": "D", "e": "Hypokalaemia and dehydration are primary risks during recovery/diuretic phase of ATN; characteristic restoration of glomerular function before tubular function produces inappropriate diuresis with electrolyte losses.<br><br>Standard diuretic phase management: careful fluid replacement (matching losses), potassium and magnesium replacement, monitoring electrolytes daily, gradual return to normal function over 2-3 weeks.<br><br>Hypermagnesemia (option A) is maintenance phase finding; Acute hypertension (option B) is uncommon; Pulmonary edema (option C) is maintenance phase from fluid overload, none being diuretic ATN phase risk like hypokalaemia and dehydration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is an endogenous toxin that causes ATN?", "a": "Hemoglobin (from hemolysis)", "b": "Cisplatin", "c": "Amphotericin B", "d": "Radiocontrast dye", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemoglobin from haemolysis is endogenous toxin causing ATN; characteristic free haemoglobin released from intravascular haemolysis produces direct tubular toxicity similar to myoglobin.<br><br>Standard causes of intravascular haemolysis: transfusion reactions (ABO incompatibility), thrombotic microangiopathies (TTP, HUS, DIC), G6PD deficiency, paroxysmal nocturnal haemoglobinuria, falciparum malaria (blackwater fever). Treatment: aggressive hydration, urine alkalinisation. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Cisplatin (option B) is exogenous nephrotoxin; Amphotericin B (option C) is exogenous nephrotoxin; Radiocontrast dye (option D) is exogenous nephrotoxin, none being endogenous ATN toxin like haemoglobin from haemolysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which lab result is most helpful in differentiating AIN from Acute Pyelonephritis?", "a": "Elevated Serum Creatinine", "b": "Absence of bacteria on Gram stain and culture", "c": "Presence of WBCs in urine", "d": "Positive Nitrites on dipstick", "ans": "B", "e": "Absence of bacteria on Gram stain and culture differentiates AIN from acute pyelonephritis; characteristic sterile pyuria in AIN reflects interstitial inflammation rather than bacterial infection.<br><br>Standard other distinguishing features: AIN typically has drug exposure, sometimes systemic symptoms (fever, rash, eosinophilia), bilateral involvement; acute pyelonephritis features flank pain, fever, costovertebral angle tenderness, positive urine culture.<br><br>Elevated Serum Creatinine (option A) is seen in both; Positive Nitrites on dipstick (option D) suggests pyelonephritis, none being AIN vs pyelonephritis distinguishing finding like absence of bacteria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient develops AKI after starting Acyclovir. The urine shows needle-shaped crystals. What is the management?", "a": "Emergency Dialysis", "b": "Renal artery stenting", "c": "Corticosteroids", "d": "Aggressive IV hydration", "ans": "D", "e": "Aggressive IV hydration is management for AKI after acyclovir with needle-shaped crystals; characteristic acyclovir crystal nephropathy responds to hydration which dilutes crystals and prevents intratubular obstruction.<br><br>Standard prevention: adequate hydration before acyclovir infusion, slow IV infusion rate (over at least 1 hour), dose adjustment for renal function, avoiding rapid bolus. Treatment: aggressive isotonic saline, discontinuing acyclovir if severe.<br><br>Emergency Dialysis (option A) is reserved for severe AKI; Corticosteroids (option C) are for AIN not crystalluria, none being acyclovir crystal nephropathy management like aggressive IV hydration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In the \"Initiation Phase\" of ischemic ATN, what is the goal of management?", "a": "Restoration of renal perfusion (BP and Volume)", "b": "Restrict all fluid intake", "c": "Immediate Renal Biopsy", "d": "Start maintenance Dialysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Restoration of renal perfusion through BP and volume is goal of management in initiation phase of ischaemic ATN; characteristic early intervention may prevent progression to established ATN.<br><br>Standard fluid resuscitation (isotonic saline targeted to volume status), vasopressors if needed (norepinephrine first-line for septic shock), addressing underlying cause (sepsis, haemorrhage, cardiogenic shock). Combined with avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>Restrict all fluid intake (option B) worsens hypovolaemia; Start maintenance Dialysis (option D) is for established failure, none being initiation phase ATN goal like restoration of renal perfusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Ethylene glycol poisoning leads to ATN through the formation of:", "a": "Uric acid crystals", "b": "Cystine stones", "c": "Calcium oxalate crystals", "d": "Myoglobin casts", "ans": "C", "e": "Calcium oxalate crystals form in ethylene glycol poisoning leading to ATN; characteristic metabolism produces glycolic and oxalic acids which precipitate with calcium in tubules.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: high anion gap metabolic acidosis with osmolar gap, urine showing envelope-shaped or needle-shaped crystals, elevated serum ethylene glycol level. Treatment: fomepizole blocks alcohol dehydrogenase, ethanol as alternative, haemodialysis for severe poisoning.<br><br>Uric acid crystals (option A) form in TLS; Cystine stones (option B) form in cystinuria; Myoglobin casts (option D) form in rhabdomyolysis, none being ethylene glycol ATN crystals like calcium oxalate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is true about the use of Fenoldopam or Dopamine in preventing ATN?", "a": "They have no proven benefit in preventing or treating ATN", "b": "They are superior to IV hydration", "c": "They are recommended as first-line therapy", "d": "They are highly effective in clinical trials", "ans": "A", "e": "Fenoldopam and dopamine have no proven benefit in preventing or treating ATN; characteristic absence of mortality or renal recovery benefit in clinical trials.<br><br>Standard proven preventive strategies: avoiding nephrotoxins, maintaining renal perfusion (volume status, BP), avoiding hypotension, dose adjustment for renal function. Proven treatment of established ATN being supportive (fluid/electrolyte management, dialysis for complications).<br><br>They are superior to IV hydration (option B) is incorrect; They are highly effective in clinical trials (option D) is incorrect, none being fenoldopam/dopamine in ATN like no proven benefit.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 40-year-old female presents with fever, a new rash on her trunk, and joint pain after taking Penicillin. Creatinine is 2.4. What is the most likely diagnosis?", "a": "Systemic Lupus Erythematosus", "b": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis", "c": "Post-renal obstruction", "d": "Acute Tubular Necrosis", "ans": "B", "e": "Acute interstitial nephritis fits 40-year-old female with fever, new rash on trunk, joint pain after penicillin, creatinine 2.4; characteristic classic AIN triad with antibiotic exposure.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: clinical features (classic triad in only 10-30 percent), urinalysis (WBC casts, sterile pyuria, mild proteinuria, haematuria), urinary eosinophils on Hansel stain, biopsy confirmation if unclear. Treatment: discontinue penicillin, corticosteroids if non-resolving.<br><br>Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (option A) features autoantibodies; Acute Tubular Necrosis (option D) features muddy brown casts, none being post-penicillin fever, rash, and creatinine rise like acute interstitial nephritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In a patient with established ATN, why does the BUN/Creatinine ratio remain < 15:1?", "a": "Damaged tubules cannot reabsorb urea from the filtrate", "b": "The liver stops producing urea", "c": "BUN is filtered more than creatinine", "d": "Creatinine is being reabsorbed", "ans": "A", "e": "Damaged tubules cannot reabsorb urea from filtrate in ATN producing BUN/Cr ratio under 15; characteristic urea reabsorption is impaired in tubular injury distinguishing from pre-renal pattern.<br><br>Standard differential: pre-renal azotemia features BUN/Cr ratio over 20 (preserved urea reabsorption with intact tubules), ATN features ratio under 15 (impaired tubular urea reabsorption). Combined with other ATN markers.<br><br>The liver stops producing urea (option B) is incorrect; Creatinine is being reabsorbed (option D) is incorrect, none being ATN BUN/Cr mechanism like damaged tubules cannot reabsorb urea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a classic non-infectious/non-drug cause of AIN?", "a": "Osteoporosis", "b": "Diabetes", "c": "Sarcoidosis", "d": "Obesity", "ans": "C", "e": "Sarcoidosis is classic non-infectious/non-drug cause of AIN; characteristic granulomatous interstitial nephritis with non-caseating granulomas reflects systemic sarcoidosis.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: biopsy showing non-caseating granulomas in interstitium, evidence of systemic sarcoidosis (hilar lymphadenopathy, elevated ACE, hypercalcaemia from extrarenal vitamin D activation). Treatment: corticosteroids (prednisolone 20-40 mg daily), tapering over months. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Osteoporosis (option A) is not principal AIN cause; Diabetes (option B) is not principal AIN cause; Obesity (option D) is not principal AIN cause, none being non-infectious/non-drug AIN cause like sarcoidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with severe hypotension for 6 hours develops AKI. Which finding on urine microscopy most strongly confirms Intrinsic ATN?", "a": "Hyaline casts", "b": "Renal tubular epithelial cell casts", "c": "Broad waxy casts", "d": "White blood cell casts", "ans": "B", "e": "Renal tubular epithelial cell casts most strongly confirm intrinsic ATN in patient with severe hypotension; characteristic sloughed tubular cells in casts pathognomonic for ATN.<br><br>Standard other ATN urine findings: muddy brown granular casts, free tubular epithelial cells, FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, urine osmolality under 350 mOsm/kg.<br><br>Hyaline casts (option A) are non-specific (dehydration, exercise); Broad waxy casts (option C) suggest CKD with stasis; White blood cell casts (option D) suggest AIN or pyelonephritis, none being ATN confirmatory finding like renal tubular epithelial cell casts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which metabolic abnormality is least likely to be seen in the maintenance phase of ATN?", "a": "Hyperkalemia", "b": "Metabolic acidosis", "c": "Metabolic alkalosis", "d": "Hyperphosphatemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Metabolic alkalosis is least likely metabolic abnormality in maintenance phase of ATN; characteristic ATN produces metabolic acidosis (high anion gap), not alkalosis.<br><br>Standard typical maintenance ATN abnormalities: high anion gap metabolic acidosis (retention of organic acids, sulphate, phosphate), hyperkalaemia (impaired excretion plus acidosis-induced cellular shift), hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia (reciprocal to phosphate), hyperuricaemia.<br><br>Hyperkalemia (option A) is typical maintenance ATN feature; Metabolic acidosis (option B) is typical maintenance ATN feature; Hyperphosphatemia (option D) is typical maintenance ATN feature, none being least likely maintenance ATN finding like metabolic alkalosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the \"Gold Standard\" for diagnosing the cause of intra-renal azotemia when the cause is unclear?", "a": "MRI with Contrast", "b": "CT Abdomen", "c": "Cystoscopy", "d": "Renal Biopsy", "ans": "D", "e": "Renal biopsy is gold standard for diagnosing intra-renal azotemia cause when unclear; characteristic histological evaluation differentiates ATN, AIN, glomerulonephritis, vasculitis, thrombotic microangiopathy.<br><br>Standard indications: unclear diagnosis after non-invasive workup, no improvement after empirical management, considering immunosuppressive therapy, abnormal urinalysis (haematuria, proteinuria, RBC casts). Risks: bleeding (1-2 percent), AV fistula, infection.<br><br>MRI with Contrast (option A) is contraindicated in AKI (NSF risk); CT Abdomen (option B) is for structural pathology; Cystoscopy (option C) is for urological evaluation, none being intrarenal AKI gold standard like renal biopsy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Risk of aminoglycoside-induced ATN is increased by:", "a": "Once-daily dosing", "b": "Concurrent use of Loop Diuretics (Furosemide)", "c": "High carbohydrate diet", "d": "Alkalinization of urine", "ans": "B", "e": "Concurrent use of loop diuretics (furosemide) increases aminoglycoside-induced ATN risk; characteristic synergistic nephrotoxicity through volume depletion and direct tubular toxicity.<br><br>Standard other aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity risk factors: prolonged duration (over 7-10 days), divided dosing (vs once-daily), concurrent nephrotoxins (vancomycin, NSAIDs, contrast), volume depletion, elderly, pre-existing CKD. Prevention: once-daily dosing, trough monitoring.<br><br>Once-daily dosing (option A) reduces aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity; High carbohydrate diet (option C) is unrelated; Alkalinization of urine (option D) reduces aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity, none being aminoglycoside ATN risk factor like concurrent loop diuretics.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with AIN shows \"Sterile Pyuria.\" This means:", "a": "Urine contains WBCs but no bacteria on culture", "b": "Urine contains only bacteria", "c": "Urine is perfectly clear", "d": "Urine contains no WBCs", "ans": "A", "e": "Urine contains WBCs but no bacteria on culture defines AIN sterile pyuria; characteristic interstitial inflammation produces WBCs without bacterial infection.<br><br>Standard other sterile pyuria causes: renal tuberculosis (classic), chronic interstitial nephritis, partial UTI on antibiotics, nephrolithiasis, polycystic kidney disease, urinary tract malignancy. Diagnosis: urine culture (negative), Hansel stain for eosinophils in AIN.<br><br>Urine contains only bacteria (option B) is incorrect; Urine is perfectly clear (option C) is incorrect; Urine contains no WBCs (option D) is incorrect, none being sterile pyuria definition like urine contains WBCs but no bacteria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In contrast-induced nephropathy (CIN), when does the creatinine usually peak after the procedure?", "a": "24 hours", "b": "1 month", "c": "3 to 5 days", "d": "2 hours", "ans": "C", "e": "3 to 5 days is when creatinine peaks in contrast-induced nephropathy; characteristic delayed peak after contrast exposure with return to baseline over 7-14 days in most cases.<br><br>Standard CIN definition: creatinine rise 0.5 mg/dL or 25 percent within 48-72 hours of contrast. Risk factors: pre-existing CKD, diabetes mellitus, volume depletion, advanced age, high contrast volume.<br><br>24 hours (option A) is too early for CIN peak; 1 month (option B) is too late; 2 hours (option D) is impossibly fast, none being CIN creatinine peak time like 3 to 5 days.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following electrolyte disturbances is common in Rhabdomyolysis-induced AKI?", "a": "Hypokalemia", "b": "Hypocalcemia (early phase)", "c": "Hyponatremia", "d": "Hypercalcemia (early phase)", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypocalcaemia in early phase characterises rhabdomyolysis-induced AKI; characteristic calcium deposition in damaged muscle alongside hyperphosphataemia produces hypocalcaemia.<br><br>Standard other rhabdomyolysis electrolyte abnormalities: hyperkalaemia (cell lysis), hyperphosphataemia (cell lysis), hyperuricaemia (cell lysis), hypercalcaemia later (during recovery, calcium release from damaged muscle). Treatment: aggressive hydration, addressing hyperkalaemia. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Hypokalemia (option A) is opposite (hyperkalaemia occurs); Hyponatremia (option C) is not principal rhabdomyolysis finding; Hypercalcemia (early phase) (option D) is late phase finding, none being rhabdomyolysis early electrolyte finding like hypocalcaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with ATN is found to have \"Isosthenuria.\" This means:", "a": "Urine osmolality is equal to plasma osmolality (~300 mOsm/kg)", "b": "Urine contains high levels of sodium", "c": "Urine contains no protein", "d": "Urine is very concentrated", "ans": "A", "e": "Urine osmolality equal to plasma osmolality describes isosthenuria in ATN; characteristic fixed urine osmolality around 300 mOsm/kg reflects loss of tubular concentrating ability.<br><br>Standard other ATN markers: FeNa over 2 percent, urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, muddy brown granular casts, tubular epithelial cell casts, fixed specific gravity around 1.010. Combined with addressing causes (ischaemic, nephrotoxic).<br><br>Urine contains high levels of sodium (option B) is separate finding; Urine is very concentrated (option D) suggests pre-renal, none being isosthenuria definition like urine osmolality equal to plasma osmolality.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which finding is unlikely in a patient with AIN?", "a": "Hematuria", "b": "Mild proteinuria", "c": "WBC casts", "d": "FeNa < 1%", "ans": "D", "e": "FeNa under 1 percent is unlikely in AIN; characteristic interstitial inflammation does not principally affect tubular sodium handling like ATN does.<br><br>Standard typical AIN findings: WBC casts (often), eosinophiluria (specific but not sensitive), mild proteinuria, haematuria, FeNa typically over 1 percent (varies), urine sodium often elevated. Combined with ruling out other causes.<br><br>Hematuria (option A) is characteristic AIN finding; Mild proteinuria (option B) is characteristic AIN finding; WBC casts (option C) is characteristic AIN finding, none being unlikely AIN finding like FeNa under 1 percent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of pigment-induced ATN (Myoglobinuria) should include:", "a": "High protein diet", "b": "Aggressive Isotonic Saline and possible urine alkalinization", "c": "Fluid restriction", "d": "Immediate dialysis regardless of electrolytes", "ans": "B", "e": "Aggressive isotonic saline and possible urine alkalinisation manage pigment-induced ATN (myoglobinuria); characteristic dilution of pigments and prevention of crystal precipitation reduces tubular toxicity.<br><br>Standard target urine output 200-300 mL/hour. Urine alkalinisation (sodium bicarbonate to urine pH over 6.5) prevents myoglobin crystallisation in acidic tubular environment. Combined with addressing hyperkalaemia (often life-threatening), monitoring CK trend, avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>High protein diet (option A) lacks benefit; Fluid restriction (option C) worsens nephrotoxicity; Immediate dialysis regardless of electrolytes (option D) is over-treatment, none being myoglobinuria management like aggressive isotonic saline and urine alkalinisation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following drugs can cause AIN?", "a": "Rifampin", "b": "Allopurinol", "c": "Ciprofloxacin", "d": "All of the above", "ans": "D", "e": "All of the above drugs (allopurinol, rifampin, ciprofloxacin) can cause AIN; characteristic broad range of medications can trigger drug-induced AIN.<br><br>Standard classic AIN drug causes: antibiotics (penicillins, cephalosporins, sulfonamides, rifampin, ciprofloxacin, vancomycin), NSAIDs (typically without classic triad), PPIs (omeprazole, esomeprazole), allopurinol, diuretics (furosemide, thiazides), phenytoin.<br><br>Rifampin (option A) is correct individually but list is comprehensive; Allopurinol (option B) is correct individually but list is comprehensive; Ciprofloxacin (option C) is correct individually but list is comprehensive, none being comprehensive AIN drug list like all of the above.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which phase of ATN is defined by the gradual rise in urine output as the GFR begins to normalize?", "a": "Maintenance", "b": "Initiation", "c": "Diuretic Phase", "d": "Pre-renal Phase", "ans": "C", "e": "Diuretic phase is ATN phase defined by gradual rise in urine output as GFR normalises; characteristic recovery phase features inappropriate diuresis with electrolyte losses.<br><br>Standard ATN phases: initiation (hours-days of declining function), maintenance (1-2 weeks oliguria), diuretic/recovery (days-weeks with gradual normalisation). Combined with careful fluid and electrolyte management during diuretic phase (risk of hypokalaemia, hypomagnesaemia, dehydration).<br><br>Maintenance (option A) features oliguria; Initiation (option B) features early declining function; Pre-renal Phase (option D) is not ATN phase, none being recovery ATN phase like diuretic phase.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient has a FeNa of 2.5% and a Urine Osmolality of 280 mOsm/kg. This supports:", "a": "Pre-renal azotemia", "b": "Post-renal obstruction", "c": "Dehydration", "d": "Intra-renal (Intrinsic) injury", "ans": "D", "e": "Intra-renal (intrinsic) injury is supported by FeNa 2.5 percent and urine osmolality 280 mOsm/kg; characteristic combination of elevated FeNa with isosthenuria indicates tubular dysfunction.<br><br>Standard other intrinsic AKI markers: urine sodium over 40 mEq/L, muddy brown casts (ATN), WBC casts (AIN), RBC casts (glomerulonephritis), BUN/Cr ratio under 15. Combined with specific diagnosis (ATN, AIN, GN, vasculitis).<br><br>Pre-renal azotemia (option A) features FeNa under 1 percent and high urine osmolality; Post-renal obstruction (option B) features hydronephrosis; Dehydration (option C) features pre-renal pattern, none being elevated FeNa with isosthenuria like intra-renal injury.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In the management of ATN, when is dialysis generally indicated?", "a": "When refractory hyperkalemia or pulmonary edema develops", "b": "As soon as the creatinine reaches 2.0", "c": "Only after 1 month of no improvement", "d": "Every patient with muddy brown casts", "ans": "A", "e": "When refractory hyperkalaemia or pulmonary oedema develops indicates dialysis in ATN; characteristic life-threatening complications unresponsive to medical management require renal replacement therapy.<br><br>Standard other dialysis indications (AEIOU mnemonic): Acidosis (pH under 7.2 refractory), Electrolytes (hyperkalaemia refractory), Intoxications (lithium, methanol, ethylene glycol, salicylates), Overload (pulmonary oedema refractory), Uraemia (encephalopathy, pericarditis, bleeding).<br><br>As soon as the creatinine reaches 2.0 (option B) is not indication; Every patient with muddy brown casts (option D) is inappropriate, none being ATN dialysis indication like refractory hyperkalaemia or pulmonary oedema.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which imaging modality is avoided in AKI to prevent further intra-renal damage?", "a": "Doppler of renal artery", "b": "CXR", "c": "Ultrasound", "d": "CT with IV contrast", "ans": "D", "e": "CT with IV contrast is avoided in AKI to prevent further intra-renal damage; characteristic contrast nephropathy in patients with pre-existing renal dysfunction worsens outcomes.<br><br>Standard alternatives: non-contrast CT, ultrasound (excludes hydronephrosis), MRI with non-gadolinium sequences (gadolinium contraindicated in severe AKI/CKD due to NSF risk). If contrast essential: hydration before/after, minimise contrast volume.<br><br>Doppler of renal artery (option A) uses no contrast; CXR (option B) lacks renal imaging concern; Ultrasound (option C) uses no contrast, none being AKI contraindicated imaging like CT with IV contrast.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient on Vancomycin develops AKI. You suspect ATN. What should you check first?", "a": "Kidney size", "b": "Renal Biopsy", "c": "Drug trough levels and dose adjustment", "d": "Blood sugar", "ans": "C", "e": "Drug trough levels and dose adjustment are first check in vancomycin-induced suspected ATN; characteristic vancomycin nephrotoxicity is dose-dependent with elevated troughs (over 15-20 mg/L) increasing risk.<br><br>Standard vancomycin nephrotoxicity risk factors: high troughs, prolonged duration (over 7 days), concurrent nephrotoxins (aminoglycosides, NSAIDs, contrast, piperacillin-tazobactam), elderly, ICU patients. Monitoring: trough levels, daily creatinine.<br><br>Kidney size (option A) is for chronicity on imaging; Renal Biopsy (option B) is for unclear cases; Blood sugar (option D) is for diabetes, none being vancomycin AKI first check like drug trough levels and dose adjustment.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Pathophysiology of AIN involves:", "a": "Type IV (Delayed) Hypersensitivity reaction", "b": "Physical obstruction of the ureters", "c": "Direct chemical burning of the tubules", "d": "Type II Hypersensitivity", "ans": "A", "e": "Type IV (delayed) hypersensitivity reaction underlies AIN pathophysiology; characteristic T-cell mediated delayed hypersensitivity is dominant mechanism.<br><br>Standard histology showing interstitial infiltrate (lymphocytes predominant, plasma cells, eosinophils), tubulitis (T-cells invading tubules), oedema, granulomas in some cases. Clinical features (delayed onset days to weeks after drug exposure).<br><br>Physical obstruction of the ureters (option B) is post-renal mechanism; Direct chemical burning of the tubules (option C) is not principal mechanism; Type II Hypersensitivity (option D) is antibody-mediated cytotoxic, none being AIN mechanism like type IV delayed hypersensitivity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a symptom of Uremia?", "a": "Clear vision", "b": "Bradycardia", "c": "Increased appetite", "d": "Encephalopathy and Asterixis", "ans": "D", "e": "Encephalopathy and asterixis are symptoms of uraemia; characteristic accumulation of nitrogenous waste products with retention of toxins produces neurological dysfunction.<br><br>Standard other uraemic symptoms: anorexia, nausea, vomiting, pruritus, pericarditis, platelet dysfunction (bleeding), seizures, coma in severe cases. Treatment: dialysis for severe uraemia, addressing underlying cause, supportive care. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Clear vision (option A) is not uraemia symptom; Bradycardia (option B) is not principal uraemia symptom; Increased appetite (option C) is opposite (anorexia occurs), none being uraemia symptoms like encephalopathy and asterixis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In AKI, the \"R\" in RIFLE criteria stands for:", "a": "Renal", "b": "Recovery", "c": "Risk", "d": "Rare", "ans": "C", "e": "Risk represents 'R' in RIFLE criteria for AKI; characteristic staging system uses Risk, Injury, Failure, Loss, End-stage renal disease for AKI severity classification.<br><br>Standard RIFLE criteria: Risk (Cr 1.5x or GFR drop 25 percent, UO under 0.5 mL/kg/hour for 6 hours), Injury (Cr 2x or GFR drop 50 percent), Failure (Cr 3x or UO under 0.3 mL/kg/hour for 24 hours), Loss (over 4 weeks), ESRD (over 3 months).<br><br>Renal (option A) is not RIFLE meaning; Rare (option D) is not RIFLE meaning, none being RIFLE 'R' meaning like risk.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "\"Sterile Pyuria\" is most commonly associated with which of the following?", "a": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis or Tuberculosis", "b": "Pre-renal failure", "c": "Bladder stones", "d": "Acute Tubular Necrosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Acute interstitial nephritis or tuberculosis are most commonly associated with sterile pyuria; characteristic WBCs without bacteria suggest interstitial inflammation or renal TB.<br><br>Standard other sterile pyuria causes: chronic interstitial nephritis, partial UTI on antibiotics, nephrolithiasis, polycystic kidney disease, urinary tract malignancy. Diagnosis: urine culture (negative), Hansel stain for eosinophils in AIN, mycobacterial culture for TB.<br><br>Pre-renal failure (option B) features bland sediment; Bladder stones (option C) feature haematuria; Acute Tubular Necrosis (option D) features muddy brown casts, none being sterile pyuria associated condition like acute interstitial nephritis or tuberculosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with ATN has a BUN of 120 mg/dL and is confused. What is the most likely cause of confusion?", "a": "Hypoglycemia", "b": "Uremic encephalopathy", "c": "Hyponatremia", "d": "Hypotension", "ans": "B", "e": "Uraemic encephalopathy is most likely cause of confusion in ATN patient with BUN 120; characteristic neurological complication of accumulated nitrogenous waste produces altered consciousness.<br><br>Standard other uraemic encephalopathy features: asterixis, myoclonus, seizures, coma in severe cases. Treatment: dialysis for severe uraemia with neurological complications, addressing underlying cause, supportive care. Risk factor modification supports outcomes. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Hypoglycemia (option A) requires glucose measurement; Hyponatremia (option C) requires sodium measurement; Hypotension (option D) features haemodynamic instability, none being elevated BUN with confusion like uraemic encephalopathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following drugs causes ATN through direct tubular toxicity?", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Prednisone", "c": "Cisplatin", "d": "Penicillin", "ans": "C", "e": "Cisplatin causes ATN through direct tubular toxicity; characteristic platinum-DNA adduct formation in proximal tubular cells produces dose-dependent nephrotoxicity.<br><br>Standard prevention: aggressive hydration before and after infusion, mannitol diuresis, amifostine (cytoprotective), monitoring renal function, addressing electrolyte disturbances (hypomagnesaemia common). Treatment: supportive care, dose modification or substitution with carboplatin (less nephrotoxic). Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Heparin (option A) is not principal nephrotoxin; Prednisone (option B) lacks principal nephrotoxicity; Penicillin (option D) causes AIN, none being direct tubular toxicity ATN cause like cisplatin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The urine sediment in AIN typically shows:", "a": "No cells", "b": "WBCs, WBC casts, and sometimes RBCs", "c": "Muddy brown casts", "d": "Malteses cross crystals", "ans": "B", "e": "WBCs, WBC casts, and sometimes RBCs typically appear in AIN urine sediment; characteristic interstitial inflammation produces these urinary findings.<br><br>Standard other AIN findings: sterile pyuria, mild proteinuria, haematuria, urinary eosinophils (Hansel stain - specific but not sensitive). Combined with biopsy showing interstitial inflammatory infiltrate with eosinophils. Treatment: discontinue offending drug.<br><br>No cells (option A) is incorrect; Muddy brown casts (option C) suggest ATN; Malteses cross crystals (option D) suggest cholesterol crystals or fatty casts, none being AIN urine sediment like WBCs, WBC casts, and sometimes RBCs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of sepsis-induced ATN includes:", "a": "Fluid restriction", "b": "Immediate nephrectomy", "c": "Early antibiotics and hemodynamic support", "d": "Steroids", "ans": "C", "e": "Early antibiotics and haemodynamic support manage sepsis-induced ATN; characteristic prompt sepsis management addresses underlying cause of ATN.<br><br>Standard sepsis management: early broad-spectrum antibiotics (within 1 hour), source control, aggressive fluid resuscitation (30 mL/kg crystalloid), vasopressors (norepinephrine first-line), monitoring response. Combined with addressing ATN supportively. Standard supportive care guides management. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Fluid restriction (option A) worsens sepsis; Immediate nephrectomy (option B) is inappropriate; Steroids (option D) are controversial in sepsis, none being sepsis-induced ATN management like early antibiotics and haemodynamic support.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following helps differentiate AKI from Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD)?", "a": "FeNa", "b": "Serum Creatinine level", "c": "Potassium level", "d": "Kidney size on Ultrasound (Normal/Large in AKI)", "ans": "D", "e": "Kidney size on ultrasound (normal/large in AKI) differentiates AKI from CKD; characteristic normal or large kidneys in AKI versus small atrophic kidneys in CKD reflects acute vs chronic disease.<br><br>Standard other CKD chronicity features: anaemia (erythropoietin deficiency), hyperphosphataemia with secondary hyperparathyroidism, hypocalcaemia, renal osteodystrophy, broad waxy casts, hyperechogenicity on ultrasound. Combined with addressing through clinical history.<br><br>FeNa (option A) is similar in AKI and CKD; Potassium level (option C) is similar in AKI and CKD, none being AKI vs CKD distinguishing feature like kidney size on ultrasound.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 24-year-old male presents with hematuria and periorbital edema. Urinalysis reveals red blood cell (RBC) casts and 1.5g of protein per day. What is the most likely primary clinical syndrome?", "a": "Isolated Asymptomatic Proteinuria", "b": "Acute Interstitial Nephritis", "c": "Nephritic Syndrome", "d": "Nephrotic Syndrome", "ans": "C", "e": "Nephritic syndrome fits 24-year-old male with haematuria and periorbital oedema; characteristic glomerular inflammation produces haematuria, hypertension, mild proteinuria, oedema, and oliguria.<br><br>Standard nephritic features: RBC casts, dysmorphic RBCs, mild-moderate proteinuria (under 3.5 g/day), hypertension, azotemia. Common causes: post-streptococcal GN, IgA nephropathy, lupus nephritis, ANCA-associated vasculitis, anti-GBM disease.<br><br>Isolated Asymptomatic Proteinuria (option A) is not the correct choice; Acute Interstitial Nephritis (option B) is not the correct choice; Nephrotic Syndrome (option D) features proteinuria over 3.5 g/day, hypoalbuminaemia, oedema, hyperlipidaemia, none being haematuria with periorbital oedema like nephritic syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is the hallmark laboratory finding that defines Nephrotic Syndrome?", "a": "Hematuria with dysmorphic RBCs", "b": "Hypokalemia", "c": "Presence of WBC casts", "d": "Proteinuria > 3.5 g/day", "ans": "D", "e": "Proteinuria over 3.5 g/day is hallmark laboratory finding of nephrotic syndrome; characteristic glomerular basement membrane damage produces massive protein loss.<br><br>Standard nephrotic tetrad: heavy proteinuria (over 3.5 g/day), hypoalbuminaemia (under 3.0 g/dL), oedema, hyperlipidaemia. Lipiduria with oval fat bodies (Maltese cross under polarised light). Complications: thromboembolism, infections, AKI.<br><br>Hematuria with dysmorphic RBCs (option A) is not the correct choice; Hypokalemia (option B) is not the correct choice; Presence of WBC casts (option C) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic syndrome hallmark like proteinuria over 3.5 g/day.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 45-year-old female with Nephrotic syndrome is at significantly increased risk for which of the following complications due to the loss of Antithrombin III?", "a": "Venous Thromboembolism (e.g., Renal Vein Thrombosis)", "b": "Bleeding diathesis", "c": "Hypothyroidism", "d": "Iron deficiency anemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Venous thromboembolism (e.g. renal vein thrombosis) is significant risk in 45-year-old female with nephrotic syndrome; characteristic urinary loss of antithrombin III and other anticoagulants produces hypercoagulable state.<br><br>Standard hypercoagulability mechanisms: loss of antithrombin III, protein C, protein S in urine; increased hepatic synthesis of fibrinogen and clotting factors; platelet hyperaggregability. Highest risk in membranous nephropathy.<br><br>Bleeding diathesis (option B) is not the correct choice; Iron deficiency anemia (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic syndrome significant risk like venous thromboembolism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Rapidly Progressive Glomerulonephritis (RPGN) is clinically defined by:", "a": "Isolated hypertension without renal impairment", "b": "Development of nephrotic range proteinuria over years", "c": "Resolving hematuria after antibiotic therapy", "d": "A 50% decline in GFR within weeks to months and \"crescents\" on biopsy", "ans": "D", "e": "50 percent decline in GFR within weeks to months and crescents on biopsy define rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis; characteristic crescentic glomerulonephritis with extracapillary proliferation reflects severe glomerular injury.<br><br>Standard three types: anti-GBM disease (type I), immune complex, pauci-immune (type III - ANCA-associated vasculitis). Diagnosis: biopsy with crescents, immunofluorescence pattern.<br><br>Isolated hypertension without renal impairment (option A) is not the correct choice; Resolving hematuria after antibiotic therapy (option C) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN clinical definition like 50 percent GFR decline with crescents.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with hemoptysis and acute renal failure has linear IgG deposits along the glomerular basement membrane on immunofluorescence. What is the diagnosis?", "a": "IgA Nephropathy", "b": "Goodpasture Syndrome (Anti-GBM disease)", "c": "Wegener’s Granulomatosis", "d": "Post-streptococcal GN", "ans": "B", "e": "Goodpasture syndrome (anti-GBM disease) fits patient with haemoptysis and acute renal failure with linear IgG deposits; characteristic antibodies against alpha-3 chain of type IV collagen affect both glomerular and alveolar basement membranes.<br><br>Standard diagnosis: anti-GBM antibody titre, biopsy showing linear IgG along GBM (immunofluorescence), crescentic glomerulonephritis. Treatment: plasmapheresis (removes antibodies), corticosteroids, cyclophosphamide.<br><br>IgA Nephropathy (option A) features mesangial IgA deposits; Wegener’s Granulomatosis (option C) is not the correct choice; Post-streptococcal GN (option D) is not the correct choice, none being haemoptysis with linear IgG deposits like Goodpasture syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In Nephrotic syndrome, hyperlipidemia occurs primarily because:", "a": "Low oncotic pressure stimulates the liver to increase lipoprotein synthesis", "b": "The patient usually consumes more fat", "c": "The kidney cannot filter cholesterol", "d": "There is a deficiency in insulin production", "ans": "A", "e": "Low oncotic pressure stimulates liver to increase lipoprotein synthesis in nephrotic hyperlipidaemia; characteristic compensatory hepatic response to hypoalbuminaemia increases LDL, VLDL, and total cholesterol.<br><br>Standard mechanism: hypoalbuminaemia from urinary protein loss reduces plasma oncotic pressure, stimulating hepatic lipoprotein synthesis. Combined with reduced lipoprotein lipase activity.<br><br>The patient usually consumes more fat (option B) is not the correct choice; There is a deficiency in insulin production (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic hyperlipidaemia mechanism like low oncotic pressure stimulating hepatic lipoprotein synthesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 10-year-old boy presents with \"cola-colored\" urine 2 days after the onset of a sore throat. His serum C3 is normal. What is the most likely diagnosis?", "a": "Minimal Change Disease", "b": "IgA Nephropathy (Berger’s Disease)", "c": "Alport Syndrome", "d": "Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis (PSGN)", "ans": "B", "e": "IgA nephropathy (Berger's disease) fits 10-year-old boy with cola-coloured urine 2 days after upper respiratory infection; characteristic synpharyngitic haematuria (within 1-3 days of URTI) distinguishes from post-strep GN (10-21 days).<br><br>Standard diagnosis: biopsy showing mesangial IgA deposits on immunofluorescence, mesangial proliferation on light microscopy. Most common primary glomerulonephritis worldwide.<br><br>Minimal Change Disease (option A) features nephrotic syndrome not haematuria; Alport Syndrome (option C) features progressive deafness and ocular abnormalities; Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis (PSGN) (option D) is not the correct choice, none being synpharyngitic haematuria like IgA nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a classic extra-renal manifestation of Alport Syndrome?", "a": "Sensorineural deafness", "b": "Pulmonary fibrosis", "c": "Malar rash", "d": "Arthritis", "ans": "A", "e": "Sensorineural deafness is classic extra-renal manifestation of Alport syndrome; characteristic type IV collagen defect affects basement membranes in cochlea producing high-frequency hearing loss.<br><br>Standard other Alport features: anterior lenticonus, perimacular flecks, posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy. Renal disease: haematuria, progressive renal failure. Diagnosis: family history, biopsy showing characteristic GBM lamellation (basket-weave pattern).<br><br>Pulmonary fibrosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Malar rash (option C) is not the correct choice; Arthritis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Alport syndrome extra-renal manifestation like sensorineural deafness.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the characteristic biopsy finding in a patient with Alport Syndrome under electron microscopy?", "a": "Subepithelial \"humps\"", "b": "\"Tram-track\" appearance of the basement membrane", "c": "Irregular thinning and thickening of the GBM (Splitting/Lamellation)", "d": "Effacement of podocyte foot processes", "ans": "C", "e": "Irregular thinning and thickening of GBM (splitting/lamellation) is characteristic Alport biopsy finding; characteristic basket-weave appearance on electron microscopy reflects type IV collagen defect.<br><br>Standard EM findings: alternating thin and thick segments of GBM, splitting of lamina densa (basket-weave pattern). Pathogenesis: mutations in COL4A3, COL4A4, COL4A5 genes encoding type IV collagen alpha chains.<br><br>Subepithelial \"humps\" (option A) is not the correct choice; Effacement of podocyte foot processes (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Alport biopsy finding like irregular thinning and thickening of GBM.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which type of RPGN is characterized by \"Pauci-immune\" staining (negative immunofluorescence) and positive c-ANCA?", "a": "Lupus Nephritis", "b": "Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (Wegener’s)", "c": "Goodpasture Syndrome", "d": "IgA Nephropathy", "ans": "B", "e": "Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener's) characterises pauci-immune RPGN; characteristic c-ANCA (PR3-ANCA) positivity with granulomatous inflammation distinguishes from other ANCA-associated vasculitides.<br><br>Standard features: upper respiratory tract involvement (sinusitis, saddle-nose deformity, nasal septal perforation), lower respiratory tract (pulmonary nodules, alveolar haemorrhage), renal involvement (RPGN with crescents). Treatment: corticosteroids plus cyclophosphamide or rituximab.<br><br>Lupus Nephritis (option A) is not the correct choice; Goodpasture Syndrome (option C) is anti-GBM disease (type I RPGN); IgA Nephropathy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being pauci-immune RPGN with c-ANCA like granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Nephrotic syndrome presents with generalized swelling (Anasarca). This is primarily due to:", "a": "Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure", "b": "Excessive intake of water", "c": "Decreased plasma oncotic pressure", "d": "High blood pressure", "ans": "C", "e": "Decreased plasma oncotic pressure causes generalised oedema in nephrotic syndrome; characteristic urinary albumin loss reduces plasma oncotic pressure allowing fluid shift to interstitium.<br><br>Standard mechanism: hypoalbuminaemia from urinary protein loss reduces plasma oncotic pressure; combined with secondary hyperaldosteronism from intravascular volume depletion causing sodium and water retention. Result: pitting oedema, periorbital oedema, ascites, pleural effusions.<br><br>Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure (option A) is not the correct choice; High blood pressure (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic oedema mechanism like decreased plasma oncotic pressure.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is considered the most common cause of Nephrotic Syndrome in children?", "a": "Minimal Change Disease", "b": "Diabetic Nephropathy", "c": "Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis (FSGS)", "d": "Membranous Nephropathy", "ans": "A", "e": "Minimal change disease is most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children; characteristic foot process effacement on electron microscopy with normal light microscopy and immunofluorescence.<br><br>Standard features: heavy proteinuria (selective for albumin), good response to corticosteroids (80-90 percent remission), often follows URTI or immunisation. EM: foot process effacement.<br><br>Diabetic Nephropathy (option B) is most common in adults with diabetes; Membranous Nephropathy (option D) is most common in adults (idiopathic or secondary), none being most common paediatric nephrotic syndrome like minimal change disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of IgA Nephropathy with persistent proteinuria (> 1g/day) and normal GFR primarily involves:", "a": "High-dose Cyclophosphamide", "b": "ACE Inhibitors or ARBs", "c": "Immediate Dialysis", "d": "Plasmapheresis", "ans": "B", "e": "ACE inhibitors or ARBs are management for IgA nephropathy with persistent proteinuria; characteristic reduction in intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria slows progression.<br><br>Standard goal: reduce proteinuria below 1 g/day, BP target under 130/80 mmHg. Combined with addressing risk factors (smoking cessation, lipid management).<br><br>High-dose Cyclophosphamide (option A) is not the correct choice; Immediate Dialysis (option C) is not the correct choice; Plasmapheresis (option D) is not first-line IgA nephropathy treatment, none being IgA nephropathy with proteinuria management like ACE inhibitors or ARBs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In Nephritic syndrome, the presence of \"Dysmorphic RBCs\" in the urine suggests:", "a": "Ureteral stone", "b": "Bladder cancer", "c": "Urinary tract infection", "d": "Glomerular origin of bleeding", "ans": "D", "e": "Glomerular origin of bleeding is suggested by dysmorphic RBCs in nephritic syndrome; characteristic deformation of RBCs as they pass through damaged glomerular basement membrane.<br><br>Standard urinary findings in nephritic syndrome: RBC casts, dysmorphic RBCs (acanthocytes), mild-moderate proteinuria, hypertension, azotemia. Common nephritic causes: post-strep GN, IgA nephropathy, lupus nephritis, ANCA-associated vasculitis, anti-GBM disease.<br><br>Ureteral stone (option A) is not the correct choice; Bladder cancer (option B) is not the correct choice; Urinary tract infection (option C) is not the correct choice, none being dysmorphic RBC indication like glomerular origin of bleeding.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a \"Confirmatory Test\" for suspected Goodpasture Syndrome?", "a": "24-hour urine for calcium", "b": "ANCA levels", "c": "Anti-GBM antibody titer and Renal Biopsy", "d": "Serum ASO titer", "ans": "C", "e": "Anti-GBM antibody titre and renal biopsy are confirmatory tests for suspected Goodpasture syndrome; characteristic positive anti-GBM antibodies with biopsy showing linear IgG along GBM confirm diagnosis.<br><br>Standard biopsy: crescentic glomerulonephritis with linear IgG immunofluorescence along GBM. Combined with anti-GBM antibody assay (ELISA).<br><br>24-hour urine for calcium (option A) is not the correct choice; ANCA levels (option B) is not the correct choice; Serum ASO titer (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Goodpasture confirmatory tests like anti-GBM antibody titre and renal biopsy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 30-year-old African American male with HIV and obesity presents with Nephrotic syndrome. What is the most likely histological diagnosis?", "a": "Minimal Change Disease", "b": "Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis (FSGS)", "c": "Alport Syndrome", "d": "Membranous Nephropathy", "ans": "B", "e": "Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) fits 30-year-old African American male with HIV and obesity presenting with nephrotic syndrome; characteristic predilection for African Americans with secondary causes (HIV, obesity, heroin).<br><br>Standard biopsy: focal (some glomeruli) and segmental (part of glomerulus) sclerosis and hyalinosis, often with podocyte injury. Combined with addressing secondary causes (HIV - HIVAN with collapsing variant, obesity, heroin).<br><br>Minimal Change Disease (option A) is more common in children; Membranous Nephropathy (option D) features spike and dome appearance, none being HIV-associated nephrotic syndrome in African American like focal segmental glomerulosclerosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which laboratory finding helps distinguish Nephritic from Nephrotic syndrome?", "a": "Presence of RBC casts in Nephritic", "b": "Elevated creatinine", "c": "Low serum albumin in Nephritic", "d": "High cholesterol in Nephritic", "ans": "A", "e": "Presence of RBC casts in nephritic distinguishes from nephrotic syndrome; characteristic glomerular inflammation in nephritic produces dysmorphic RBCs and RBC casts.<br><br>Standard nephritic features: RBC casts, dysmorphic RBCs, mild-moderate proteinuria (under 3.5 g/day), hypertension, azotemia. Nephrotic features: heavy proteinuria (over 3.5 g/day), hypoalbuminaemia, oedema, hyperlipidaemia, oval fat bodies (Maltese cross under polarised light).<br><br>Elevated creatinine (option B) is not the correct choice; High cholesterol in Nephritic (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephritic vs nephrotic distinguishing finding like presence of RBC casts in nephritic.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Alport Syndrome is most commonly inherited as:", "a": "Mitochondrial inheritance", "b": "Autosomal Dominant", "c": "Autosomal Recessive only", "d": "X-linked Dominant", "ans": "D", "e": "X-linked dominant is most common Alport syndrome inheritance pattern; characteristic COL4A5 gene mutation (80-85 percent of cases) on X chromosome produces type IV collagen alpha-5 chain defect.<br><br>Standard inheritance patterns: X-linked dominant (most common, 80-85 percent, COL4A5), autosomal recessive (15 percent, COL4A3 or COL4A4), autosomal dominant (rare, COL4A3 or COL4A4). Males with X-linked typically more severely affected than females.<br><br>Mitochondrial inheritance (option A) is not the correct choice; Autosomal Recessive only (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Alport inheritance like X-linked dominant.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the mainstay of treatment for Rapidly Progressive Glomerulonephritis (RPGN)?", "a": "Low-salt diet only", "b": "Pulse Methylprednisolone and Cyclophosphamide", "c": "Antibiotics for 4 weeks", "d": "Observation only", "ans": "B", "e": "Pulse methylprednisolone and cyclophosphamide are mainstay of treatment for rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis; characteristic immunosuppression targets autoimmune mechanisms in crescentic glomerulonephritis.<br><br>Standard induction: pulse methylprednisolone (500-1000 mg IV daily for 3 days), then prednisolone 1 mg/kg daily; cyclophosphamide (oral or IV pulse). Combined with plasmapheresis for anti-GBM disease, ANCA vasculitis with severe renal involvement.<br><br>Low-salt diet only (option A) is not the correct choice; Observation only (option D) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN treatment like pulse methylprednisolone and cyclophosphamide.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a classic cause of secondary Nephrotic Syndrome?", "a": "Alport Syndrome", "b": "Thin Basement Membrane Disease", "c": "Diabetes Mellitus", "d": "IgA Nephropathy", "ans": "C", "e": "Diabetes mellitus is classic cause of secondary nephrotic syndrome; characteristic hyperglycaemia-induced glomerular damage with mesangial expansion and Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodular glomerulosclerosis.<br><br>Standard diabetic nephropathy stages: hyperfiltration, microalbuminuria (30-300 mg/day), macroalbuminuria (over 300 mg/day), nephrotic-range proteinuria, declining GFR. Treatment: glycaemic control, ACE inhibitors/ARBs, BP control, SGLT-2 inhibitors.<br><br>Alport Syndrome (option A) is not the correct choice; Thin Basement Membrane Disease (option B) is not the correct choice; IgA Nephropathy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being secondary nephrotic cause like diabetes mellitus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Nephrotic Syndrome has \"Oval Fat Bodies\" in the urine. These are:", "a": "Stones made of fat", "b": "Contamination from skin", "c": "Clumps of white blood cells", "d": "Degenerated tubular epithelial cells filled with lipids", "ans": "D", "e": "Degenerated tubular epithelial cells filled with lipids describe oval fat bodies in nephrotic syndrome; characteristic appearance reflects heavy proteinuria with lipiduria.<br><br>Standard appearance under polarised light: Maltese cross pattern (cholesterol esters birefringent). Combined with other nephrotic features: heavy proteinuria (over 3.5 g/day), hypoalbuminaemia (under 3.0 g/dL), oedema, hyperlipidaemia.<br><br>Stones made of fat (option A) is not the correct choice; Clumps of white blood cells (option C) is not the correct choice, none being oval fat bodies like degenerated tubular epithelial cells filled with lipids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In IgA Nephropathy, the immunofluorescence on renal biopsy shows:", "a": "No staining (Pauci-immune)", "b": "Granular IgA deposits in the mesangium", "c": "Linear IgG", "d": "Granular IgG and C3 in subepithelial space", "ans": "B", "e": "Granular IgA deposits in the mesangium characterise IgA nephropathy on immunofluorescence; characteristic mesangial IgA deposition (often with C3) confirms diagnosis.<br><br>Standard biopsy: mesangial proliferation on light microscopy, granular IgA deposits in mesangium on immunofluorescence (often with C3), electron-dense deposits in mesangium on EM. Most common primary glomerulonephritis worldwide.<br><br>No staining (Pauci-immune) (option A) is not the correct choice; Granular IgG and C3 in subepithelial space (option D) is not the correct choice, none being IgA nephropathy immunofluorescence like granular IgA deposits in mesangium.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which ocular finding is associated with Alport Syndrome?", "a": "Anterior lenticonus", "b": "Blue sclera", "c": "Cataracts", "d": "Glaucoma", "ans": "A", "e": "Anterior lenticonus is ocular finding associated with Alport syndrome; characteristic cone-shaped deformation of anterior lens capsule reflects type IV collagen defect in lens basement membrane.<br><br>Standard other ocular Alport findings: perimacular flecks (whitish dots near macula), posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy. Combined with sensorineural deafness, progressive renal failure with haematuria.<br><br>Blue sclera (option B) is not the correct choice; Cataracts (option C) is not the correct choice; Glaucoma (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Alport ocular finding like anterior lenticonus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is an emergency treatment used specifically for the Anti-GBM type of RPGN to remove circulating antibodies?", "a": "Hemodialysis", "b": "Blood transfusion", "c": "Plasmapheresis", "d": "Peritoneal dialysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Plasmapheresis is emergency treatment specifically used for Goodpasture syndrome; characteristic removal of anti-GBM antibodies from circulation reduces immunological damage to kidneys and lungs.<br><br>Standard urgent plasmapheresis (daily or alternate-day exchanges) combined with corticosteroids (pulse methylprednisolone then prednisolone) and cyclophosphamide. Combined with addressing pulmonary haemorrhage (oxygen, mechanical ventilation if needed). Continue plasmapheresis until anti-GBM antibodies undetectable.<br><br>Hemodialysis (option A) is not the correct choice; Blood transfusion (option B) is not the correct choice; Peritoneal dialysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Goodpasture emergency treatment like plasmapheresis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Why are patients with Nephrotic Syndrome prone to infections?", "a": "They lose Immunoglobulins and Complement factors in the urine", "b": "They have too many white blood cells", "c": "They lose glucose in the urine", "d": "They are always on antibiotics", "ans": "A", "e": "Patients with nephrotic syndrome lose immunoglobulins and complement factors in urine making them prone to infections; characteristic urinary loss of IgG and factor B reduces immunity against encapsulated organisms.<br><br>Standard high infection risk pathogens: Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, gram-negative organisms. Vaccination and prompt antibiotics for suspected infections.<br><br>They have too many white blood cells (option B) is not the correct choice; They are always on antibiotics (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic infection susceptibility like loss of immunoglobulins and complement factors in urine.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with recurrent hematuria coincident with upper respiratory infections (\"Synpharyngitic hematuria\") most likely has:", "a": "Renal Cell Carcinoma", "b": "IgA Nephropathy", "c": "Post-streptococcal GN", "d": "Minimal Change Disease", "ans": "B", "e": "IgA nephropathy fits patient with recurrent haematuria coincident with upper respiratory infections; characteristic synpharyngitic haematuria (within 1-3 days of URTI) distinguishes from post-strep GN (10-21 days latent period).<br><br>Standard diagnosis: biopsy showing mesangial IgA deposits on immunofluorescence, mesangial proliferation on light microscopy. Most common primary glomerulonephritis worldwide.<br><br>Renal Cell Carcinoma (option A) is not the correct choice; Post-streptococcal GN (option C) is not the correct choice; Minimal Change Disease (option D) is not the correct choice, none being recurrent synpharyngitic haematuria like IgA nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The \"crescents\" seen in RPGN biopsy are composed of:", "a": "Only Red blood cells", "b": "Fungal hyphae", "c": "Only collagen", "d": "Prophylating parietal epithelial cells and macrophages", "ans": "D", "e": "Proliferating parietal epithelial cells and macrophages compose crescents in RPGN biopsy; characteristic extracapillary proliferation in Bowman's space reflects severe glomerular injury.<br><br>Standard crescent formation mechanism: GBM disruption allows fibrin and inflammatory mediators into Bowman's space, stimulating proliferation of parietal epithelial cells and influx of macrophages. Combined with fibrin deposition, T cells.<br><br>Only Red blood cells (option A) is not the correct choice; Only collagen (option C) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN crescent composition like proliferating parietal epithelial cells and macrophages.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a primary management goal in Nephrotic Syndrome?", "a": "Stopping all exercise", "b": "Increasing salt intake", "c": "Edema control with diuretics and ACE-i for proteinuria", "d": "High protein diet (>4g/kg)", "ans": "C", "e": "Oedema control with diuretics and ACE inhibitors for proteinuria is primary management goal in nephrotic syndrome; characteristic supportive measures address principal manifestations.<br><br>Standard management: loop diuretics for oedema, ACE inhibitors/ARBs for proteinuria reduction, statins for hyperlipidaemia, addressing through dietary sodium restriction. Combined with treating underlying cause (corticosteroids for primary glomerular diseases).<br><br>Stopping all exercise (option A) is not the correct choice; High protein diet (>4g/kg) (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic primary management like oedema control with diuretics and ACE inhibitors for proteinuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 60-year-old male with a history of malignancy presents with Nephrotic syndrome. Which diagnosis is most likely?", "a": "Minimal Change Disease", "b": "Alport Syndrome", "c": "IgA Nephropathy", "d": "Membranous Nephropathy", "ans": "D", "e": "Membranous nephropathy fits 60-year-old male with history of malignancy presenting with nephrotic syndrome; characteristic association with solid tumours (lung, colon, breast, prostate) makes it most common adult nephrotic syndrome with secondary causes.<br><br>Standard biopsy: thickened GBM, subepithelial immune deposits with spike-and-dome on silver stain, granular IgG/C3 on immunofluorescence. Treatment: anti-PLA2R antibody, addressing secondary causes, immunosuppression.<br><br>Minimal Change Disease (option A) is most common paediatric nephrotic syndrome; IgA Nephropathy (option C) features nephritic features not nephrotic syndrome, none being malignancy-associated adult nephrotic syndrome like membranous nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which finding on urine dipstick is most characteristic of Nephritic syndrome?", "a": "4+ Glucose", "b": "Moderate blood and 1+ to 2+ Protein", "c": "Nitrites and Leukocyte Esterase", "d": "Bilirubin", "ans": "B", "e": "Moderate blood and 1+ to 2+ protein on urine dipstick characterise acute glomerulonephritis; characteristic glomerular inflammation produces haematuria with mild-moderate proteinuria.<br><br>Standard nephritic syndrome features: RBC casts, dysmorphic RBCs, haematuria (often macroscopic), mild-moderate proteinuria (under 3.5 g/day), hypertension, azotemia. Combined with addressing through diagnosis (post-strep GN, IgA nephropathy, lupus nephritis, ANCA vasculitis, anti-GBM disease).<br><br>4+ Glucose (option A) is not the correct choice; Bilirubin (option D) is not the correct choice, none being acute glomerulonephritis dipstick like moderate blood and 1+ to 2+ protein.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In RPGN, Type II (Immune complex) can be caused by:", "a": "Goodpasture", "b": "Wegener’s", "c": "Alport Syndrome", "d": "Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)", "ans": "D", "e": "Systemic lupus erythematosus causes type II immune complex RPGN; characteristic autoantibodies (anti-dsDNA, anti-Sm) form immune complexes that deposit in glomeruli triggering inflammation.<br><br>Standard lupus nephritis classification (ISN/RPS): Class I (minimal mesangial), Class II (mesangial proliferative), Class III (focal), Class IV (diffuse proliferative - most severe), Class V (membranous), Class VI (advanced sclerosis). Treatment: corticosteroids plus mycophenolate or cyclophosphamide.<br><br>Goodpasture (option A) is not the correct choice; Alport Syndrome (option C) is not the correct choice, none being type II immune complex RPGN cause like systemic lupus erythematosus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of Minimal Change Disease in children is highly responsive to:", "a": "Dialysis", "b": "Penicillin", "c": "Corticosteroids (Prednisone)", "d": "ACE inhibitors only", "ans": "C", "e": "Corticosteroids (prednisone) are mainstay of management for minimal change disease in children; characteristic excellent response (80-90 percent remission) reflects immunological pathogenesis.<br><br>Standard regimen: prednisolone 60 mg/m2/day for 4-6 weeks, then alternate-day for 2-5 months. Combined with addressing relapses (additional courses, alternative agents for steroid-dependent or steroid-resistant cases: cyclophosphamide, ciclosporin, tacrolimus, rituximab).<br><br>Dialysis (option A) is not the correct choice; Penicillin (option B) is not the correct choice; ACE inhibitors only (option D) are inadequate for active disease, none being minimal change disease management like corticosteroids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which statement about Alport Syndrome is correct?", "a": "It is caused by IgA deposits", "b": "It is a defect in Type IV Collagen", "c": "It is purely a kidney disease", "d": "It is easily cured with steroids", "ans": "B", "e": "Alport syndrome is defect in type IV collagen; characteristic mutations in COL4A3, COL4A4, or COL4A5 genes encoding alpha-3, alpha-4, alpha-5 chains affect basement membranes in glomeruli, cochlea, and lens.<br><br>Standard inheritance: X-linked dominant (80 percent, COL4A5), autosomal recessive (15 percent), rare autosomal dominant.<br><br>It is caused by IgA deposits (option A) is IgA nephropathy mechanism; It is purely a kidney disease (option C) is incorrect (extra-renal manifestations occur); It is easily cured with steroids (option D) is incorrect, none being Alport basis like defect in type IV collagen.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with RPGN has negative ANCA, negative anti-GBM, but low C3 and C4. What is the likely cause?", "a": "Alport Syndrome", "b": "Wegener’s", "c": "Goodpasture", "d": "Lupus Nephritis or Cryoglobulinemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Lupus nephritis or cryoglobulinaemia fit RPGN patient with negative ANCA, negative anti-GBM antibodies; characteristic type II (immune complex) RPGN with granular immune deposits distinguishes from pauci-immune and anti-GBM types.<br><br>Standard type II RPGN causes: post-streptococcal GN, IgA nephropathy/Henoch-Schönlein purpura, lupus nephritis (anti-dsDNA, anti-Sm), MPGN, cryoglobulinaemia (hepatitis C association). Diagnosis: biopsy with granular immune deposits, specific serology.<br><br>Alport Syndrome (option A) is not the correct choice; Goodpasture (option C) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN with negative ANCA and anti-GBM like lupus nephritis or cryoglobulinaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is the most common symptom of Nephrotic Syndrome?", "a": "Dysuria", "b": "Peripheral edema (pitting)", "c": "Fever", "d": "Flank pain", "ans": "B", "e": "Peripheral oedema (pitting) is most common symptom of nephrotic syndrome; characteristic generalised oedema from hypoalbuminaemia is dominant clinical feature.<br><br>Standard oedema distribution: dependent areas (legs, ankles in ambulatory patients; sacrum in bedridden patients), periorbital (especially morning), genital, ascites, pleural effusions. Combined with mechanism: hypoalbuminaemia reduces plasma oncotic pressure, secondary hyperaldosteronism causes sodium and water retention.<br><br>Dysuria (option A) is not the correct choice; Fever (option C) is not the correct choice; Flank pain (option D) is not the correct choice, none being most common nephrotic symptom like peripheral oedema.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is NOT part of the classic Nephritic presentation?", "a": "Hematuria", "b": "Oliguria", "c": "Hyperlipidemia", "d": "Hypertension", "ans": "C", "e": "Hyperlipidaemia is NOT part of classic nephritic tetrad; characteristic nephritic features are haematuria, hypertension, mild-moderate proteinuria, oliguria with azotemia, while hyperlipidaemia is nephrotic feature.<br><br>Standard nephritic tetrad: haematuria (RBC casts, dysmorphic RBCs), hypertension, mild-moderate proteinuria (under 3.5 g/day), oliguria/azotemia. Nephrotic tetrad: heavy proteinuria (over 3.5 g/day), hypoalbuminaemia, oedema, hyperlipidaemia.<br><br>Hematuria (option A) IS part of classic nephritic tetrad; Oliguria (option B) IS part of classic nephritic tetrad; Hypertension (option D) IS part of classic nephritic tetrad, none being NOT part of classic nephritic tetrad like hyperlipidaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "IgA Nephropathy is also known as:", "a": "Berger's Disease", "b": "Goodpasture's Disease", "c": "Bright's Disease", "d": "Wegener's Disease", "ans": "A", "e": "Berger's disease is alternative name for IgA nephropathy; characteristic mesangial IgA deposits define disease named after French pathologist Jean Berger who described it in 1968.<br><br>Standard features: synpharyngitic haematuria (within 1-3 days of URTI), most common primary glomerulonephritis worldwide, mesangial IgA deposits on immunofluorescence, mesangial proliferation on light microscopy. Treatment: ACE inhibitors/ARBs for proteinuria, corticosteroids for severe disease.<br><br>Goodpasture's Disease (option B) is not the correct choice; Wegener's Disease (option D) is not the correct choice, none being IgA nephropathy alternative name like Berger's disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Nephrotic syndrome has \"Maltese cross\" appearance in urine. This is seen under:", "a": "Bright-field microscopy", "b": "Polarized light microscopy", "c": "Ultrasound", "d": "Electron microscopy", "ans": "B", "e": "Polarised light microscopy reveals Maltese cross appearance in nephrotic syndrome urine; characteristic birefringence of cholesterol esters in oval fat bodies produces distinctive cross pattern.<br><br>Standard appearance: oval fat bodies are degenerated tubular epithelial cells filled with lipids; under polarised light show Maltese cross pattern (cholesterol esters birefringent). Combined with other nephrotic features: heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, oedema, hyperlipidaemia.<br><br>Bright-field microscopy (option A) is not the correct choice; Electron microscopy (option D) is for ultrastructural detail not Maltese cross, none being Maltese cross detection like polarised light microscopy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In a patient with Alport Syndrome, the end-stage renal disease (ESRD) typically occurs:", "a": "Never", "b": "In infancy", "c": "Only after age 80", "d": "Between ages 20 and 50", "ans": "D", "e": "Between ages 20 and 50 end-stage renal disease typically occurs in Alport syndrome; characteristic progressive decline reflects type IV collagen defect with gradual glomerular damage.<br><br>Standard progression: haematuria in childhood, progressive proteinuria, declining GFR, ESRD typically in 2nd-4th decade for X-linked males. Females with X-linked typically milder.<br><br>Never (option A) is not the correct choice; In infancy (option B) is not the correct choice; Only after age 80 (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Alport ESRD age like between ages 20 and 50.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "RPGN Type I is also known as:", "a": "Pauci-immune GN", "b": "Anti-GBM Disease", "c": "Post-infectious GN", "d": "Immune complex GN", "ans": "B", "e": "Anti-GBM disease is alternative name for RPGN type I; characteristic antibodies against alpha-3 chain of type IV collagen in GBM produce linear immunofluorescence pattern.<br><br>Standard features: pulmonary involvement (Goodpasture syndrome with haemoptysis) in 50-60 percent of cases, isolated renal involvement (anti-GBM disease) in others. Biopsy: crescentic glomerulonephritis with linear IgG along GBM.<br><br>Pauci-immune GN (option A) is not the correct choice; Post-infectious GN (option C) is not the correct choice; Immune complex GN (option D) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN type I alternative name like anti-GBM disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Nephrotic syndrome can lead to a \"Hypercoagulable state.\" Which vessel is a classic site for thrombosis in this condition?", "a": "Renal vein", "b": "Hepatic vein", "c": "Radial artery", "d": "Carotid artery", "ans": "A", "e": "Renal vein is classic thrombosis site in nephrotic hypercoagulable state; characteristic urinary loss of antithrombin III and increased clotting factors produces predisposition.<br><br>Standard renal vein thrombosis features: highest risk in membranous nephropathy, presentation with flank pain, haematuria, sudden worsening of renal function. Diagnosis: Doppler ultrasound, CT/MRI venogram.<br><br>Hepatic vein (option B) is not principal nephrotic thrombosis site; Radial artery (option C) is not the correct choice; Carotid artery (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic hypercoagulable thrombosis site like renal vein.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which laboratory test is typically low in Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis but normal in IgA Nephropathy?", "a": "Creatinine", "b": "Serum C3 (Complement)", "c": "BUN", "d": "Hemoglobin", "ans": "B", "e": "Serum C3 (complement) is typically low in post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis; characteristic immune complex deposition activates complement consuming C3 and C4.<br><br>Standard PSGN features: 10-21 days after streptococcal infection (pharyngitis or skin infection), nephritic syndrome (haematuria, hypertension, oedema, oliguria), elevated ASO titre or anti-DNase B, low C3 (returns to normal in 6-8 weeks). Treatment: supportive care, prognosis usually good.<br><br>Creatinine (option A) is not the correct choice; BUN (option C) is not the correct choice; Hemoglobin (option D) is not the correct choice, none being low PSGN marker like serum C3 complement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The \"Spikes\" seen on silver stain in Membranous Nephropathy represent:", "a": "Basement membrane material growing around subepithelial deposits", "b": "Crystals", "c": "Bacteria", "d": "RBCs", "ans": "A", "e": "Basement membrane material growing around subepithelial deposits produces spikes on silver stain in membranous nephropathy; characteristic immune complexes form between podocytes and GBM with subsequent GBM matrix synthesis.<br><br>Standard biopsy: diffusely thickened GBM, subepithelial immune deposits, spike and dome appearance on silver stain, granular IgG and C3 deposits on immunofluorescence. Anti-PLA2R antibody in primary membranous nephropathy.<br><br>Crystals (option B) is not the correct choice; RBCs (option D) is not the correct choice, none being membranous nephropathy spikes like basement membrane material growing around subepithelial deposits.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with RPGN and a history of asthma and eosinophilia most likely has:", "a": "IgA Nephropathy", "b": "Churg-Strauss Syndrome (EGPA)", "c": "Wegener’s", "d": "Goodpasture", "ans": "B", "e": "Churg-Strauss syndrome (EGPA) fits RPGN patient with history of asthma and eosinophilia; characteristic eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (p-ANCA/MPO positive) features asthma, eosinophilia, vasculitis.<br><br>Standard EGPA features: asthma (often longstanding), peripheral eosinophilia (over 10 percent), pulmonary infiltrates, neuropathy (mononeuritis multiplex), skin involvement, cardiac involvement. Renal involvement (pauci-immune crescentic GN) less common than other ANCA vasculitides.<br><br>IgA Nephropathy (option A) is not the correct choice; Wegener’s (option C) is not the correct choice; Goodpasture (option D) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN with asthma and eosinophilia like Churg-Strauss syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a symptom of Alport Syndrome?", "a": "Chronic cough", "b": "Jaundice", "c": "Seizures", "d": "Hematuria", "ans": "D", "e": "Haematuria is symptom of Alport syndrome; characteristic glomerular bleeding from type IV collagen defect produces persistent or recurrent haematuria.<br><br>Standard Alport renal features: persistent microscopic haematuria (universal), episodic macroscopic haematuria (often after URTI), progressive proteinuria, declining GFR, ESRD in 2nd-4th decade. Extra-renal: sensorineural deafness, anterior lenticonus, perimacular flecks.<br><br>Chronic cough (option A) is not the correct choice; Jaundice (option B) is not the correct choice; Seizures (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Alport syndrome symptom like haematuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most definitive way to differentiate between the different types of RPGN is:", "a": "Immunofluorescence on Renal Biopsy", "b": "Serum Electrolytes", "c": "Urine analysis", "d": "Renal Ultrasound", "ans": "A", "e": "Immunofluorescence on renal biopsy most definitively differentiates types of RPGN; characteristic patterns (linear vs granular vs negative) distinguish anti-GBM, immune complex, and pauci-immune types.<br><br>Standard immunofluorescence patterns: linear IgG along GBM (type I, anti-GBM disease), granular immune deposits, absent or scant deposits (type III, pauci-immune - ANCA vasculitis). Combined with serology (anti-GBM antibody, ANCA, ANA, anti-dsDNA, complement levels).<br><br>Serum Electrolytes (option B) is not the correct choice; Renal Ultrasound (option D) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN type differentiation like immunofluorescence on renal biopsy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hypoalbuminemia in Nephrotic syndrome is defined as serum albumin less than:", "a": "4.5 g/dL", "b": "5.0 g/dL", "c": "6.0 g/dL", "d": "3.0 g/dL", "ans": "D", "e": "3.0 g/dL serum albumin defines hypoalbuminaemia in nephrotic syndrome; characteristic urinary loss of protein produces low plasma albumin (under 3.0 g/dL).<br><br>Standard nephrotic syndrome diagnostic criteria: heavy proteinuria (over 3.5 g/day), hypoalbuminaemia (under 3.0 g/dL), oedema, hyperlipidaemia. Combined with addressing through urinary protein quantification (24-hour urine collection or spot protein/creatinine ratio), serum albumin measurement.<br><br>4.5 g/dL (option A) is normal albumin level; 5.0 g/dL (option B) is normal albumin level; 6.0 g/dL (option C) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic hypoalbuminaemia threshold like 3.0 g/dL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In IgA Nephropathy, the prognosis is worse if the patient has:", "a": "Female gender", "b": "Persistent Hypertension and significant proteinuria", "c": "Only one episode of hematuria", "d": "Young age at onset", "ans": "B", "e": "Persistent hypertension and significant proteinuria worsen IgA nephropathy prognosis; characteristic predictors of progressive disease reflect renal damage severity.<br><br>Standard adverse prognostic factors: heavy proteinuria (over 1 g/day), hypertension, elevated serum creatinine at diagnosis, severe histological lesions (mesangial hypercellularity, segmental sclerosis, tubular atrophy, crescents - MEST-C scoring). Treatment: ACE inhibitors/ARBs, corticosteroids for severe disease.<br><br>Female gender (option A) is not principal prognostic factor; Young age at onset (option D) is not the correct choice, none being IgA nephropathy worse prognosis like persistent hypertension and significant proteinuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Alport syndrome who receives a kidney transplant may rarely develop:", "a": "IgA deposits", "b": "Minimal change disease", "c": "Diabetes", "d": "Anti-GBM disease (Goodpasture) in the graft", "ans": "D", "e": "Anti-GBM disease (Goodpasture) in the graft is risk after kidney transplantation in Alport syndrome; characteristic exposure to wild-type type IV collagen alpha-5 chain in donor kidney triggers antibody formation in recipient lacking the protein.<br><br>Standard incidence: 5-10 percent of Alport patients develop anti-GBM antibodies after transplantation; only 3-5 percent develop clinically significant disease. Higher risk in males with truncating COL4A5 mutations.<br><br>IgA deposits (option A) is not the correct choice; Diabetes (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Alport post-transplant risk like anti-GBM disease in the graft.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Nephrotic syndrome patients should be vaccinated against which organism due to increased susceptibility?", "a": "Streptococcus pneumoniae", "b": "Hepatitis C", "c": "Malaria", "d": "Tetanus", "ans": "A", "e": "Streptococcus pneumoniae is most important pathogen for nephrotic syndrome vaccination; characteristic encapsulated organism causing peritonitis, pneumonia, sepsis in nephrotic patients due to urinary loss of immunoglobulins.<br><br>Standard recommended vaccinations: pneumococcal (PCV13 and PPSV23), influenza (annual), varicella (if non-immune, before immunosuppression), hepatitis B. Combined with addressing through prompt antibiotic treatment for suspected infections, particularly in children.<br><br>Hepatitis C (option B) is not the correct choice; Malaria (option C) is not the correct choice; Tetanus (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic syndrome most important vaccination like Streptococcus pneumoniae.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "According to KDIGO guidelines, CKD Stage 3a is defined by GFR of:", "a": "60–89 ml/min", "b": "90 ml/min", "c": "45–59 ml/min", "d": "30–44 ml/min", "ans": "C", "e": "45-59 mL/min defines CKD stage 3a per KDIGO guidelines; characteristic moderate decline in GFR represents subdivision of stage 3 reflecting cardiovascular and progression risk.<br><br>Standard CKD stages: G1 (normal/high, over 90), G2 (mildly decreased, 60-89), G3a (mild-moderate, 45-59), G3b (moderate-severe, 30-44), G4 (severe, 15-29), G5 (kidney failure, under 15). Combined with albuminuria categories (A1, A2, A3).<br><br>60–89 ml/min (option A) is not the correct choice; 30–44 ml/min (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD stage 3a GFR like 45-59 mL/min.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which GFR value defines CKD Stage 5 (End Stage Renal Disease)?", "a": "<20 ml/min", "b": "<15 ml/min", "c": "<10 ml/min", "d": "<30 ml/min", "ans": "B", "e": "Under 15 mL/min defines CKD stage 5 (end-stage renal disease) per KDIGO guidelines; characteristic kidney failure threshold requires renal replacement therapy or symptom management.<br><br>Standard stage 5 features: severe symptoms (fatigue, anorexia, nausea, pruritus, oedema, oliguria), metabolic abnormalities (acidosis, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, anaemia, renal osteodystrophy), cardiovascular complications. Treatment: dialysis (haemodialysis or peritoneal), kidney transplantation, conservative care in selected patients.<br><br><20 ml/min (option A) is not the correct choice; <30 ml/min (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD stage 5 GFR like under 15 mL/min.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "CKD is defined as kidney damage or GFR <60 ml/min for a duration of at least:", "a": "6 months", "b": "1 month", "c": "2 months", "d": "3 months", "ans": "D", "e": "3 months duration is required to define CKD as kidney damage or GFR under 60 mL/min; characteristic chronicity threshold distinguishes from acute kidney injury.<br><br>Standard CKD definition (KDIGO): abnormalities of kidney structure or function present for over 3 months, with implications for health. Combined with addressing through GFR (under 60 mL/min/1.73 m2) or markers of kidney damage.<br><br>6 months (option A) exceeds the required threshold; 2 months (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD duration threshold like 3 months.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In CKD staging, which additional marker is used alongside GFR in KDIGO 2012 classification?", "a": "Serum urea", "b": "Albuminuria", "c": "Serum creatinine", "d": "Cystatin C", "ans": "B", "e": "Albuminuria is additional marker used alongside GFR in CKD staging; characteristic CKD risk stratification combines GFR category (G1-G5) with albuminuria category (A1, A2, A3).<br><br>Standard albuminuria categories (KDIGO): A1 (normal-mild, under 30 mg/g creatinine), A2 (moderate, 30-300 mg/g), A3 (severe, over 300 mg/g). Combined with addressing through 24-hour urine collection or spot urine albumin/creatinine ratio.<br><br>Serum urea (option A) is not the correct choice; Serum creatinine (option C) is not the correct choice; Cystatin C (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD staging additional marker like albuminuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient has GFR of 22 ml/min. This corresponds to CKD stage:", "a": "Stage 3b", "b": "Stage 3a", "c": "Stage 5", "d": "Stage 4", "ans": "D", "e": "Stage 4 corresponds to GFR of 22 mL/min per KDIGO classification; characteristic severe decline (15-29 mL/min) requires preparation for renal replacement therapy.<br><br>Standard stage 4 features: significant symptoms (fatigue, anorexia, pruritus), metabolic abnormalities (acidosis, hyperphosphataemia, anaemia, secondary hyperparathyroidism), cardiovascular risk. Management: preparation for renal replacement therapy (vascular access for haemodialysis, peritoneal catheter, transplant work-up), nephrology referral.<br><br>Stage 3b (option A) is not the correct choice; Stage 5 (option C) is GFR under 15 mL/min, none being GFR 22 mL/min like stage 4.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "CKD Stage 2 is characterized by GFR of:", "a": "30–44 ml/min", "b": "60–89 ml/min", "c": "90 ml/min or above", "d": "45–59 ml/min", "ans": "B", "e": "60-89 mL/min characterises CKD stage 2 with mild decline in GFR; characteristic stage requires evidence of kidney damage (albuminuria, structural abnormalities) for CKD diagnosis at this GFR level.<br><br>Standard stage 2 management: identifying and treating reversible causes, BP control (under 130/80 mmHg if proteinuria, otherwise under 140/90 mmHg), ACE inhibitors/ARBs if proteinuria, glycaemic control in diabetes, lifestyle modification (smoking cessation, weight reduction).<br><br>30–44 ml/min (option A) is not the correct choice; 45–59 ml/min (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD stage 2 GFR like 60-89 mL/min.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common cause of CKD worldwide is:", "a": "Glomerulonephritis", "b": "Hypertension", "c": "Polycystic kidney disease", "d": "Diabetes mellitus", "ans": "D", "e": "Diabetes mellitus is most common cause of CKD worldwide; characteristic hyperglycaemia-induced glomerular damage with mesangial expansion and Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodular glomerulosclerosis.<br><br>Standard diabetic nephropathy stages: hyperfiltration, microalbuminuria (30-300 mg/day), macroalbuminuria (over 300 mg/day), nephrotic-range proteinuria, declining GFR. Treatment: glycaemic control (HbA1c under 7 percent if appropriate), BP control, ACE inhibitors/ARBs, SGLT-2 inhibitors.<br><br>Glomerulonephritis (option A) is third most common cause of CKD; Polycystic kidney disease (option C) is most common inherited cause, none being most common CKD cause worldwide like diabetes mellitus.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The second most common cause of CKD in developed countries is:", "a": "Hypertension", "b": "Chronic pyelonephritis", "c": "IgA nephropathy", "d": "Lupus nephritis", "ans": "A", "e": "Hypertension is second most common cause of CKD in developed countries; characteristic chronic elevated BP produces nephrosclerosis with arteriolar and glomerular damage.<br><br>Standard hypertensive nephrosclerosis features: gradual decline in GFR, mild-moderate proteinuria, hyperuricaemia common. Prevention/treatment: BP control (target under 130/80 mmHg if proteinuria), ACE inhibitors/ARBs (preferred), lifestyle modification (sodium restriction, weight loss, exercise).<br><br>Chronic pyelonephritis (option B) is not the correct choice; IgA nephropathy (option C) is not the correct choice; Lupus nephritis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being second most common CKD cause like hypertension.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which genetic condition is the most common hereditary cause of CKD?", "a": "Fabry disease", "b": "D) Medullary cystic kidney disease", "c": "Alport syndrome", "d": "Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPK", "ans": "D", "e": "Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) is most common hereditary cause of CKD; characteristic multiple bilateral renal cysts with progressive enlargement and renal dysfunction.<br><br>Standard ADPKD features: PKD1 mutation (85 percent, chromosome 16) or PKD2 mutation (15 percent, chromosome 4), bilateral renal cysts, extrarenal manifestations. Treatment: BP control, tolvaptan (V2 receptor antagonist) for rapidly progressive disease.<br><br>Fabry disease (option A) is not the correct choice; Alport syndrome (option C) is not the correct choice, none being most common hereditary CKD cause like autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Analgesic nephropathy is most commonly associated with chronic use of:", "a": "Aspirin alone", "b": "Opioids", "c": "NSAIDs or combined analgesic preparations", "d": "Paracetamol alone", "ans": "C", "e": "NSAIDs or combined analgesic preparations are most commonly associated with analgesic nephropathy; characteristic chronic use produces papillary necrosis and chronic interstitial nephritis.<br><br>Standard analgesic nephropathy features: chronic interstitial nephritis, papillary necrosis (sloughed papillae causing obstruction), reduced renal medullary blood flow, increased urothelial malignancy risk. Combined with addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>Aspirin alone (option A) is not the correct choice; Opioids (option B) is not the correct choice; Paracetamol alone (option D) is not the correct choice, none being analgesic nephropathy cause like NSAIDs or combined analgesic preparations.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Reflux nephropathy as a cause of CKD results from:", "a": "Recurrent urinary tract infections due to vesicoureteral reflux", "b": "Tubular toxins", "c": "Glomerular inflammation", "d": "Renal artery stenosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Recurrent urinary tract infections due to vesicoureteric reflux cause reflux nephropathy; characteristic ascending infections damage renal cortex producing scarring and progressive renal dysfunction.<br><br>Standard reflux nephropathy features: childhood UTIs with vesicoureteric reflux, renal scarring (focal cortical thinning, calyceal clubbing), hypertension, proteinuria, progressive CKD. Diagnosis: voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG), DMSA scan for scarring.<br><br>Tubular toxins (option B) is not the correct choice; Renal artery stenosis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being reflux nephropathy cause like recurrent UTIs due to vesicoureteric reflux.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a common obstructive cause of CKD in elderly men?", "a": "Bladder cancer", "b": "Urethral stricture", "c": "Renal calculi", "d": "Benign prostatic hyperplasia", "ans": "D", "e": "Benign prostatic hyperplasia is common obstructive cause of CKD; characteristic progressive prostatic enlargement obstructs urinary outflow producing bilateral hydronephrosis.<br><br>Standard BPH features: lower urinary tract symptoms (hesitancy, weak stream, frequency, nocturia, incomplete emptying), elevated post-void residual, hydronephrosis (severe cases). Diagnosis: digital rectal examination, PSA, ultrasound. Treatment: alpha-blockers (tamsulosin), 5-alpha reductase inhibitors (finasteride), surgical relief.<br><br>Bladder cancer (option A) is not the correct choice; Urethral stricture (option B) is not the correct choice; Renal calculi (option C) is not the correct choice, none being obstructive CKD cause like benign prostatic hyperplasia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The earliest symptom of CKD is often:", "a": "Severe oedema", "b": "Haematuria", "c": "Nocturia", "d": "Oliguria", "ans": "C", "e": "Nocturia is often earliest symptom of CKD; characteristic loss of tubular concentrating ability produces inability to concentrate urine at night.<br><br>Standard early CKD symptoms: nocturia, polyuria (due to impaired urine concentration), fatigue. Progressive symptoms: anorexia, nausea, pruritus, oedema, hypertension. Combined with metabolic abnormalities (acidosis, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, anaemia) and complications (cardiovascular disease, renal osteodystrophy, neurological symptoms).<br><br>Severe oedema (option A) is not the correct choice; Haematuria (option B) is not the correct choice; Oliguria (option D) is not the correct choice, none being earliest CKD symptom like nocturia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic frost is a skin manifestation of CKD caused by:", "a": "Phosphate deposition", "b": "Urea crystallizing on the skin", "c": "Calcium deposits", "d": "Bile pigments", "ans": "B", "e": "Urea crystallising on skin causes uraemic frost; characteristic skin manifestation of severe CKD reflects extremely elevated urea levels with crystallisation in sweat.<br><br>Standard uraemic frost features: white powder-like deposits on skin (especially face, beard area, exposed surfaces), seen in advanced uraemia with very high BUN levels. Combined with other uraemic skin features: pruritus, hyperpigmentation, half-and-half nails, pseudoporphyria.<br><br>Phosphate deposition (option A) is not the correct choice; Bile pigments (option D) is not the correct choice, none being uraemic frost mechanism like urea crystallising on skin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which type of anaemia is classically seen in CKD?", "a": "Macrocytic", "b": "Microcytic hypochromic", "c": "Haemolytic", "d": "Normocytic normochromic", "ans": "D", "e": "Normocytic normochromic anaemia is classically seen in CKD; characteristic erythropoietin deficiency from declining renal mass produces hypoproliferative anaemia with normal cell size and haemoglobin content.<br><br>Standard CKD anaemia features: normocytic normochromic, hypoproliferative (low reticulocyte count), worsens with declining GFR (typically apparent at GFR under 60 mL/min). Combined with iron deficiency (impaired iron absorption, blood loss from dialysis), vitamin deficiency (folate, B12), uraemic suppression of erythropoiesis.<br><br>Macrocytic (option A) is not the correct choice; Haemolytic (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD anaemia type like normocytic normochromic.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The anaemia of CKD is primarily due to deficiency of:", "a": "Iron", "b": "Erythropoietin", "c": "Vitamin B12", "d": "Folic acid", "ans": "B", "e": "Erythropoietin deficiency is primary cause of CKD anaemia; characteristic decline in EPO production from damaged kidneys produces hypoproliferative anaemia.<br><br>Standard EPO physiology: produced by peritubular interstitial cells in renal cortex, stimulates erythropoiesis in bone marrow. Treatment of CKD anaemia: erythropoiesis-stimulating agents (epoetin alfa, darbepoetin), iron supplementation (oral or IV), target haemoglobin 10-11.5 g/dL (avoiding higher targets due to cardiovascular risk).<br><br>Iron (option A) is contributing but not primary cause; Folic acid (option D) is contributing but not primary cause, none being CKD anaemia primary deficiency like erythropoietin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic pericarditis in CKD is an indication for:", "a": "Urgent dialysis", "b": "IV antibiotics", "c": "Steroids", "d": "Pericardiectomy", "ans": "A", "e": "Urgent dialysis is indicated for uraemic pericarditis in CKD; characteristic life-threatening complication of severe uraemia requires immediate renal replacement therapy.<br><br>Standard uraemic pericarditis features: friction rub, chest pain, ECG changes (PR depression, ST elevation), pericardial effusion, risk of cardiac tamponade. Combined with other dialysis indications (AEIOU mnemonic): Acidosis, Electrolytes (hyperkalaemia), Intoxications, Overload (fluid), Uraemia (encephalopathy, pericarditis, bleeding).<br><br>IV antibiotics (option B) is not the correct choice; Steroids (option C) is not the correct choice; Pericardiectomy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being uraemic pericarditis indication like urgent dialysis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which electrolyte abnormality is most life-threatening in CKD?", "a": "Hyperphosphataemia", "b": "Hypocalcaemia", "c": "Hyperkalaemia", "d": "Hyponatraemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Hyperkalaemia is most life-threatening electrolyte abnormality in CKD; characteristic impaired potassium excretion combined with acidosis-induced cellular shift produces cardiac arrhythmia risk.<br><br>Standard hyperkalaemia ECG changes: peaked T waves (over 5.5 mEq/L), prolonged PR interval, widened QRS, sine wave pattern (severe). Treatment: calcium gluconate (cardiac membrane stabilisation), insulin plus glucose, salbutamol nebulisation, sodium bicarbonate if acidotic, kayexalate or dialysis.<br><br>Hyperphosphataemia (option A) occurs in CKD but less immediately life-threatening; Hyponatraemia (option D) is not the correct choice, none being most life-threatening CKD electrolyte like hyperkalaemia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Restless leg syndrome in CKD patients is associated with:", "a": "Metabolic alkalosis", "b": "Uraemia and iron deficiency", "c": "Hyperphosphataemia", "d": "Hyperkalaemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Uraemia and iron deficiency are associated with restless leg syndrome in CKD patients; characteristic uraemic neuropathy and iron deficiency contribute to lower limb dysaesthesia and urge to move.<br><br>Standard CKD restless leg features: unpleasant sensations with urge to move, worsens at rest, relieved by movement. Treatment: correct iron deficiency, optimise dialysis, dopaminergic agents (ropinirole), gabapentin.<br><br>Metabolic alkalosis (option A) is not the correct choice; Hyperkalaemia (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD restless leg syndrome association like uraemia and iron deficiency.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Metabolic acidosis in CKD is primarily due to:", "a": "Inability of kidneys to excrete hydrogen ions and synthesize ammonia", "b": "Excess lactic acid production", "c": "Loss of bicarbonate in urine", "d": "Hyperventilation", "ans": "A", "e": "Inability of kidneys to excrete hydrogen ions and bicarbonate loss cause metabolic acidosis in CKD; characteristic impaired acid excretion combined with reduced bicarbonate regeneration produces acidaemia.<br><br>Standard CKD acidosis features: high anion gap metabolic acidosis, normal anion gap metabolic acidosis. Treatment: sodium bicarbonate supplementation (target serum bicarbonate over 22 mEq/L), addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>Excess lactic acid production (option B) is not the correct choice; Hyperventilation (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD acidosis mechanism like inability of kidneys to excrete hydrogen ions and bicarbonate loss.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "“Chicken wire” pattern on skull X-ray is seen in CKD due to:", "a": "Amyloid deposition", "b": "Fluorosis", "c": "Renal osteodystrophy (secondary hyperparathyroidism)", "d": "Metastatic calcification", "ans": "C", "e": "Renal osteodystrophy (secondary hyperparathyroidism) produces chicken wire pattern on skull X-ray in CKD; characteristic subperiosteal bone resorption reflects severe secondary hyperparathyroidism.<br><br>Standard renal osteodystrophy features: secondary hyperparathyroidism (elevated PTH from hypocalcaemia, hyperphosphataemia, decreased calcitriol), subperiosteal bone resorption, brown tumours, osteomalacia, adynamic bone disease. Treatment: phosphate binders, calcitriol or active vitamin D analogues, cinacalcet (calcimimetic).<br><br>Amyloid deposition (option A) is not the correct choice; Fluorosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Metastatic calcification (option D) is not the correct choice, none being chicken wire skull X-ray cause like renal osteodystrophy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Kussmaul breathing in CKD is a compensatory response to:", "a": "Metabolic acidosis", "b": "Fluid overload", "c": "Hypernatraemia", "d": "Uraemic encephalopathy", "ans": "A", "e": "Metabolic acidosis triggers Kussmaul breathing compensatory response in CKD; characteristic deep rapid breathing reflects respiratory compensation for metabolic acidaemia.<br><br>Standard Kussmaul breathing features: deep, rapid, laboured breathing without distress, reflects respiratory drive to blow off CO2 lowering pH. Seen in metabolic acidosis from various causes (DKA, uraemia, lactic acidosis, salicylate poisoning, methanol/ethylene glycol poisoning).<br><br>Fluid overload (option B) is not the correct choice; Hypernatraemia (option C) is not the correct choice; Uraemic encephalopathy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Kussmaul breathing trigger like metabolic acidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The target blood pressure in CKD patients with proteinuria is:", "a": "<120/70 mmHg", "b": "<140/90 mmHg", "c": "<150/90 mmHg", "d": "<130/80 mmHg", "ans": "D", "e": "Under 130/80 mmHg is target blood pressure in CKD patients with proteinuria; characteristic stricter BP target reduces proteinuria progression and cardiovascular events.<br><br>Standard BP targets: CKD with proteinuria (under 130/80 mmHg), CKD without proteinuria (under 140/90 mmHg). Combined with addressing through ACE inhibitors/ARBs, thiazide diuretics (early CKD), loop diuretics (advanced CKD), calcium channel blockers, beta blockers.<br><br><120/70 mmHg (option A) is not the correct choice; <150/90 mmHg (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD with proteinuria BP target like under 130/80 mmHg.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "First-line antihypertensive agent in CKD with proteinuria is:", "a": "Diuretics", "b": "Beta-blocker", "c": "ACE inhibitor or ARB", "d": "Calcium channel blocker", "ans": "C", "e": "ACE inhibitor or ARB is first-line antihypertensive in CKD with proteinuria; characteristic reduction in intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria slows renal progression.<br><br>Standard ACE inhibitor/ARB benefits: reduce proteinuria, lower BP, slow CKD progression, reduce cardiovascular events. Side effects: hyperkalaemia, dry cough (ACE inhibitors), angioedema (rare).<br><br>Diuretics (option A) is not the correct choice; Beta-blocker (option B) is not the correct choice; Calcium channel blocker (option D) is adjunct not first-line for CKD with proteinuria, none being CKD with proteinuria first-line antihypertensive like ACE inhibitor or ARB.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "ACE inhibitors are beneficial in CKD because they:", "a": "Increase GFR", "b": "Reduce intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria", "c": "Increase erythropoietin production", "d": "Reduce serum potassium", "ans": "B", "e": "ACE inhibitors reduce intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria in CKD; characteristic efferent arteriolar vasodilation lowers glomerular capillary pressure protecting glomeruli.<br><br>Standard ACE inhibitor mechanism: blocks angiotensin II formation, causes efferent arteriolar vasodilation greater than afferent, lowers intraglomerular pressure, reduces hyperfiltration, decreases proteinuria, slows nephron loss. Combined with addressing systemic BP control.<br><br>Increase GFR (option A) is not the correct choice; Reduce serum potassium (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ACE inhibitor benefit in CKD like reduce intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which dietary modification is essential in CKD management?", "a": "High protein diet", "b": "High sodium diet to maintain BP", "c": "High calcium diet", "d": "Low potassium, low phosphate, low protein diet", "ans": "D", "e": "Low potassium, low phosphate, low protein diet is essential dietary modification in CKD management; characteristic addressing of metabolic abnormalities and reducing waste production slows progression.<br><br>Standard CKD diet recommendations: protein 0.6-0.8 g/kg/day, potassium restriction in hyperkalaemia, phosphate restriction, sodium restriction (under 2 g/day), adequate caloric intake. Combined with addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>High protein diet (option A) increases urea load and may worsen CKD progression; High calcium diet (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD essential dietary modification like low potassium, low phosphate, low protein diet.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents (ESAs) in CKD should be initiated when Hb drops below:", "a": "11 g/dL", "b": "13 g/dL", "c": "7 g/dL", "d": "9 g/dL", "ans": "A", "e": "11 g/dL is target haemoglobin level for erythropoiesis-stimulating agents in CKD; characteristic balancing of symptomatic anaemia treatment with cardiovascular risk avoidance.<br><br>Standard ESA therapy targets: haemoglobin 10-11.5 g/dL (avoiding higher targets due to increased cardiovascular events, thrombosis, mortality). Combined with iron supplementation (oral or IV, target ferritin over 200-500 ng/mL, transferrin saturation over 20-30 percent).<br><br>13 g/dL (option B) is too high (increased cardiovascular risk); 9 g/dL (option D) is below the target range, none being CKD ESA haemoglobin target like 11 g/dL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Phosphate binders used in CKD include all EXCEPT:", "a": "Calcium carbonate", "b": "Sevelamer", "c": "Lanthanum carbonate", "d": "Sodium bicarbonate", "ans": "D", "e": "Sodium bicarbonate is NOT a phosphate binder used in CKD; characteristic phosphate binders bind dietary phosphate in gut preventing absorption, while sodium bicarbonate treats metabolic acidosis.<br><br>Standard CKD phosphate binders: calcium-based (calcium carbonate, calcium acetate - watch for hypercalcaemia), non-calcium-based (sevelamer, lanthanum carbonate, iron-based: ferric citrate, sucroferric oxyhydroxide), aluminium-based (rarely used due to toxicity). Combined with addressing through dietary phosphate restriction.<br><br>Calcium carbonate (option A) IS phosphate binder (calcium-based); Lanthanum carbonate (option C) IS phosphate binder (non-calcium-based), none being NOT CKD phosphate binder like sodium bicarbonate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which drug is used to manage secondary hyperparathyroidism in CKD?", "a": "Cinacalcet", "b": "Raloxifene", "c": "Calcitonin", "d": "Pamidronate", "ans": "A", "e": "Cinacalcet manages secondary hyperparathyroidism in CKD; characteristic calcimimetic agent increases sensitivity of calcium-sensing receptor on parathyroid cells, reducing PTH secretion.<br><br>Standard cinacalcet indications: secondary hyperparathyroidism in dialysis patients (PTH consistently over 300 pg/mL despite other treatments), parathyroid carcinoma. Combined with phosphate binders, vitamin D analogues (calcitriol, paricalcitol). Side effects: hypocalcaemia, nausea, vomiting.<br><br>Raloxifene (option B) is not the correct choice; Calcitonin (option C) is not the correct choice; Pamidronate (option D) is not the correct choice, none being secondary hyperparathyroidism management like cinacalcet.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Sodium bicarbonate supplementation in CKD is given to correct:", "a": "Hyperphosphataemia", "b": "Hypernatraemia", "c": "Hyperkalaemia", "d": "Metabolic acidosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Sodium bicarbonate supplementation in CKD corrects metabolic acidosis; characteristic exogenous bicarbonate replaces lost bicarbonate slowing CKD progression and improving outcomes.<br><br>Standard sodium bicarbonate therapy: target serum bicarbonate over 22 mEq/L, typical dose 0.5-1 mEq/kg/day. Benefits: slows CKD progression, improves bone metabolism, reduces muscle wasting, may improve nutritional status.<br><br>Hyperphosphataemia (option A) is addressed with phosphate binders not bicarbonate; Hypernatraemia (option B) is not the correct choice; Hyperkalaemia (option C) is addressed with bicarbonate as adjunct but not primary indication, none being sodium bicarbonate CKD indication like metabolic acidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which class of drugs should be avoided or used with caution in CKD due to risk of lactic acidosis?", "a": "DPP-4 inhibitors", "b": "Metformin", "c": "Sulfonylureas", "d": "GLP-1 agonists", "ans": "B", "e": "Metformin should be avoided or used with caution in CKD; characteristic risk of lactic acidosis in advanced CKD requires dose adjustment or avoidance.<br><br>Standard metformin in CKD: avoid if eGFR under 30 mL/min, reduce dose if eGFR 30-45 mL/min (target dose 1000 mg/day), normal dose if eGFR over 45 mL/min. Combined with addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>DPP-4 inhibitors (option A) is not the correct choice; Sulfonylureas (option C) is not the correct choice; GLP-1 agonists (option D) is not the correct choice, none being drug avoided in CKD like metformin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Loop diuretics are preferred over thiazides in CKD when GFR falls below:", "a": "60 ml/min", "b": "15 ml/min", "c": "45 ml/min", "d": "30 ml/min", "ans": "D", "e": "30 mL/min GFR threshold makes loop diuretics preferred over thiazides in CKD; characteristic decreased thiazide efficacy in advanced CKD requires loop diuretics for diuresis.<br><br>Standard diuretic use in CKD: thiazides, loop diuretics, potassium-sparing diuretics (caution in CKD due to hyperkalaemia risk). Combined with monitoring electrolytes and fluid status.<br><br>60 ml/min (option A) is normal-mild reduction (thiazides still effective); 45 ml/min (option C) is above the threshold (thiazides still partially effective), none being thiazide ineffective threshold in CKD like 30 mL/min.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A new drug class shown to slow CKD progression in diabetic nephropathy is:", "a": "Thiazolidinediones", "b": "DPP-4 inhibitors", "c": "SGLT-2 inhibitors", "d": "Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors", "ans": "C", "e": "SGLT-2 inhibitors slow CKD progression in diabetic patients; characteristic renoprotection through reduced intraglomerular pressure, decreased proteinuria, and pleotropic effects.<br><br>Standard SGLT-2 inhibitor benefits: reduced cardiovascular events, reduced heart failure hospitalisations, slowed CKD progression, reduced proteinuria. Examples: empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, canagliflozin. Side effects: genital fungal infections, euglycaemic DKA (rare), increased UTI risk.<br><br>Thiazolidinediones (option A) is not the correct choice; DPP-4 inhibitors (option B) is not the correct choice; Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors (option D) are not principal CKD-progression slowing drugs, none being diabetic CKD progression slowing drug class like SGLT-2 inhibitors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Vitamin D supplementation in CKD is given as:", "a": "Cholecalciferol only", "b": "Vitamin D2", "c": "Ergocalciferol only", "d": "Active form – Calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D)", "ans": "D", "e": "Active form calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D) is given as vitamin D supplementation in CKD; characteristic impaired 1-alpha-hydroxylation in kidneys requires bypassing this step with active vitamin D.<br><br>Standard vitamin D therapy in CKD: calcitriol or active vitamin D analogues (paricalcitol, doxercalciferol) for secondary hyperparathyroidism, ergocalciferol or cholecalciferol for nutritional vitamin D deficiency. Combined with addressing through phosphate binders, dietary phosphate restriction.<br><br>Cholecalciferol only (option A) is not the correct choice; Ergocalciferol only (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD vitamin D form like active calcitriol.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Renal osteodystrophy in CKD results from:", "a": "High PTH, low calcium, high phosphate, low active Vitamin D", "b": "Normal PTH with low Vitamin D", "c": "High calcium and low phosphate", "d": "Low PTH and low calcium", "ans": "A", "e": "High PTH, low calcium, high phosphate, low active vitamin D produces renal osteodystrophy in CKD; characteristic metabolic disturbances combine to disrupt bone metabolism.<br><br>Standard renal osteodystrophy mechanism: decreased calcitriol, phosphate retention, hypocalcaemia stimulating PTH (secondary hyperparathyroidism). Bone manifestations: osteitis fibrosa cystica, adynamic bone disease, osteomalacia.<br><br>Normal PTH with low Vitamin D (option B) is not the correct choice; Low PTH and low calcium (option D) is not the correct choice, none being renal osteodystrophy pattern like high PTH, low calcium, high phosphate, low active vitamin D.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of death in CKD patients. The main contributing risk factor is:", "a": "Malnutrition", "b": "Multiple factors: hypertension, dyslipidaemia, fluid overload, uraemia", "c": "Electrolyte imbalance alone", "d": "Anaemia alone", "ans": "B", "e": "Multiple factors (hypertension, dyslipidaemia, fluid overload) cause cardiovascular disease as leading cause of death in CKD; characteristic accelerated atherosclerosis and cardiac dysfunction reflect uraemic vasculopathy.<br><br>Standard CKD cardiovascular risk factors: hypertension, dyslipidaemia, fluid overload, anaemia, hyperphosphataemia (vascular calcification), elevated FGF-23, uraemic toxins, oxidative stress, chronic inflammation. Combined with addressing through BP control, statins, fluid management, addressing anaemia, phosphate control.<br><br>Malnutrition (option A) is not the correct choice; Anaemia alone (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD cardiovascular death cause like multiple factors (hypertension, dyslipidaemia, fluid overload).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "“Brown tumors” seen in CKD are due to:", "a": "Malignant transformation", "b": "Metastatic calcification", "c": "Severe secondary hyperparathyroidism", "d": "Amyloid deposits", "ans": "C", "e": "Severe secondary hyperparathyroidism causes brown tumours in CKD; characteristic localised bone resorption with osteoclast accumulation and haemosiderin produces brown appearance.<br><br>Standard brown tumour features: focal bone lesions (jaw, pelvis, long bones, fingers), composed of osteoclasts, haemorrhage, haemosiderin deposition. Combined with other secondary hyperparathyroidism features: subperiosteal bone resorption, salt-and-pepper skull, osteitis fibrosa cystica.<br><br>Malignant transformation (option A) is not the correct choice; Metastatic calcification (option B) is not the correct choice; Amyloid deposits (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD brown tumour cause like severe secondary hyperparathyroidism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Metastatic calcification in CKD most commonly affects:", "a": "Joints and blood vessels", "b": "Lungs and brain only", "c": "Eyes only", "d": "Liver and spleen", "ans": "A", "e": "Joints and blood vessels are most commonly affected by metastatic calcification in CKD; characteristic deposition of calcium-phosphate complexes in soft tissues reflects elevated calcium-phosphate product.<br><br>Standard metastatic calcification mechanism: elevated calcium-phosphate product (over 55-70 mg2/dL2 in CKD), vascular calcification, soft tissue calcification (periarticular, conjunctival, dermal). Combined with addressing through phosphate binders, dietary phosphate restriction, addressing secondary hyperparathyroidism.<br><br>Lungs and brain only (option B) is not the correct choice; Liver and spleen (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD metastatic calcification sites like joints and blood vessels.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic encephalopathy presents with all EXCEPT:", "a": "Seizures", "b": "Confusion and asterixis", "c": "Coma", "d": "Fever as the primary manifestation", "ans": "D", "e": "Fever as the primary manifestation is NOT typical of uraemic encephalopathy; characteristic neurological symptoms (confusion, asterixis, seizures, coma) rather than fever dominate clinical picture.<br><br>Standard uraemic encephalopathy features: progressive cognitive impairment, confusion, lethargy, asterixis, myoclonus, seizures, coma in severe cases. Combined with addressing through dialysis for severe uraemic encephalopathy, addressing underlying cause, supportive care.<br><br>Seizures (option A) ARE uraemic encephalopathy feature in severe cases; Coma (option C) is not the correct choice, none being NOT uraemic encephalopathy feature like fever as primary manifestation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The bleeding tendency in CKD is mainly due to:", "a": "Clotting factor deficiency", "b": "Thrombocytopenia", "c": "Platelet dysfunction caused by uraemic toxins", "d": "Fibrinolysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Platelet dysfunction caused by uraemic toxins is main cause of bleeding tendency in CKD; characteristic uraemic toxins impair platelet aggregation and adhesion producing prolonged bleeding time.<br><br>Standard CKD bleeding features: prolonged bleeding time, gastrointestinal bleeding, pericardial effusion. Treatment: addressing through dialysis (removes uraemic toxins), desmopressin (DDAVP - releases von Willebrand factor), conjugated oestrogens, cryoprecipitate for severe bleeding, addressing anaemia.<br><br>Clotting factor deficiency (option A) is not the correct choice; Fibrinolysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD bleeding mechanism like platelet dysfunction caused by uraemic toxins.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis in CKD patients can be triggered by:", "a": "Gadolinium-based contrast", "b": "CT scan radiation", "c": "MRI magnetic field", "d": "Iodinated contrast", "ans": "A", "e": "Gadolinium-based contrast is triggering exposure for nephrogenic systemic fibrosis in CKD; characteristic severe AKI or CKD with gadolinium exposure produces systemic fibrotic disorder.<br><br>Standard NSF features: progressive cutaneous thickening and hardening (typically lower extremities), joint contractures, systemic fibrosis affecting muscles, viscera. Pathogenesis: gadolinium deposition in tissues triggering fibrosis.<br><br>CT scan radiation (option B) is not the correct choice; MRI magnetic field (option C) is not the correct choice; Iodinated contrast (option D) is not the correct choice, none being NSF triggering exposure like gadolinium-based contrast.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hyperuricaemia in CKD can lead to:", "a": "Only gout", "b": "Only renal calculi", "c": "Pseudogout exclusively", "d": "Renal calculi and gout", "ans": "D", "e": "Renal calculi and gout result from hyperuricaemia in CKD; characteristic uric acid accumulation produces stone formation and crystal deposition in joints.<br><br>Standard hyperuricaemia in CKD features: reduced uric acid excretion, urate crystal deposition, uric acid stones (more in acid urine). Treatment: addressing modifiable factors (alcohol moderation, weight loss, dietary purine restriction), allopurinol (xanthine oxidase inhibitor with dose adjustment in CKD), febuxostat.<br><br>Only gout (option A) is not the correct choice; Pseudogout exclusively (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD hyperuricaemia consequence like renal calculi and gout.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "ESRD is defined as GFR below:", "a": "5 ml/min", "b": "15 ml/min", "c": "20 ml/min", "d": "10 ml/min", "ans": "B", "e": "15 mL/min GFR defines end-stage renal disease threshold; characteristic stage 5 CKD requires renal replacement therapy or conservative care.<br><br>Standard ESRD features: severe symptoms (fatigue, anorexia, nausea, pruritus, oedema, oliguria), metabolic abnormalities (acidosis, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, anaemia, renal osteodystrophy), cardiovascular complications. Treatment: dialysis (haemodialysis or peritoneal), kidney transplantation, conservative care in selected patients (poor prognosis, frailty).<br><br>5 ml/min (option A) is not the correct choice; 10 ml/min (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ESRD GFR definition like under 15 mL/min.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common form of renal replacement therapy (RRT) used worldwide is:", "a": "Peritoneal dialysis", "b": "Kidney transplantation", "c": "Haemodialysis", "d": "Haemofiltration", "ans": "C", "e": "Haemodialysis is most common form of renal replacement therapy; characteristic extracorporeal blood circulation through dialyser provides effective solute and fluid removal.<br><br>Standard haemodialysis features: typically 3 sessions per week, 3-4 hours each session. Requires vascular access (arteriovenous fistula preferred, arteriovenous graft, central venous catheter). Combined with addressing complications (hypotension, cramps, arrhythmias, access dysfunction, infections).<br><br>Peritoneal dialysis (option A) is less common than haemodialysis worldwide; Kidney transplantation (option B) is not the correct choice; Haemofiltration (option D) is not the correct choice, none being most common RRT form like haemodialysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In haemodialysis, the principle of solute removal is mainly:", "a": "Diffusion", "b": "Convection", "c": "Osmosis", "d": "Ultrafiltration", "ans": "A", "e": "Diffusion is mainly principle of solute removal in haemodialysis; characteristic concentration gradient drives movement of solutes from blood across semipermeable membrane into dialysate.<br><br>Standard haemodialysis principles: diffusion, convection (water and middle molecules through ultrafiltration), ultrafiltration (water removal by pressure gradient). Combined with addressing through anticoagulation (heparin), bicarbonate-based dialysate, blood flow rate 300-500 mL/min, dialysate flow rate 500-800 mL/min.<br><br>Convection (option B) is contributory but not principal mechanism in standard haemodialysis; Ultrafiltration (option D) is not the correct choice, none being haemodialysis solute removal principle like diffusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Peritoneal dialysis uses which membrane for filtration?", "a": "Haemodialysis membrane", "b": "Peritoneal membrane", "c": "Synthetic membrane", "d": "Glomerular basement membrane", "ans": "B", "e": "Peritoneal membrane is filtration membrane in peritoneal dialysis; characteristic semipermeable peritoneum allows solute and fluid exchange between dialysate in peritoneal cavity and blood in peritoneal capillaries.<br><br>Standard peritoneal dialysis features: continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis (CAPD - 4 exchanges/day manual), automated peritoneal dialysis (APD - overnight machine). Dialysate (glucose-based or icodextrin-based) instilled through Tenckhoff catheter.<br><br>Haemodialysis membrane (option A) is not the correct choice; Glomerular basement membrane (option D) is not the correct choice, none being peritoneal dialysis filtration membrane like peritoneal membrane.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common complication of peritoneal dialysis is:", "a": "Thrombosis", "b": "Fluid overload", "c": "Bacterial peritonitis", "d": "Hyperkalaemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Bacterial peritonitis is most common complication of peritoneal dialysis; characteristic catheter-related infection produces abdominal pain, fever, cloudy dialysate effluent.<br><br>Standard PD peritonitis diagnosis: dialysate WBC over 100/microL with over 50 percent neutrophils, positive culture (most common organisms: Staphylococcus epidermidis, Staphylococcus aureus, gram-negative bacteria). Treatment: intraperitoneal antibiotics, addressing through cultures, considering catheter removal for refractory or fungal peritonitis.<br><br>Thrombosis (option A) is not the correct choice; Hyperkalaemia (option D) is rare with PD (often improves), none being most common PD complication like bacterial peritonitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The preferred arteriovenous access for long-term haemodialysis is:", "a": "Arteriovenous graft", "b": "Arteriovenous fistula (AVF)", "c": "Femoral catheter", "d": "Subclavian catheter", "ans": "B", "e": "Arteriovenous fistula (AVF) is preferred arteriovenous access for long-term haemodialysis; characteristic native vessel anastomosis provides best longevity and lowest complication rates.<br><br>Standard AVF features: surgically created connection between artery and vein, requires 6-12 weeks for maturation, lower infection and thrombosis rates than alternatives. Combined with addressing through vein preservation in CKD patients, early referral for vascular access creation, avoiding subclavian access.<br><br>Arteriovenous graft (option A) is not the correct choice; Subclavian catheter (option D) is not the correct choice, none being preferred long-term haemodialysis access like arteriovenous fistula.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Contraindications to kidney transplantation include all EXCEPT:", "a": "Controlled hypertension", "b": "Active infections", "c": "Active malignancy", "d": "Severe cardiovascular disease", "ans": "A", "e": "Controlled hypertension is NOT contraindication to kidney transplantation; characteristic well-managed hypertension is common in CKD and does not preclude transplantation.<br><br>Standard kidney transplant contraindications: active malignancy (with limited disease-free interval), active infection (treat first), severe cardiovascular disease (high perioperative risk), severe psychiatric disease, active substance abuse, short life expectancy. Combined with addressing through pre-transplant evaluation (cardiac, infectious disease, malignancy screening).<br><br>Active infections (option B) is not the correct choice; Severe cardiovascular disease (option D) is not the correct choice, none being NOT kidney transplant contraindication like controlled hypertension.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common cause of death in ESRD patients on dialysis is:", "a": "Stroke", "b": "Cardiovascular disease", "c": "Malignancy", "d": "Infection/sepsis", "ans": "B", "e": "Cardiovascular disease is most common cause of death in ESRD patients on dialysis; characteristic accelerated atherosclerosis and cardiac dysfunction from uraemic vasculopathy and traditional risk factors.<br><br>Standard ESRD cardiovascular features: ischaemic heart disease, sudden cardiac death (arrhythmias), heart failure, pericarditis, valvular calcification. Combined with addressing through BP control, statins, addressing anaemia, phosphate control, addressing dialysis adequacy.<br><br>Stroke (option A) is part of cardiovascular spectrum but specific category less than overall CV; Infection/sepsis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being most common ESRD dialysis death cause like cardiovascular disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is an endocrine function of the kidney?", "a": "Erythropoietin synthesis", "b": "Glucose reabsorption", "c": "Bicarbonate reabsorption", "d": "Urea excretion", "ans": "A", "e": "Erythropoietin synthesis is endocrine function of kidney; characteristic peritubular interstitial fibroblasts produce EPO in response to hypoxia stimulating red cell production in bone marrow.<br><br>Standard other kidney endocrine functions: renin secretion (juxtaglomerular cells, BP regulation), calcitriol production (1-alpha-hydroxylation of vitamin D), prostaglandin synthesis. Combined with non-endocrine functions: filtration, reabsorption, secretion, acid-base balance.<br><br>Glucose reabsorption (option B) is not the correct choice; Bicarbonate reabsorption (option C) is not the correct choice; Urea excretion (option D) is not the correct choice, none being kidney endocrine function like erythropoietin synthesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Erythropoietin (EPO) is primarily produced by which cells in the kidney?", "a": "Mesangial cells", "b": "Collecting duct cells", "c": "Podocytes", "d": "Peritubular interstitial fibroblasts (cortical)", "ans": "D", "e": "Peritubular interstitial fibroblasts (cortical) primarily produce erythropoietin; characteristic specialised fibroblasts in renal cortex respond to hypoxia through HIF (hypoxia-inducible factor) pathway.<br><br>Standard EPO production mechanism: hypoxia stabilises HIF-2alpha, which upregulates EPO gene transcription in peritubular fibroblasts. Combined with addressing through synthetic ESAs (epoetin alfa, darbepoetin) for anaemia management.<br><br>Mesangial cells (option A) are glomerular structural cells not EPO producers; Collecting duct cells (option B) is not the correct choice; Podocytes (option C) is not the correct choice, none being EPO-producing cells like peritubular interstitial fibroblasts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney converts Vitamin D into its active form. This activation step is:", "a": "1-alpha hydroxylation in the kidney", "b": "25-hydroxylation in the kidney", "c": "Dehydrogenation in the gut", "d": "24-hydroxylation in the liver", "ans": "A", "e": "1-alpha hydroxylation in the kidney activates vitamin D; characteristic conversion of 25-hydroxyvitamin D to active 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D occurs in proximal tubule cells.<br><br>Standard vitamin D activation pathway: cholecalciferol (D3) from skin/diet, hydroxylation to 25-hydroxyvitamin D in liver, 1-alpha-hydroxylation to active calcitriol in kidney. Combined with addressing through PTH stimulation of 1-alpha-hydroxylase.<br><br>25-hydroxylation in the kidney (option B); Dehydrogenation in the gut (option C); 24-hydroxylation in the liver (option D) is not the correct choice, none being vitamin D renal activation like 1-alpha hydroxylation in the kidney.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Active Vitamin D produced by the kidney is called:", "a": "Cholecalciferol", "b": "Calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol)", "c": "Calcidiol", "d": "Ergocalciferol", "ans": "B", "e": "Calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol) is active vitamin D produced by kidney; characteristic 1-alpha-hydroxylation of 25-hydroxyvitamin D produces hormonally active form.<br><br>Standard calcitriol functions: increases intestinal calcium and phosphate absorption, mobilises bone calcium, reduces PTH secretion. Combined with addressing through CKD therapy with calcitriol or analogues (paricalcitol, doxercalciferol) for secondary hyperparathyroidism management.<br><br>Cholecalciferol (option A) is not the correct choice; Calcidiol (option C) is not the correct choice; Ergocalciferol (option D) is not the correct choice, none being kidney active vitamin D form like calcitriol.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which enzyme in the kidney is responsible for activation of Vitamin D?", "a": "Dehydrogenase", "b": "25-hydroxylase", "c": "24-hydroxylase", "d": "1-alpha hydroxylase", "ans": "D", "e": "1-alpha hydroxylase enzyme activates vitamin D in kidney; characteristic proximal tubule enzyme converts 25-hydroxyvitamin D to active calcitriol.<br><br>Standard 1-alpha-hydroxylase regulation: stimulated by PTH, hypocalcaemia, hypophosphataemia; inhibited by FGF-23, calcitriol (negative feedback). Combined with addressing through CKD reducing functional renal mass and 1-alpha-hydroxylase activity contributing to renal osteodystrophy.<br><br>Dehydrogenase (option A) is not the correct choice; 25-hydroxylase (option B) is not the correct choice; 24-hydroxylase (option C) is not the correct choice, none being vitamin D renal activation enzyme like 1-alpha hydroxylase.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney produces renin from which cells?", "a": "Macula densa cells", "b": "Juxtaglomerular (JG) cells", "c": "Mesangial cells", "d": "Podocytes", "ans": "B", "e": "Juxtaglomerular (JG) cells produce renin in kidney; characteristic specialised smooth muscle cells in afferent arteriole wall secrete renin in response to decreased renal perfusion.<br><br>Standard renin secretion triggers: decreased renal perfusion pressure, decreased NaCl delivery to macula densa, sympathetic nervous system stimulation. Combined with renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system: renin activates angiotensinogen to angiotensin I, ACE converts to angiotensin II, stimulates aldosterone.<br><br>Macula densa cells (option A); Mesangial cells (option C) are glomerular structural cells; Podocytes (option D) are glomerular filtration barrier cells, none being renin-producing cells like juxtaglomerular cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Renin secretion is stimulated by all of the following EXCEPT:", "a": "Increased serum potassium", "b": "Decreased NaCl at macula densa", "c": "Decreased renal perfusion pressure", "d": "Sympathetic stimulation (beta-1)", "ans": "A", "e": "Increased serum potassium is NOT renin secretion stimulus; characteristic renin secretion responds to decreased perfusion, decreased NaCl delivery, sympathetic stimulation, while hyperkalaemia directly stimulates aldosterone (not renin).<br><br>Standard renin secretion stimulators: decreased renal perfusion pressure, decreased NaCl delivery to macula densa, sympathetic nervous system. Hyperkalaemia stimulates aldosterone directly from adrenal zona glomerulosa bypassing renin-angiotensin system.<br><br>Decreased NaCl at macula densa (option B) stimulates renin via macula densa mechanism; Decreased renal perfusion pressure (option C); Sympathetic stimulation (beta-1) (option D), none being NOT renin secretion stimulus like increased serum potassium.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney contributes to gluconeogenesis. This function becomes particularly important during:", "a": "Exercise", "b": "Fed state", "c": "Hyperglycaemia", "d": "Prolonged fasting", "ans": "D", "e": "Prolonged fasting makes renal gluconeogenesis matter most; characteristic kidney contribution to glucose production increases significantly during fasting and stress.<br><br>Standard renal gluconeogenesis features: contributes 20-25 percent of total endogenous glucose production during fasting (up from 5-10 percent in fed state), occurs in proximal tubule cells, substrates: lactate, glutamine, glycerol, amino acids. Combined with addressing through liver as primary gluconeogenesis site (75-80 percent).<br><br>Exercise (option A) uses glucose, hepatic gluconeogenesis dominates; Fed state (option B); Hyperglycaemia (option C) suppresses gluconeogenesis, none being renal gluconeogenesis important condition like prolonged fasting.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Prostaglandins produced by the kidney primarily act to:", "a": "Vasodilate renal arterioles and regulate sodium excretion", "b": "Increase aldosterone secretion", "c": "Reduce GFR", "d": "Vasoconstrict renal arterioles", "ans": "A", "e": "Vasodilate renal arterioles and regulate sodium excretion describe renal prostaglandin actions; characteristic prostaglandin E2 and prostacyclin counterbalance vasoconstrictors maintaining renal blood flow.<br><br>Standard renal prostaglandins: produced primarily in medullary interstitial cells, important during volume depletion or renal hypoperfusion. NSAIDs inhibit COX-1 and COX-2 reducing prostaglandin synthesis, may precipitate AKI especially in volume-depleted patients or pre-existing renal disease.<br><br>Increase aldosterone secretion (option B); Reduce GFR (option C); Vasoconstrict renal arterioles (option D) is not the correct choice, none being renal prostaglandin actions like vasodilate renal arterioles and regulate sodium excretion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Bradykinin is degraded by which enzyme also present in the kidney?", "a": "Renin", "b": "Angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE)", "c": "Aldosterone synthase", "d": "Phospholipase A2", "ans": "B", "e": "Angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE) degrades bradykinin in kidney and lungs; characteristic same enzyme that converts angiotensin I to angiotensin II also inactivates bradykinin (a vasodilator).<br><br>Standard ACE actions: converts angiotensin I to angiotensin II (vasoconstrictor), degrades bradykinin (vasodilator). ACE inhibitors block both functions causing accumulation of bradykinin (contributing to cough, angioedema).<br><br>Renin (option A) converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I; Aldosterone synthase (option C) produces aldosterone in adrenal zona glomerulosa; Phospholipase A2 (option D) is not the correct choice, none being bradykinin-degrading enzyme like angiotensin converting enzyme.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is a non-endocrine function of the kidney?", "a": "EPO production", "b": "Calcitriol production", "c": "Renin secretion", "d": "Acid-base regulation", "ans": "D", "e": "Acid-base regulation is non-endocrine function of kidney; characteristic bicarbonate reabsorption and hydrogen ion excretion maintain systemic pH balance.<br><br>Standard kidney acid-base regulation: bicarbonate reabsorption (proximal tubule, 80-90 percent), bicarbonate regeneration (distal nephron through ammoniagenesis and titratable acid excretion). Combined with kidney endocrine functions: renin, EPO, calcitriol, prostaglandins.<br><br>EPO production (option A) is not the correct choice; Calcitriol production (option B) is not the correct choice; Renin secretion (option C) is not the correct choice, none being non-endocrine kidney function like acid-base regulation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney maintains acid-base balance primarily by:", "a": "Producing carbonic anhydrase", "b": "Reabsorbing bicarbonate and excreting hydrogen ions", "c": "Retaining chloride ions", "d": "Excreting CO2", "ans": "B", "e": "Reabsorbing bicarbonate and excreting hydrogen ions maintain acid-base balance in kidney; characteristic combination preserves bicarbonate stores while eliminating fixed acids from metabolism.<br><br>Standard mechanisms: bicarbonate reabsorption (proximal tubule, requires carbonic anhydrase, 80-90 percent of filtered bicarbonate), hydrogen ion secretion (distal nephron), buffering systems (phosphate, ammonia), bicarbonate regeneration (ammoniagenesis in proximal tubule, titratable acid excretion in distal tubule).<br><br>Producing carbonic anhydrase (option A); Retaining chloride ions (option C); Excreting CO2 (option D) is not the correct choice, none being kidney acid-base mechanism like reabsorbing bicarbonate and excreting hydrogen ions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which segment of the nephron is the primary site of bicarbonate reabsorption?", "a": "Collecting duct", "b": "Loop of Henle", "c": "Distal convoluted tubule", "d": "Proximal convoluted tubule", "ans": "D", "e": "Proximal convoluted tubule is primary site of bicarbonate reabsorption; characteristic 80-90 percent of filtered bicarbonate is reclaimed here through carbonic anhydrase-dependent mechanism.<br><br>Standard PCT bicarbonate reabsorption mechanism: H+ secretion via Na+/H+ antiporter combines with HCO3- forming H2CO3, carbonic anhydrase converts to CO2 + H2O, CO2 diffuses into cell, regenerates HCO3- intracellularly, exits via basolateral Na+/HCO3- cotransporter. Combined with carbonic anhydrase inhibitors blocking this process.<br><br>Collecting duct (option A); Loop of Henle (option B); Distal convoluted tubule (option C), none being primary bicarbonate reabsorption site like proximal convoluted tubule.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney excretes nitrogenous waste products. Which is the major nitrogenous waste?", "a": "Urea", "b": "Ammonia", "c": "Creatine", "d": "Uric acid", "ans": "A", "e": "Urea is principal nitrogenous waste product excreted by kidney; characteristic end product of protein catabolism is freely filtered with partial reabsorption.<br><br>Standard urea handling: synthesised in liver from ammonia (urea cycle), freely filtered at glomerulus, 50-60 percent reabsorbed in tubules (passively follows water in proximal tubule, urea recycling in medulla contributes to concentration gradient). BUN/Cr ratio: over 20 in pre-renal, under 15 in intrinsic renal disease.<br><br>Ammonia (option B); Creatine (option C); Uric acid (option D) is not the correct choice, none being principal nitrogenous waste like urea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Osmoregulation by the kidney is primarily controlled by:", "a": "Cortisol", "b": "Aldosterone", "c": "ADH (Vasopressin)", "d": "ANP", "ans": "C", "e": "ADH (vasopressin) primarily controls osmoregulation by kidney; characteristic posterior pituitary hormone increases water reabsorption in collecting ducts maintaining plasma osmolality.<br><br>Standard ADH actions: binds V2 receptors on collecting duct principal cells, inserts aquaporin-2 channels in apical membrane, increases water reabsorption. Triggers: increased plasma osmolality (osmoreceptors in hypothalamus), decreased blood volume/pressure (baroreceptors).<br><br>Cortisol (option A) is glucocorticoid not principal osmoregulator; Aldosterone (option B) regulates sodium and potassium (not osmolality directly); ANP (option D) is not the correct choice, none being principal osmoregulation hormone like ADH.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney regulates blood pressure through all mechanisms EXCEPT:", "a": "Sodium and water balance", "b": "Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System", "c": "Prostaglandin release", "d": "Insulin secretion", "ans": "D", "e": "Insulin secretion is NOT mechanism by which kidney regulates blood pressure; characteristic insulin is pancreatic beta cell function for glucose homeostasis, while kidney BP regulation involves renin-angiotensin, sodium handling, prostaglandins.<br><br>Standard kidney BP regulation mechanisms: renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (vasoconstriction, sodium retention), pressure natriuresis (sodium excretion increases with BP), prostaglandins (vasodilation), kinin-kallikrein system (vasodilation). Combined with addressing through sympathetic nervous system interaction.<br><br>Sodium and water balance (option A); Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System (option B); Prostaglandin release (option C) is not the correct choice, none being NOT kidney BP regulation mechanism like insulin secretion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Tubuloglomerular feedback, a non-endocrine autoregulatory mechanism, involves:", "a": "Mesangial cells contracting", "b": "JG cells sensing pressure", "c": "Macula densa sensing NaCl delivery and adjusting GFR", "d": "Podocytes adjusting filtration", "ans": "C", "e": "Macula densa sensing NaCl delivery and adjusting GFR describes tubuloglomerular feedback; characteristic specialised distal tubule cells detect distal NaCl and modulate afferent arteriolar tone.<br><br>Standard mechanism: increased distal NaCl delivery (high GFR) detected by macula densa, releases adenosine, causes afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction, reduces GFR. Decreased NaCl delivery reduces afferent tone increasing GFR.<br><br>Mesangial cells contracting (option A); JG cells sensing pressure (option B); Podocytes adjusting filtration (option D), none being tubuloglomerular feedback like macula densa sensing NaCl delivery and adjusting GFR.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which non-endocrine function of the kidney is impaired causing anaemia in CKD?", "a": "Iron reabsorption", "b": "Production of EPO (actually endocrine, but EPO deficiency drives anaemia)", "c": "Destruction of old red cells", "d": "Filtration of red cells", "ans": "B", "e": "Production of EPO is impaired in CKD; characteristic declining renal mass reduces erythropoietin production from peritubular fibroblasts producing anaemia.<br><br>Standard CKD-related EPO deficiency features: hypoproliferative normocytic anaemia, worsens with declining GFR (typically apparent at GFR under 60 mL/min), contributes to fatigue, cardiovascular complications. Treatment: erythropoiesis-stimulating agents (epoetin alfa, darbepoetin), iron supplementation, target Hb 10-11.5 g/dL.<br><br>Iron reabsorption (option A); Destruction of old red cells (option C); Filtration of red cells (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD impaired function (often listed) like production of EPO.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The kidney excretes drugs primarily by:", "a": "Glomerular filtration and tubular secretion", "b": "Exhalation", "c": "Biliary excretion", "d": "Sweat excretion", "ans": "A", "e": "Glomerular filtration and tubular secretion primarily excrete drugs through kidney; characteristic two main mechanisms eliminate water-soluble drugs and metabolites.<br><br>Standard drug excretion mechanisms: glomerular filtration (free unbound drug, molecular weight under 60-70 kDa), tubular secretion (active transport via OAT, OCT, P-glycoprotein in proximal tubule), tubular reabsorption (passive, dependent on lipid solubility and pH). Combined with addressing through dose adjustment in renal impairment.<br><br>Exhalation (option B); Biliary excretion (option C); Sweat excretion (option D) is not the correct choice, none being renal drug excretion like glomerular filtration and tubular secretion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Ammoniagenesis in the kidney is important for:", "a": "Protein synthesis", "b": "Glucose production", "c": "Urea cycle completion", "d": "Buffering excreted hydrogen ions in urine", "ans": "D", "e": "Buffering excreted hydrogen ions in urine is importance of ammoniagenesis in kidney; characteristic NH3 production from glutamine in proximal tubule cells combines with H+ to form NH4+ allowing acid excretion.<br><br>Standard ammoniagenesis features: proximal tubule cells convert glutamine to NH3 + alpha-ketoglutarate, NH3 diffuses into tubular lumen, combines with H+ forming NH4+ (trapped in urine), each NH4+ excreted regenerates HCO3-. Upregulated in chronic acidosis.<br><br>Protein synthesis (option A); Glucose production (option B); Urea cycle completion (option C), none being ammoniagenesis importance like buffering excreted hydrogen ions in urine.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of anaemia in CKD includes all EXCEPT:", "a": "Iron supplementation", "b": "Blood transfusion when necessary", "c": "Androgen therapy as first line", "d": "Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents (ESAs)", "ans": "C", "e": "Androgen therapy as first line is NOT used for CKD anaemia management; characteristic outdated approach with significant adverse effects has been replaced by ESAs and iron supplementation.<br><br>Standard CKD anaemia management: erythropoiesis-stimulating agents, iron supplementation, target haemoglobin 10-11.5 g/dL (avoiding higher targets due to cardiovascular risk). Combined with addressing through nutritional support, blood transfusions reserved for symptomatic severe anaemia.<br><br>Iron supplementation (option A) IS adjunct CKD anaemia treatment; Blood transfusion when necessary (option B); Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents (ESAs) (option D), none being NOT CKD anaemia first-line treatment like androgen therapy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Target haemoglobin when using ESAs in CKD is:", "a": "8–9 g/dL", "b": "13–14 g/dL", "c": ">14 g/dL", "d": "10–12 g/dL", "ans": "D", "e": "10-12 g/dL is target haemoglobin with ESAs in CKD; characteristic balancing of symptomatic anaemia treatment with cardiovascular risk avoidance.<br><br>Standard ESA therapy approach: target haemoglobin 10-11.5 g/dL (KDIGO recommends not exceeding 11.5 g/dL), avoiding higher targets due to increased cardiovascular events, thrombosis, stroke (TREAT, CHOIR, CREATE trials). Combined with iron supplementation, monitoring transferrin saturation and ferritin.<br><br>8–9 g/dL (option A); 13–14 g/dL (option B) is not the correct choice; >14 g/dL (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD ESA Hb target like 10-12 g/dL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Excessive correction of anaemia with ESAs in CKD increases the risk of:", "a": "Stroke and cardiovascular events", "b": "Pulmonary fibrosis", "c": "Hyperkalaemia", "d": "Renal failure progression", "ans": "A", "e": "Stroke and cardiovascular events increase with excessive anaemia correction by ESAs in CKD; characteristic higher haemoglobin targets associated with thrombosis, hypertension, cardiovascular mortality.<br><br>Standard evidence: TREAT, CHOIR, CREATE trials showed increased cardiovascular events with Hb targets over 13 g/dL. Mechanisms: hypertension worsening, thrombosis (vascular access, deep vein, stroke), tumour progression.<br><br>Pulmonary fibrosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Hyperkalaemia (option C) is not the correct choice; Renal failure progression (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ESA over-correction risk like stroke and cardiovascular events.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of hyperkalaemia in CKD includes all EXCEPT:", "a": "Dietary potassium restriction", "b": "Avoiding ACE inhibitors if severely elevated", "c": "Potassium exchange resins (patiromer, sodium zirconium cyclosilicate)", "d": "Potassium supplementation", "ans": "D", "e": "Potassium supplementation is NOT used for hyperkalaemia management in CKD; characteristic opposite intervention worsens hyperkalaemia and increases cardiac arrhythmia risk.<br><br>Standard hyperkalaemia management in CKD: dietary potassium restriction, loop diuretics (kaliuretic effect), sodium polystyrene sulfonate (kayexalate) or patiromer (potassium-binding resins), addressing acidosis (sodium bicarbonate), discontinuing potassium-sparing drugs (ACE inhibitors, ARBs, spironolactone) if severe.<br><br>Dietary potassium restriction (option A) IS hyperkalaemia treatment; Avoiding ACE inhibitors if severely elevated (option B); Potassium exchange resins (patiromer, sodium zirconium cyclosilicate) (option C), none being NOT hyperkalaemia management like potassium supplementation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is used as an emergency treatment for hyperkalaemia in CKD?", "a": "Oral fludrocortisone", "b": "IV calcium gluconate (to stabilize cardiac membrane)", "c": "Thiazide diuretics", "d": "Sodium polystyrene sulfonate alone", "ans": "B", "e": "IV calcium gluconate stabilises cardiac membrane in emergency hyperkalaemia treatment; characteristic membrane stabilisation antagonises hyperkalaemia effects without lowering potassium.<br><br>Standard emergency hyperkalaemia management: calcium gluconate (10 mL of 10 percent IV over 2-3 minutes, immediate membrane stabilisation), insulin plus glucose (shifts K intracellularly), salbutamol nebulisation (beta-2 agonist shifts K intracellularly), sodium bicarbonate (if acidotic), kayexalate or dialysis (removes K).<br><br>Oral fludrocortisone (option A); Thiazide diuretics (option C); Sodium polystyrene sulfonate alone (option D) is not the correct choice, none being emergency hyperkalaemia membrane stabilisation like IV calcium gluconate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Treatment of metabolic acidosis in CKD involves:", "a": "Acetazolamide", "b": "IV potassium chloride", "c": "Oral sodium bicarbonate supplementation", "d": "Hyperventilation therapy", "ans": "C", "e": "Oral sodium bicarbonate supplementation treats metabolic acidosis in CKD; characteristic exogenous bicarbonate replaces lost bicarbonate slowing CKD progression.<br><br>Standard sodium bicarbonate therapy: target serum bicarbonate over 22 mEq/L, typical dose 0.5-1 mEq/kg/day, available as oral tablets (650 mg = 7.7 mEq) or IV solutions. Benefits: slows CKD progression, improves bone metabolism, reduces muscle wasting.<br><br>Acetazolamide (option A); IV potassium chloride (option B) is not the correct choice; Hyperventilation therapy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD metabolic acidosis treatment like oral sodium bicarbonate supplementation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Sodium bicarbonate therapy in CKD is recommended when serum bicarbonate falls below:", "a": "18 mEq/L", "b": "15 mEq/L", "c": "28 mEq/L", "d": "22 mEq/L", "ans": "D", "e": "22 mEq/L serum bicarbonate threshold initiates sodium bicarbonate therapy in CKD; characteristic intervention level for chronic metabolic acidosis management.<br><br>Standard KDIGO recommendation: sodium bicarbonate supplementation when serum bicarbonate falls below 22 mEq/L to slow CKD progression. Target: maintain serum bicarbonate over 22 mEq/L. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>18 mEq/L (option A) is not the correct choice; 15 mEq/L (option B) is not the correct choice; 28 mEq/L (option C) is not the correct choice, none being CKD bicarbonate therapy threshold like 22 mEq/L.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of hyperphosphataemia in CKD includes all EXCEPT:", "a": "Dietary phosphate restriction", "b": "Sevelamer", "c": "Calcium supplementation in high doses without regard to phosphate levels", "d": "Calcium carbonate (phosphate binder)", "ans": "C", "e": "Calcium supplementation in high doses without regard to phosphate is NOT used for hyperphosphataemia in CKD; characteristic approach worsens calcium-phosphate product elevation increasing vascular calcification risk.<br><br>Standard hyperphosphataemia management: dietary phosphate restriction, phosphate binders with meals (calcium-based with caution, sevelamer, lanthanum, iron-based), addressing secondary hyperparathyroidism (cinacalcet, active vitamin D). Combined with addressing through balancing calcium intake.<br><br>Dietary phosphate restriction (option A) IS hyperphosphataemia management; Sevelamer (option B); Calcium carbonate (phosphate binder) (option D), none being NOT CKD hyperphosphataemia management like high-dose calcium without regard to phosphate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Sevelamer is preferred over calcium-based phosphate binders because it:", "a": "Has fewer gastrointestinal side effects", "b": "Does not cause hypercalcaemia and may reduce cardiovascular calcification", "c": "Increases PTH levels", "d": "Is cheaper", "ans": "B", "e": "Sevelamer does not cause hypercalcaemia and may reduce cardiovascular calcification; characteristic non-calcium-based phosphate binder avoids calcium loading advantages in vascular health.<br><br>Standard sevelamer features: hydrochloride or carbonate forms, binds dietary phosphate in gut, also reduces LDL cholesterol, may reduce vascular calcification progression compared to calcium-based binders. Combined with addressing through dose 800-3200 mg with meals, side effects.<br><br>Has fewer gastrointestinal side effects (option A); Increases PTH levels (option C); Is cheaper (option D), none being sevelamer advantage like does not cause hypercalcaemia and may reduce cardiovascular calcification.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Secondary hyperparathyroidism in CKD is managed by:", "a": "Calcium restriction alone", "b": "Thiazide diuretics", "c": "Active Vitamin D (calcitriol), calcimimetics (cinacalcet), phosphate binders", "d": "Parathyroidectomy alone in all cases", "ans": "C", "e": "Active vitamin D (calcitriol) and calcimimetics (cinacalcet) manage secondary hyperparathyroidism in CKD; characteristic combination addresses PTH secretion through different mechanisms.<br><br>Standard secondary hyperparathyroidism management: phosphate control (binders, dietary restriction), active vitamin D analogues (calcitriol, paricalcitol, doxercalciferol), calcimimetics (cinacalcet, etelcalcetide - increase sensitivity of calcium-sensing receptor reducing PTH). Combined with addressing through parathyroidectomy in severe refractory cases.<br><br>Calcium restriction alone (option A); Thiazide diuretics (option B); Parathyroidectomy alone in all cases (option D) is not the correct choice, none being secondary hyperparathyroidism management like active vitamin D and calcimimetics.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Cinacalcet works in CKD by:", "a": "Blocking PTH receptors in bone", "b": "Supplementing calcium", "c": "Inhibiting 1-alpha hydroxylase", "d": "Increasing sensitivity of calcium-sensing receptors in parathyroid gland, reducing PTH", "ans": "D", "e": "Increasing sensitivity of calcium-sensing receptor on parathyroid cells is mechanism of cinacalcet in CKD; characteristic calcimimetic action reduces PTH secretion without raising calcium.<br><br>Standard cinacalcet features: allosteric modulator of calcium-sensing receptor (CaSR) on parathyroid chief cells, sensitises receptor to ambient calcium, reduces PTH secretion. Indications: secondary hyperparathyroidism in dialysis patients (PTH consistently over 300 pg/mL), parathyroid carcinoma.<br><br>Blocking PTH receptors in bone (option A); Supplementing calcium (option B); Inhibiting 1-alpha hydroxylase (option C) is not the correct choice, none being cinacalcet mechanism like increasing sensitivity of calcium-sensing receptor.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Pruritus (itch) in CKD is managed by all EXCEPT:", "a": "Gabapentin", "b": "High-dose aspirin", "c": "Antihistamines", "d": "Optimizing dialysis adequacy", "ans": "B", "e": "High-dose aspirin is NOT used for pruritus in CKD; characteristic NSAID use is generally avoided in CKD and lacks efficacy for uraemic pruritus.<br><br>Standard CKD pruritus management: optimising dialysis adequacy, addressing hyperphosphataemia, topical emollients, antihistamines (limited efficacy), gabapentin or pregabalin (effective), naltrexone (mu-opioid antagonist), difelikefalin (kappa-opioid agonist, newer approved drug), UV-B phototherapy, addressing iron deficiency.<br><br>Gabapentin (option A) IS effective CKD pruritus treatment; Antihistamines (option C) IS used (limited efficacy); Optimizing dialysis adequacy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being NOT CKD pruritus management like high-dose aspirin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A newer drug approved specifically for uraemic pruritus in dialysis patients is:", "a": "Difelikefalin (kappa-opioid receptor agonist)", "b": "Pregabalin", "c": "Ondansetron", "d": "Naltrexone", "ans": "A", "e": "Difelikefalin (kappa-opioid receptor agonist) is newer drug approved specifically for uraemic pruritus; characteristic peripherally-acting kappa-opioid agonist reduces itch sensation.<br><br>Standard difelikefalin features: peripherally-restricted (does not cross blood-brain barrier minimising CNS side effects), IV administration during dialysis sessions, approved 2021 for moderate-to-severe pruritus in haemodialysis patients. Combined with addressing through other modalities (optimising dialysis, gabapentin, addressing phosphate).<br><br>Pregabalin (option B) is not the correct choice; Ondansetron (option C) is not the correct choice; Naltrexone (option D) is not the correct choice, none being uraemic pruritus newer specific drug like difelikefalin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Fluid overload in CKD is managed by:", "a": "Thiazide diuretics as first choice at low GFR", "b": "Loop diuretics and fluid restriction", "c": "Increased sodium intake", "d": "Spironolactone as first line", "ans": "B", "e": "Loop diuretics and fluid restriction manage fluid overload in CKD; characteristic combination removes excess fluid while limiting further accumulation.<br><br>Standard fluid overload management in CKD: loop diuretics, fluid restriction (typically 1-1.5 L/day if symptomatic), sodium restriction (under 2 g/day), addressing underlying causes (heart failure, hypertension). Combined with addressing through dialysis with ultrafiltration in ESRD.<br><br>Thiazide diuretics as first choice at low GFR (option A); Increased sodium intake (option C); Spironolactone as first line (option D), none being CKD fluid overload management like loop diuretics and fluid restriction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hypertension management in CKD preferably includes which drug class as first line when proteinuria is present?", "a": "RAAS blockade (ACE inhibitors/ARBs)", "b": "Beta-blockers", "c": "Calcium channel blockers", "d": "Alpha-blockers", "ans": "A", "e": "RAAS blockade (ACE inhibitors/ARBs) is preferred hypertension management in CKD; characteristic reduction in proteinuria and intraglomerular pressure slows progression.<br><br>Standard CKD hypertension treatment: ACE inhibitors/ARBs (first-line, especially with proteinuria), addressing through second-line agents (calcium channel blockers, thiazide diuretics in early CKD, loop diuretics in advanced CKD, beta blockers). Combined with addressing through lifestyle modifications, BP target under 130/80 mmHg with proteinuria.<br><br>Beta-blockers (option B); Calcium channel blockers (option C); Alpha-blockers (option D) is not the correct choice, none being preferred CKD hypertension management like RAAS blockade.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Indications for initiation of RRT in CKD include all EXCEPT:", "a": "Uraemic pericarditis", "b": "Serum creatinine of 2 mg/dL alone", "c": "Uraemic encephalopathy", "d": "Refractory hyperkalaemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Serum creatinine of 2 mg/dL alone is NOT indication for RRT initiation; characteristic isolated creatinine level without symptoms or complications does not require dialysis.<br><br>Standard RRT initiation indications: Acidosis, Electrolytes (refractory hyperkalaemia), Intoxications (specific poisonings), Overload (refractory fluid overload, pulmonary oedema), Uraemia (encephalopathy, pericarditis, bleeding, severe symptoms). Combined with addressing through GFR-based timing (typically GFR 5-10 mL/min in stable patients).<br><br>Uraemic pericarditis (option A) IS RRT indication; Uraemic encephalopathy (option C); Refractory hyperkalaemia (option D) IS RRT indication, none being NOT RRT indication like serum creatinine of 2 mg/dL alone.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The mnemonic “AEIOU” for dialysis indications stands for:", "a": "Acidosis, Enzymes, Infection, Output, Uraemia", "b": "Acidosis, Erythropoietin, Ions, Overload, Urea", "c": "Acidosis, Electrolytes, Intoxication, Overload, Uraemia", "d": "Anaemia, Electrolytes, Intoxication, Oedema, Urea", "ans": "C", "e": "Acidosis, Electrolytes, Intoxication, Overload, Uraemia describe AEIOU mnemonic for dialysis indications; characteristic memory aid covers key emergency RRT triggers.<br><br>Standard AEIOU details: Acidosis (pH under 7.1-7.2 refractory to medical management), Electrolytes (refractory hyperkalaemia, severe hypernatraemia or hyponatraemia), Intoxications (lithium, methanol, ethylene glycol, salicylates, theophylline), Overload (pulmonary oedema refractory to diuretics), Uraemia (encephalopathy, pericarditis, bleeding, severe symptoms).<br><br>Acidosis, Enzymes, Infection, Output, Uraemia (option A); Acidosis, Erythropoietin, Ions, Overload, Urea (option B); Anaemia, Electrolytes, Intoxication, Oedema, Urea (option D), none being AEIOU dialysis indication mnemonic like Acidosis, Electrolytes, Intoxication, Overload, Uraemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Haemodialysis works primarily on the principle of:", "a": "Diffusion across a semipermeable membrane", "b": "Convection only", "c": "Osmosis", "d": "Active transport", "ans": "A", "e": "Diffusion across semipermeable membrane is primary haemodialysis principle; characteristic concentration gradient drives solute movement from blood to dialysate.<br><br>Standard haemodialysis principles: diffusion (small molecules like urea, creatinine, potassium follow concentration gradient), ultrafiltration (water and solutes by hydrostatic pressure gradient), convection (solvent drag carries solutes with bulk fluid movement). Combined with anticoagulation (heparin), bicarbonate-based dialysate, counter-current flow.<br><br>Convection only (option B); Osmosis (option C) is not the correct choice; Active transport (option D) is not the correct choice, none being primary haemodialysis principle like diffusion across semipermeable membrane.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The dialysate used in haemodialysis flows in which direction relative to blood?", "a": "Perpendicular direction", "b": "Same direction (co-current)", "c": "Direction doesn’t matter", "d": "Opposite direction (counter-current)", "ans": "D", "e": "Opposite direction (counter-current) flow describes dialysate flow in haemodialysis; characteristic arrangement maximises concentration gradient throughout dialyser improving solute clearance.<br><br>Standard counter-current flow benefits: maintains concentration gradient along entire dialyser length, blood flow 300-500 mL/min, dialysate flow 500-800 mL/min, opposing flow directions optimise efficiency. Combined with addressing through dialyser membrane characteristics (high-flux vs low-flux, biocompatibility).<br><br>Perpendicular direction (option A); Same direction (co-current) (option B) is less efficient than counter-current; Direction doesn’t matter (option C) is not the correct choice, none being haemodialysis dialysate flow direction like opposite (counter-current).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "What is “dialysis disequilibrium syndrome”?", "a": "Cardiovascular collapse during dialysis", "b": "Air embolism during dialysis", "c": "Neurological complication due to rapid osmotic shifts during dialysis causing cerebral oedema", "d": "Electrolyte imbalance after dialysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Neurological complication due to rapid osmotic shifts describes dialysis disequilibrium syndrome; characteristic cerebral oedema from rapid urea removal causes neurological symptoms.<br><br>Standard DDS features: headache, nausea, vomiting, confusion, seizures, coma in severe cases. Mechanism: rapid removal of urea from blood while brain urea slower to equilibrate, creating osmotic gradient drawing water into brain.<br><br>Cardiovascular collapse during dialysis (option A); Air embolism during dialysis (option B); Electrolyte imbalance after dialysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being dialysis disequilibrium syndrome like neurological complication due to rapid osmotic shifts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Continuous Renal Replacement Therapy (CRRT) is preferred over intermittent haemodialysis in:", "a": "Haemodynamically unstable critically ill patients", "b": "Peritoneal dialysis failures", "c": "Stable outpatient CKD", "d": "Patients with AV fistula", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemodynamically unstable critically ill patients are preferred for continuous renal replacement therapy (CRRT); characteristic slow continuous fluid and solute removal better tolerated than intermittent haemodialysis in unstable patients.<br><br>Standard CRRT features: continuous 24-hour treatment, slow blood flow (150-200 mL/min), continuous ultrafiltration, modalities (CVVH, CVVHD, CVVHDF). Indications: ICU patients with haemodynamic instability, severe fluid overload, high catabolic state, multiple organ failure.<br><br>Peritoneal dialysis failures (option B); Stable outpatient CKD (option C); Patients with AV fistula (option D), none being CRRT preferred population like haemodynamically unstable critically ill patients.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most serious complication of AV fistula creation for haemodialysis is:", "a": "Thrombosis", "b": "Aneurysm formation", "c": "Infection", "d": "Steal syndrome (vascular steal causing hand ischaemia)", "ans": "D", "e": "Steal syndrome (vascular steal causing hand ischaemia) is most serious AV fistula complication; characteristic diversion of blood through fistula reduces distal perfusion to hand.<br><br>Standard AV fistula complications: stenosis (most common), thrombosis, infection, aneurysm formation, steal syndrome (5-10 percent, can cause severe hand ischaemia requiring intervention), high-output cardiac failure (large fistulas), peripheral neuropathy. Treatment of steal: distal revascularisation interval ligation (DRIL), banding, fistula ligation.<br><br>Thrombosis (option A); Aneurysm formation (option B); Infection (option C) is not the correct choice, none being most serious AV fistula complication like steal syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Peritoneal dialysis (PD) uses which solution as the osmotic agent to drive fluid removal?", "a": "Glucose (dextrose)", "b": "Albumin", "c": "Mannitol", "d": "Saline", "ans": "A", "e": "Glucose (dextrose) is osmotic agent in peritoneal dialysis; characteristic hyperosmolar dialysate draws fluid from blood across peritoneal membrane.<br><br>Standard PD solutions: glucose-based (1.5 percent, 2.5 percent, 4.25 percent dextrose, providing osmotic gradient for ultrafiltration), icodextrin-based (glucose polymer, longer ultrafiltration for long dwells), amino acid-based (for nutrition). Combined with addressing through buffer (lactate or bicarbonate), electrolytes (sodium, calcium, magnesium).<br><br>Albumin (option B); Mannitol (option C) is not standard PD osmotic agent; Saline (option D) is not the correct choice, none being PD osmotic agent like glucose (dextrose).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Automated Peritoneal Dialysis (APD) differs from CAPD in that:", "a": "APD is performed manually during the day", "b": "APD uses a machine to perform exchanges overnight", "c": "APD has higher infection rates", "d": "APD uses glucose-free solutions", "ans": "B", "e": "APD uses a machine to perform exchanges overnight differing from CAPD; characteristic automated cycler enables nocturnal exchanges allowing daytime freedom.<br><br>Standard APD features: automated cycler machine performs multiple exchanges overnight (typically 8-10 hours, 4-6 exchanges), daytime dwell with longer exchange. Combined with CAPD: continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis, 4 manual exchanges per day, no machine required.<br><br>APD is performed manually during the day (option A); APD has higher infection rates (option C); APD uses glucose-free solutions (option D), none being APD vs CAPD difference like APD uses machine for overnight exchanges.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Contraindications to peritoneal dialysis include:", "a": "Previous abdominal surgeries causing extensive adhesions", "b": "Diabetes mellitus", "c": "Hypertension", "d": "Elderly age", "ans": "A", "e": "Previous abdominal surgeries causing extensive adhesions contraindicate peritoneal dialysis; characteristic impaired peritoneal membrane access and surface area precludes effective dialysis.<br><br>Standard PD contraindications: extensive abdominal adhesions, large abdominal hernias (unrepaired), inflammatory bowel disease (active), abdominal wall stomas, severe COPD (diaphragmatic compromise), patient inability to perform exchanges, lack of suitable home environment. Combined with addressing through alternative RRT (haemodialysis, transplant).<br><br>Diabetes mellitus (option B) is not PD contraindication (PD often suitable); Hypertension (option C); Elderly age (option D), none being PD contraindication like previous abdominal surgeries with extensive adhesions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Adequacy of haemodialysis is measured by:", "a": "Serum creatinine level only", "b": "Blood pressure control", "c": "Urine output", "d": "Kt/V (urea kinetic modelling) with target Kt/V ≥1.2", "ans": "D", "e": "Kt/V (urea kinetic modelling) with target over 1.2 measures haemodialysis adequacy; characteristic mathematical model quantifies fractional urea clearance per session.<br><br>Standard Kt/V calculation: K (dialyser urea clearance) x t (treatment time) divided by V (urea distribution volume). Target single-pool Kt/V over 1.2 per session (3 sessions/week).<br><br>Serum creatinine level only (option A) is not the correct choice; Blood pressure control (option B) is not the correct choice; Urine output (option C) is not the correct choice, none being haemodialysis adequacy measure like Kt/V with target over 1.2.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is an advantage of peritoneal dialysis over haemodialysis?", "a": "No dietary restrictions required", "b": "Better clearance of large molecules", "c": "Better preservation of residual renal function and home-based therapy", "d": "No risk of peritonitis", "ans": "C", "e": "Better preservation of residual renal function and haemodynamic stability are advantages of peritoneal dialysis; characteristic gentler continuous treatment benefits compared to intermittent haemodialysis.<br><br>Standard PD advantages: home-based therapy, better preservation of residual renal function and haemodynamic stability, no anticoagulation, preserved vascular access. Disadvantages: peritonitis risk, ultrafiltration failure over time.<br><br>No dietary restrictions required (option A); Better clearance of large molecules (option B); No risk of peritonitis (option D), none being PD advantage like better preservation of residual renal function and haemodynamic stability.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Kidney transplantation is considered the gold standard for RRT because it:", "a": "Provides best quality of life and survival compared to dialysis", "b": "Is available for all ESRD patients", "c": "Has no risk of rejection", "d": "Eliminates all immunosuppression needs", "ans": "A", "e": "Provides best quality of life and survival compared to dialysis describes kidney transplantation gold standard status; characteristic restoration of renal function offers superior outcomes.<br><br>Standard transplant advantages: improved survival vs dialysis, better quality of life, freedom from dialysis sessions, correction of anaemia and renal osteodystrophy. Disadvantages: surgery risks, immunosuppression complications.<br><br>Is available for all ESRD patients (option B); Has no risk of rejection (option C); Eliminates all immunosuppression needs (option D), none being transplantation gold standard like provides best quality of life and survival.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common cause of long-term kidney transplant failure (beyond 1 year) is:", "a": "Hyperacute rejection", "b": "Chronic allograft nephropathy", "c": "Acute rejection episodes", "d": "Infection", "ans": "B", "e": "Chronic allograft nephropathy is most common cause of long-term kidney transplant failure; characteristic combination of immunological injury, calcineurin inhibitor toxicity, and ageing produces progressive graft dysfunction.<br><br>Standard chronic allograft nephropathy features: progressive interstitial fibrosis, tubular atrophy, vasculopathy, glomerulosclerosis. Multifactorial: chronic immunological injury, calcineurin inhibitor (tacrolimus, ciclosporin) nephrotoxicity, BK virus infection, recurrent disease, donor factors.<br><br>Hyperacute rejection (option A); Acute rejection episodes (option C) is not the correct choice; Infection (option D) is significant cause but not most common long-term failure, none being long-term transplant failure cause like chronic allograft nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which immunosuppressive agent is used as the backbone of most kidney transplant regimens?", "a": "Calcineurin inhibitors (Tacrolimus or Cyclosporine)", "b": "Mycophenolate mofetil", "c": "Azathioprine", "d": "Sirolimus", "ans": "A", "e": "Calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus or ciclosporin) are backbone of maintenance immunosuppression in kidney transplantation; characteristic inhibition of T-cell activation prevents rejection.<br><br>Standard maintenance immunosuppression triple therapy: calcineurin inhibitor (tacrolimus preferred over ciclosporin), antimetabolite (mycophenolate mofetil or azathioprine), corticosteroid (prednisolone, often weaned). Combined with addressing through induction therapy (basiliximab or thymoglobulin), monitoring drug levels, surveillance for rejection, infection, malignancy.<br><br>Mycophenolate mofetil (option B) is not the correct choice; Azathioprine (option C) is not the correct choice; Sirolimus (option D) is not the correct choice, none being transplant immunosuppression backbone like calcineurin inhibitors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The primary rationale for dialysis in renal failure is to:", "a": "Increase urine output permanently", "b": "Artificially replace the excretory and regulatory functions of failed kidneys", "c": "Stimulate regeneration of nephrons", "d": "Restore kidney architecture", "ans": "B", "e": "Artificially replace excretory and regulatory functions of failed kidneys is rationale for dialysis; characteristic substitution of solute clearance, fluid removal, and electrolyte/acid-base balance restores homeostasis.<br><br>Standard dialysis functions: removes nitrogenous waste (urea, creatinine), removes uraemic toxins, corrects electrolyte abnormalities (hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia), corrects acid-base disturbances, removes excess fluid (ultrafiltration). Combined with addressing through inability to replace endocrine functions (EPO, calcitriol).<br><br>Increase urine output permanently (option A); Stimulate regeneration of nephrons (option C); Restore kidney architecture (option D), none being dialysis primary rationale like artificially replace excretory and regulatory functions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following best describes the principle of diffusion in dialysis?", "a": "Active transport of urea across tubular cells", "b": "Movement of solutes from low to high concentration across a membrane", "c": "Movement of solutes from high to low concentration across a semipermeable membrane", "d": "Movement of water against an osmotic gradient", "ans": "C", "e": "Movement of solutes from high to low concentration describes diffusion principle in dialysis; characteristic concentration gradient drives passive solute transport across semipermeable membrane.<br><br>Standard diffusion features: small molecules cross membrane down concentration gradient, larger molecules cross less efficiently. Driving forces: gradient, surface area, membrane characteristics.<br><br>Active transport of urea across tubular cells (option A); Movement of solutes from low to high concentration across a membrane (option B); Movement of water against an osmotic gradient (option D), none being dialysis diffusion principle like movement of solutes from high to low concentration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Ultrafiltration in dialysis refers to:", "a": "Removal of excess fluid by applying a pressure gradient across the membrane", "b": "Removal of large proteins from blood", "c": "Removal of solutes by diffusion", "d": "Filtration of blood through the glomerulus", "ans": "A", "e": "Removal of excess fluid by applying pressure gradient describes ultrafiltration in dialysis; characteristic transmembrane pressure drives water and small solutes from blood to dialysate.<br><br>Standard ultrafiltration features: transmembrane pressure created by negative dialysate or positive blood pressure, removes excess fluid (2-4 kg per session). Combined with monitoring dry weight, avoiding excessive removal.<br><br>Removal of large proteins from blood (option B); Removal of solutes by diffusion (option C); Filtration of blood through the glomerulus (option D), none being ultrafiltration in dialysis like removal of excess fluid by applying pressure gradient.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Convection in dialysis (as used in haemofiltration) involves:", "a": "Osmotic removal of water", "b": "Diffusion of solutes down concentration gradients", "c": "Active transport of toxins", "d": "Solute removal by “solvent drag” alongside bulk fluid movement", "ans": "D", "e": "Solute removal by solvent drag alongside bulk fluid movement describes convection in dialysis; characteristic mechanism removes middle molecules more efficiently than pure diffusion.<br><br>Standard convection features: bulk water movement carries dissolved solutes, removes middle molecules (beta-2 microglobulin, 11 kDa) more efficiently than diffusion. Used in haemofiltration (CVVH), haemodiafiltration (CVVHDF combines diffusion and convection), high-flux haemodialysis.<br><br>Osmotic removal of water (option A); Diffusion of solutes down concentration gradients (option B); Active transport of toxins (option C), none being convection in dialysis like solute removal by solvent drag alongside bulk fluid movement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The semipermeable membrane used in haemodialysis allows passage of:", "a": "Small solutes and water but not large proteins or blood cells", "b": "All plasma proteins", "c": "Red blood cells and platelets", "d": "Only water molecules", "ans": "A", "e": "Small solutes and water but not large proteins or cells pass through haemodialysis semipermeable membrane; characteristic size-selective pores allow targeted solute removal while preserving plasma proteins and cells.<br><br>Standard membrane features: low-flux, high-flux, biocompatible synthetic materials (polysulfone, polyethersulfone), pore sizes determining clearance. Combined with addressing through dialyser selection based on patient needs.<br><br>All plasma proteins (option B); Red blood cells and platelets (option C); Only water molecules (option D), none being haemodialysis membrane permeability like small solutes and water but not large proteins or cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following uraemic toxins is most effectively cleared by dialysis?", "a": "Lipid-soluble toxins", "b": "Protein-bound toxins (e.g., indoxyl sulfate)", "c": "Small water-soluble molecules such as urea and creatinine", "d": "Beta-2 microglobulin exclusively", "ans": "C", "e": "Small water-soluble molecules such as urea and creatinine are most effectively removed by conventional haemodialysis; characteristic small size and water solubility maximise diffusion across membrane.<br><br>Standard well-removed solutes: urea (60 Da), creatinine (113 Da), potassium, phosphate (97 Da), small organic acids. Less well-removed: middle molecules (beta-2 microglobulin 11 kDa - better with high-flux), protein-bound toxins (p-cresyl sulfate, indoxyl sulfate - poorly removed), large proteins.<br><br>Lipid-soluble toxins (option A); Protein-bound toxins (e.g., indoxyl sulfate) (option B); Beta-2 microglobulin exclusively (option D), none being well-removed by haemodialysis like small water-soluble molecules.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The counter-current flow arrangement in haemodialysis is used to:", "a": "Reduce blood pressure during dialysis", "b": "Prevent haemolysis", "c": "Prevent clotting in the circuit", "d": "Maximize concentration gradient and efficiency of solute removal throughout the dialyser", "ans": "D", "e": "Maximise concentration gradient and efficiency of clearance is purpose of counter-current flow in haemodialysis; characteristic opposing blood and dialysate flow maintains gradient along entire dialyser length.<br><br>Standard counter-current advantages: blood flows one direction through hollow fibres, dialysate flows opposite direction outside fibres, maintains concentration gradient throughout dialyser. Combined with optimising blood flow 300-500 mL/min, dialysate flow 500-800 mL/min.<br><br>Reduce blood pressure during dialysis (option A); Prevent haemolysis (option B); Prevent clotting in the circuit (option C), none being counter-current flow purpose like maximise concentration gradient and efficiency of clearance.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is NOT removed effectively by conventional haemodialysis?", "a": "Bicarbonate replenishment", "b": "Protein-bound uraemic toxins (e.g., p-cresyl sulfate)", "c": "Potassium", "d": "Urea", "ans": "B", "e": "Protein-bound uraemic toxins (e.g. p-cresyl sulfate, indoxyl sulfate) are NOT effectively removed by conventional haemodialysis; characteristic albumin binding limits diffusion across dialyser membrane.<br><br>Standard protein-bound toxins: p-cresyl sulfate, indoxyl sulfate, hippuric acid - generated by gut microbiota metabolism. Poorly removed because albumin-bound fraction does not diffuse easily. Combined with cardiovascular and inflammatory consequences.<br><br>Bicarbonate replenishment (option A) is not the correct choice; Potassium (option C) is well removed (small ion); Urea (option D) is well removed (small, free), none being NOT well-removed by conventional haemodialysis like protein-bound uraemic toxins.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Peritoneal dialysis utilizes which membrane as the dialysing surface?", "a": "The peritoneum (visceral and parietal)", "b": "Synthetic polysulfone membrane", "c": "The glomerular basement membrane", "d": "Cellulose acetate membrane", "ans": "A", "e": "The peritoneum (visceral and parietal) is dialysing membrane in peritoneal dialysis; characteristic natural semipermeable membrane allows solute and fluid exchange with dialysate in peritoneal cavity.<br><br>Standard peritoneal membrane features: surface area approximately 1-2 m2, blood supply from mesenteric vessels, three-pore model. Combined with peritoneal transport characterisation (peritoneal equilibration test - PET, classifying as high, high-average, low-average, low transporters).<br><br>Synthetic polysulfone membrane (option B); The glomerular basement membrane (option C); Cellulose acetate membrane (option D), none being PD dialysing membrane like peritoneum (visceral and parietal).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The rationale for using glucose (dextrose) in peritoneal dialysis fluid is:", "a": "To buffer metabolic acidosis", "b": "To provide nutrition to the patient", "c": "To prevent bacterial growth", "d": "To create an osmotic gradient that drives fluid removal from blood into dialysate", "ans": "D", "e": "Create an osmotic gradient that drives fluid removal is rationale for glucose (dextrose) in peritoneal dialysis solution; characteristic hyperosmolar glucose attracts water from blood across peritoneal membrane.<br><br>Standard glucose concentrations: 1.5 percent (mild ultrafiltration), 2.5 percent (moderate), 4.25 percent (high ultrafiltration). Higher concentrations achieve more ultrafiltration but increase glucose absorption (contributing to hyperglycaemia, weight gain, dyslipidaemia).<br><br>To buffer metabolic acidosis (option A); To provide nutrition to the patient (option B); To prevent bacterial growth (option C), none being PD glucose rationale like creating osmotic gradient for fluid removal.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Metabolic acidosis is an indication for dialysis when:", "a": "Severe refractory metabolic acidosis with pH <7.1–7.2 not responding to medical therapy", "b": "pH is 7.35", "c": "PaCO2 is elevated", "d": "Serum bicarbonate is 20 mEq/L", "ans": "A", "e": "Severe refractory metabolic acidosis with pH under 7.1-7.2 is dialysis indication; characteristic life-threatening acidosis unresponsive to bicarbonate therapy requires renal replacement.<br><br>Standard severe acidosis features: pH under 7.1-7.2 refractory to bicarbonate, often combined with other complications (hyperkalaemia, fluid overload, uraemia). Combined with mechanisms in CKD: impaired hydrogen ion excretion, bicarbonate loss, accumulation of organic acids.<br><br>pH is 7.35 (option B); PaCO2 is elevated (option C); Serum bicarbonate is 20 mEq/L (option D) is not the correct choice, none being metabolic acidosis dialysis indication like severe refractory with pH under 7.1-7.2.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In CKD, metabolic acidosis develops primarily because of:", "a": "Excessive CO2 production", "b": "Increased lactic acid production", "c": "Loss of bicarbonate in stools", "d": "Failure of kidneys to excrete hydrogen ions and regenerate bicarbonate", "ans": "D", "e": "Failure of kidneys to excrete hydrogen ions and regenerate bicarbonate primarily causes metabolic acidosis in CKD; characteristic impaired acid excretion combined with reduced bicarbonate regeneration produces acidaemia.<br><br>Standard CKD acidosis mechanisms: reduced ammoniagenesis, reduced titratable acid excretion, accumulation of organic acids, bicarbonate loss. Combined with addressing through sodium bicarbonate supplementation, addressing through dialysis if severe.<br><br>Excessive CO2 production (option A); Increased lactic acid production (option B); Loss of bicarbonate in stools (option C), none being CKD metabolic acidosis cause like failure to excrete hydrogen ions and regenerate bicarbonate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Before initiating dialysis for acidosis, which medical treatment should be attempted?", "a": "IV potassium chloride", "b": "Calcium gluconate infusion", "c": "Oral or IV sodium bicarbonate supplementation", "d": "Hyperventilation via mechanical ventilation", "ans": "C", "e": "Oral or IV sodium bicarbonate supplementation should be tried before dialysis for acidosis; characteristic medical management addresses chronic acidosis without requiring dialysis.<br><br>Standard sodium bicarbonate approach: oral therapy for chronic CKD acidosis, IV bicarbonate for severe acute acidosis. Combined with addressing through monitoring response, sodium load complications (worsening hypertension and oedema), persisting need despite optimisation suggests dialysis requirement.<br><br>IV potassium chloride (option A); Calcium gluconate infusion (option B); Hyperventilation via mechanical ventilation (option D), none being pre-dialysis acidosis medical management like oral or IV sodium bicarbonate supplementation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The type of acidosis seen in CKD that warrants dialysis is:", "a": "Lactic acidosis from metformin", "b": "Respiratory acidosis", "c": "Hyperchloraemic non-anion gap acidosis only", "d": "High anion gap metabolic acidosis due to retained acid", "ans": "D", "e": "High anion gap metabolic acidosis due to retained organic acids warrants dialysis in CKD; characteristic accumulation of unmeasured anions reflects severe renal dysfunction.<br><br>Standard CKD acidosis evolution: early CKD shows normal anion gap acidosis, advanced CKD shows high anion gap acidosis. Combined with addressing through sodium bicarbonate, dialysis for severe refractory acidosis, addressing through correction of complications.<br><br>Lactic acidosis from metformin (option A); Respiratory acidosis (option B); Hyperchloraemic non-anion gap acidosis only (option C), none being CKD dialysis-warranting acidosis type like high anion gap metabolic acidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Kussmaul breathing seen in a CKD patient indicates:", "a": "Uraemic pneumonitis", "b": "Respiratory compensation for severe metabolic acidosis — may indicate need for dialysis", "c": "Pulmonary oedema", "d": "Pleural effusion", "ans": "B", "e": "Respiratory compensation for severe metabolic acidosis is indicated by Kussmaul breathing in CKD patient; characteristic deep rapid breathing reflects respiratory drive to blow off CO2 raising pH.<br><br>Standard Kussmaul breathing features: deep, rapid, laboured breathing without distress, reflects compensatory mechanism for metabolic acidosis. Causes: DKA, uraemia, lactic acidosis, salicylate poisoning, methanol/ethylene glycol poisoning.<br><br>Uraemic pneumonitis (option A); Pulmonary oedema (option C) is not the correct choice; Pleural effusion (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Kussmaul breathing in CKD indication like respiratory compensation for severe metabolic acidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which electrolyte abnormality most commonly necessitates urgent dialysis?", "a": "Refractory hyperkalaemia (K⁺ >6.5 mEq/L or with ECG changes)", "b": "Hyponatraemia", "c": "Hypermagnesaemia", "d": "Hypocalcaemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Refractory hyperkalaemia (potassium over 6.5 mEq/L or with ECG changes) most commonly necessitates urgent dialysis; characteristic cardiac arrhythmia risk requires immediate intervention.<br><br>Standard hyperkalaemia management hierarchy: medical management (calcium gluconate for cardiac stabilisation, insulin plus glucose, salbutamol nebulisation, sodium bicarbonate, kayexalate). Dialysis when refractory to medical management, ECG changes, very high levels.<br><br>Hyponatraemia (option B) is not the correct choice; Hypermagnesaemia (option C) is not the correct choice; Hypocalcaemia (option D) is not the correct choice, none being most common urgent dialysis electrolyte indication like refractory hyperkalaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "ECG changes seen in severe hyperkalaemia that may indicate need for emergency dialysis include:", "a": "ST elevation and Q waves", "b": "Prolonged QT interval only", "c": "Peaked T waves, widened QRS, sine wave pattern", "d": "Delta waves", "ans": "C", "e": "Peaked T waves, widened QRS, sine wave pattern indicate urgent dialysis in severe hyperkalaemia; characteristic progressive ECG changes precede cardiac arrest.<br><br>Standard hyperkalaemia ECG progression: peaked T waves, prolonged PR interval (6.5-7.5), widened QRS (7-8), loss of P waves, sine wave pattern (above 8 mEq/L), ventricular fibrillation/asystole (severe). Combined with immediate management (calcium gluconate, insulin/glucose, dialysis).<br><br>ST elevation and Q waves (option A); Prolonged QT interval only (option B); Delta waves (option D), none being severe hyperkalaemia ECG changes like peaked T waves, widened QRS, sine wave pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Medical management of hyperkalaemia before dialysis includes all EXCEPT:", "a": "Insulin + dextrose", "b": "Potassium chloride supplementation", "c": "Sodium bicarbonate", "d": "IV calcium gluconate", "ans": "B", "e": "Potassium chloride supplementation is NOT used in pre-dialysis hyperkalaemia management; characteristic opposite intervention worsens hyperkalaemia and increases cardiac risk.<br><br>Standard pre-dialysis hyperkalaemia management: calcium gluconate (cardiac membrane stabilisation, immediate but transient), insulin plus glucose (shifts K intracellularly for 4-6 hours), salbutamol nebulisation (shifts K intracellularly), sodium bicarbonate (if acidotic), kayexalate (sodium polystyrene sulfonate, slow K removal).<br><br>Insulin + dextrose (option A); Sodium bicarbonate (option C) is not the correct choice; IV calcium gluconate (option D) is not the correct choice, none being NOT pre-dialysis hyperkalaemia management like potassium chloride supplementation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hyperkalaemia in CKD is worsened by which commonly used drug class?", "a": "ACE inhibitors/ARBs", "b": "Beta-blockers", "c": "Thiazide diuretics", "d": "Calcium channel blockers", "ans": "A", "e": "ACE inhibitors/ARBs commonly worsen hyperkalaemia in CKD; characteristic reduction in aldosterone production combined with reduced potassium excretion contributes to hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Standard medications worsening hyperkalaemia: ACE inhibitors, ARBs, aldosterone antagonists (spironolactone, eplerenone), potassium-sparing diuretics, NSAIDs, beta-blockers, heparin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, calcineurin inhibitors. Combined with addressing through monitoring potassium, dose adjustment, discontinuation if severe.<br><br>Beta-blockers (option B) is not the correct choice; Thiazide diuretics (option C) is not the correct choice; Calcium channel blockers (option D) do not principally worsen hyperkalaemia, none being common medication worsening CKD hyperkalaemia like ACE inhibitors/ARBs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Severe hypernatraemia refractory to fluid management in a dialysis patient is best corrected by:", "a": "Free water supplementation only", "b": "Dialysis with adjusted dialysate sodium concentration", "c": "Loop diuretics", "d": "Desmopressin", "ans": "B", "e": "Dialysis with adjusted dialysate sodium concentration manages severe hypernatraemia refractory to fluid management in CKD; characteristic controlled correction prevents rapid osmotic shifts.<br><br>Standard severe hypernatraemia approach: gradual correction to avoid cerebral oedema, free water replacement orally or IV (5 percent dextrose, half-normal saline), dialysis if refractory or rapid correction needed. Combined with addressing through dialysate sodium adjustment, addressing underlying cause.<br><br>Free water supplementation only (option A); Loop diuretics (option C); Desmopressin (option D), none being severe hypernatraemia refractory management like dialysis with adjusted dialysate sodium.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Dialysis is indicated in poisoning with which substance?", "a": "Methanol and ethylene glycol", "b": "Digoxin", "c": "Tricyclic antidepressants", "d": "Benzodiazepines", "ans": "A", "e": "Methanol and ethylene glycol are classic poisoning indications for dialysis; characteristic toxic metabolites cause severe metabolic acidosis with osmolar gap requiring removal.<br><br>Standard methanol poisoning: metabolised to formaldehyde and formic acid (causes blindness, severe metabolic acidosis). Ethylene glycol poisoning: metabolised to glycolic and oxalic acids (causes AKI, hypocalcaemia, metabolic acidosis).<br><br>Digoxin (option B) is not the correct choice; Tricyclic antidepressants (option C) is not the correct choice; Benzodiazepines (option D) is not the correct choice, none being classic poisoning dialysis indications like methanol and ethylene glycol.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which property of a toxin makes it amenable to removal by dialysis?", "a": "Lipid solubility", "b": "High protein binding", "c": "High molecular weight", "d": "Low molecular weight, low protein binding, small volume of distribution, water solubility", "ans": "D", "e": "Low molecular weight, low protein binding, small volume of distribution make toxin amenable to dialysis removal; characteristic properties allow efficient diffusion across dialyser membrane.<br><br>Standard dialysable toxin characteristics: molecular weight under 500 Da (high-flux can remove larger), low protein binding (under 80 percent), low volume of distribution (under 1 L/kg), water-soluble. Examples: methanol, ethylene glycol, lithium, salicylates, theophylline, methotrexate.<br><br>Lipid solubility (option A); High protein binding (option B); High molecular weight (option C), none being dialysable toxin properties like low molecular weight, low protein binding, small volume of distribution.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Salicylate (aspirin) overdose is an indication for dialysis when:", "a": "Serum salicylate >30 mg/dL in any patient", "b": "Serum salicylate >100 mg/dL OR severe toxicity with acidosis, renal failure, or neurological symptoms", "c": "Any symptomatic patient regardless of level", "d": "Salicylate >50 mg/dL with normal pH", "ans": "B", "e": "Serum salicylate over 100 mg/dL or severe toxicity with metabolic acidosis indicates dialysis in salicylate overdose; characteristic clearance thresholds and clinical severity guide intervention.<br><br>Standard salicylate toxicity features: tinnitus, mixed respiratory alkalosis/metabolic acidosis, seizures/coma/pulmonary oedema/severe acidosis. Treatment: urinary alkalinisation, haemodialysis for severe toxicity.<br><br>Serum salicylate >30 mg/dL in any patient (option A); Any symptomatic patient regardless of level (option C); Salicylate >50 mg/dL with normal pH (option D), none being salicylate dialysis indication like serum salicylate over 100 mg/dL or severe toxicity with metabolic acidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Lithium toxicity requiring dialysis is indicated when:", "a": "Lithium >2.5 mEq/L with no symptoms", "b": "Serum lithium is >1.5 mEq/L", "c": "Serum lithium >4 mEq/L or severe neurological toxicity regardless of level", "d": "Any patient with tremor", "ans": "C", "e": "Serum lithium over 4 mEq/L or severe neurological toxicity indicates lithium toxicity requiring dialysis; characteristic threshold and clinical severity guide intervention.<br><br>Standard lithium toxicity features: mild, moderate, severe. Treatment: aggressive isotonic saline hydration, addressing through dialysis for severe toxicity (level over 4 mEq/L, severe neurological symptoms, renal failure).<br><br>Lithium >2.5 mEq/L with no symptoms (option A); Serum lithium is >1.5 mEq/L (option B); Any patient with tremor (option D), none being lithium dialysis indication like serum lithium over 4 mEq/L or severe neurological toxicity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Methanol poisoning causes toxicity primarily through its metabolite:", "a": "Acetaldehyde", "b": "Formaldehyde and formic acid causing metabolic acidosis and blindness", "c": "Oxalic acid", "d": "Glycolic acid", "ans": "B", "e": "Formaldehyde and formic acid cause primary methanol toxicity through metabolic acidosis and blindness; characteristic alcohol dehydrogenase metabolism produces toxic metabolites.<br><br>Standard methanol metabolism: methanol -> formaldehyde (alcohol dehydrogenase) -> formic acid (aldehyde dehydrogenase). Formic acid causes high anion gap metabolic acidosis (often with osmolar gap), retinal damage and blindness, basal ganglia injury.<br><br>Acetaldehyde (option A); Oxalic acid (option C) is not the correct choice; Glycolic acid (option D) is not the correct choice, none being methanol toxicity mechanism like formaldehyde and formic acid causing metabolic acidosis and blindness.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Ethylene glycol poisoning is best treated with dialysis AND which antidote?", "a": "N-acetylcysteine", "b": "Naloxone", "c": "Fomepizole (alcohol dehydrogenase inhibitor)", "d": "Flumazenil", "ans": "C", "e": "Fomepizole (alcohol dehydrogenase inhibitor) plus dialysis treats ethylene glycol poisoning; characteristic blockade of toxic metabolite formation combined with elimination provides effective therapy.<br><br>Standard ethylene glycol management: fomepizole (4-methylpyrazole, first-line, IV loading dose 15 mg/kg then 10 mg/kg every 12 hours), alternative ethanol (target blood level 100-150 mg/dL), haemodialysis for severe acidosis, AKI, high levels, persistent metabolic acidosis despite antidote. Combined with thiamine and pyridoxine (cofactors).<br><br>N-acetylcysteine (option A); Naloxone (option B); Flumazenil (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ethylene glycol antidote with dialysis like fomepizole.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following drugs is NOT effectively removed by haemodialysis due to high protein binding?", "a": "Salicylates at toxic levels", "b": "Tricyclic antidepressants", "c": "Methanol", "d": "Lithium", "ans": "B", "e": "Tricyclic antidepressants are NOT effectively removed by dialysis; characteristic high protein binding, large volume of distribution, and lipid solubility prevent dialysis clearance.<br><br>Standard non-dialysable poisons: tricyclic antidepressants, benzodiazepines (highly protein-bound), digoxin (large Vd, mostly tissue-bound), phenytoin (highly protein-bound). Treatment: supportive care, addressing through sodium bicarbonate (TCA cardiotoxicity), specific antidotes (flumazenil for benzodiazepines, digoxin-specific antibody fragments).<br><br>Salicylates at toxic levels (option A); Methanol (option C) IS effectively removed by dialysis; Lithium (option D) IS effectively removed by dialysis, none being NOT effectively dialysed poison like tricyclic antidepressants.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In theophylline toxicity, dialysis is indicated when:", "a": "Serum level >10 mg/L", "b": "Level >40 mg/L routinely", "c": "Any symptomatic patient", "d": "Serum level >90–100 mg/L or severe toxicity (seizures, arrhythmias)", "ans": "D", "e": "Serum level over 90-100 mg/L or severe toxicity (seizures, arrhythmias) indicates dialysis in theophylline toxicity; characteristic threshold and clinical severity guide intervention.<br><br>Standard theophylline toxicity features: mild, moderate (25-40 mg/L, vomiting, agitation, hypokalaemia), severe (over 40 mg/L acute or over 30 mg/L chronic, seizures, ventricular arrhythmias). Treatment: activated charcoal, supportive care, haemodialysis or haemoperfusion for severe toxicity.<br><br>Serum level >10 mg/L (option A); Level >40 mg/L routinely (option B); Any symptomatic patient (option C), none being theophylline dialysis indication like serum level over 90-100 mg/L or severe toxicity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Fluid overload refractory to diuretics is an indication for dialysis. The most dangerous manifestation of fluid overload requiring urgent dialysis is:", "a": "Pulmonary oedema causing respiratory failure", "b": "Peripheral oedema", "c": "Pleural effusion alone", "d": "Ascites", "ans": "A", "e": "Pulmonary oedema causing respiratory failure is indication for dialysis when fluid overload refractory to diuretics; characteristic life-threatening complication requires immediate fluid removal.<br><br>Standard refractory fluid overload features: pulmonary oedema despite maximal diuretics, hypoxaemia, respiratory distress, fluid retention with weight gain. Combined with addressing through emergency haemodialysis or ultrafiltration (isolated UF without solute removal), continuous renal replacement therapy in ICU.<br><br>Peripheral oedema (option B); Pleural effusion alone (option C); Ascites (option D) is not the correct choice, none being refractory fluid overload requiring dialysis like pulmonary oedema causing respiratory failure.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which diuretic is preferred in managing fluid overload in CKD before initiating dialysis?", "a": "Spironolactone", "b": "Thiazide diuretics", "c": "Acetazolamide", "d": "Loop diuretics (furosemide)", "ans": "D", "e": "Loop diuretics (furosemide) are preferred for managing fluid overload in CKD before dialysis; characteristic potent diuresis effective even at low GFR with appropriate dose adjustment.<br><br>Standard CKD diuretic use: furosemide IV (more reliable absorption), higher doses often required in advanced CKD (80-200 mg or more), continuous infusion for refractory cases, combination with thiazide-like diuretics (metolazone) for synergy. Combined with addressing through fluid restriction, sodium restriction, optimising heart failure management.<br><br>Spironolactone (option A); Thiazide diuretics (option B); Acetazolamide (option C), none being preferred CKD fluid overload diuretic like loop diuretics.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Oliguria in the context of dialysis indications is defined as urine output less than:", "a": "100 ml/day", "b": "200 ml/day", "c": "400 ml/day", "d": "500 ml/day", "ans": "C", "e": "400 mL/day defines oliguria in dialysis indications context; characteristic urine output threshold reflects inadequate renal function requiring intervention.<br><br>Standard oliguria definitions: 400 mL/day (general clinical), under 0.5 mL/kg/hour for over 6 hours (AKI KDIGO). Combined with addressing through evaluation of cause (pre-renal, intrinsic, post-renal), addressing through fluid balance, electrolyte monitoring, addressing complications.<br><br>100 ml/day (option A) is anuria range; 200 ml/day (option B) is not the correct choice; 500 ml/day (option D) is not the correct choice, none being oliguria definition like 400 mL/day.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Anuria in a patient with CKD is defined as urine output less than:", "a": "400 ml/day", "b": "50 ml/day", "c": "200 ml/day", "d": "100 ml/day", "ans": "D", "e": "100 mL/day defines anuria in CKD patient; characteristic minimal urine output reflects severe renal failure or complete obstruction.<br><br>Standard anuria definitions: under 100 mL/day (complete absence of urine), versus oliguria (under 400 mL/day). Causes: complete bilateral obstruction, severe AKI, ESRD on maintenance dialysis, vascular catastrophe (renal artery thrombosis), severe acute tubular necrosis.<br><br>400 ml/day (option A) is not the correct choice; 50 ml/day (option B) is below anuria definition (some definitions use 50 mL/day); 200 ml/day (option C) is oliguria not anuria, none being anuria definition like 100 mL/day.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Isolated ultrafiltration in dialysis is specifically used for:", "a": "Fluid removal only without significant solute clearance", "b": "Solute clearance only", "c": "Correction of acidosis", "d": "Toxin removal", "ans": "A", "e": "Fluid removal only without significant solute clearance is purpose of isolated ultrafiltration in dialysis; characteristic technique addresses pure fluid overload without disturbing solute balance.<br><br>Standard isolated ultrafiltration features: applied transmembrane pressure removes water, preserves electrolytes and acid-base balance, well-tolerated haemodynamically, useful for diuretic-resistant fluid overload (especially decompensated heart failure with normal kidney function). Combined with sequential UF + dialysis for combined needs.<br><br>Solute clearance only (option B); Correction of acidosis (option C); Toxin removal (option D), none being isolated ultrafiltration purpose like fluid removal only without significant solute clearance.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with ESRD develops acute pulmonary oedema with oxygen saturation of 82% not responding to IV furosemide. The immediate next step is:", "a": "Increase oral diuretic dose", "b": "Emergency haemodialysis/ultrafiltration", "c": "IV albumin infusion", "d": "Fluid challenge", "ans": "B", "e": "Emergency haemodialysis/ultrafiltration is appropriate for ESRD patient with acute pulmonary oedema; characteristic rapid fluid removal addresses life-threatening fluid overload.<br><br>Standard ESRD pulmonary oedema management: supplemental oxygen, non-invasive ventilation (CPAP/BiPAP) if respiratory failure, nitrates (if BP allows), morphine (cautiously), addressing through emergency haemodialysis or isolated ultrafiltration. Combined with addressing through avoiding excessive volume removal causing hypotension.<br><br>Increase oral diuretic dose (option A); IV albumin infusion (option C) is not the correct choice; Fluid challenge (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ESRD acute pulmonary oedema management like emergency haemodialysis/ultrafiltration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hypertonic saline is contraindicated in hyponatraemia associated with fluid overload in dialysis patients because:", "a": "It is contraindicated only in peritoneal dialysis", "b": "It causes hypokalaemia", "c": "It worsens fluid overload and can cause central pontine myelinolysis if corrected too fast", "d": "It directly damages the peritoneum", "ans": "C", "e": "Worsens fluid overload and can cause central pontine myelinolysis make hypertonic saline contraindicated in hyponatraemia with CKD; characteristic sodium load aggravates fluid retention while rapid correction risks osmotic demyelination.<br><br>Standard CKD hyponatraemia management: gradual correction, fluid restriction, addressing underlying cause, dialysis if severe or refractory. Combined with addressing through identifying chronicity.<br><br>It is contraindicated only in peritoneal dialysis (option A); It causes hypokalaemia (option B); It directly damages the peritoneum (option D), none being CKD hyponatraemia hypertonic saline contraindication like worsens fluid overload and causes central pontine myelinolysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic pericarditis is an absolute indication for dialysis. It is characterized by:", "a": "Fever with productive cough", "b": "Troponin elevation alone", "c": "ST elevation in all leads with reciprocal changes", "d": "Pleuritic chest pain, pericardial friction rub, and pericardial effusion in a uraemic patient", "ans": "D", "e": "Pleuritic chest pain, pericardial friction rub, and risk of cardiac tamponade make uraemic pericarditis absolute dialysis indication; characteristic life-threatening complication requires immediate intervention.<br><br>Standard uraemic pericarditis features: pericardial friction rub, pleuritic chest pain, ECG changes, pericardial effusion, associated with severe uraemia. Treatment: urgent daily haemodialysis until resolution.<br><br>Fever with productive cough (option A); Troponin elevation alone (option B); ST elevation in all leads with reciprocal changes (option C), none being uraemic pericarditis dialysis indication like pleuritic chest pain, pericardial friction rub, and risk of cardiac tamponade.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic encephalopathy requiring dialysis presents with all EXCEPT:", "a": "Seizures", "b": "Focal neurological deficits as the primary feature", "c": "Confusion and disorientation", "d": "Asterixis (flapping tremor)", "ans": "B", "e": "Focal neurological deficits as the primary feature are NOT typical of uraemic encephalopathy requiring dialysis; characteristic diffuse non-specific neurological symptoms predominate.<br><br>Standard uraemic encephalopathy features: confusion, lethargy, asterixis, myoclonus, seizures, coma in severe cases (diffuse manifestations). Focal deficits suggest alternative diagnoses (stroke, intracranial haemorrhage - more common in dialysis patients).<br><br>Seizures (option A); Confusion and disorientation (option C) is not the correct choice; Asterixis (flapping tremor) (option D) is not the correct choice, none being NOT uraemic encephalopathy feature like focal neurological deficits as primary feature.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Asterixis (flapping tremor) in CKD is caused by:", "a": "Accumulation of uraemic toxins affecting the brain", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Hypocalcaemia", "d": "Hyponatraemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Accumulation of uraemic toxins affecting brain causes asterixis (flapping tremor) in CKD; characteristic uraemic encephalopathy produces brief loss of postural muscle tone reflected as flapping movements.<br><br>Standard asterixis features: tested by extending arms with wrists dorsiflexed, brief loss of tone causes hands to flap downward, also seen in hepatic encephalopathy, hypercapnia, severe electrolyte abnormalities. Combined with other uraemic encephalopathy features: confusion, lethargy, myoclonus, seizures.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option B); Hypocalcaemia (option C); Hyponatraemia (option D), none being CKD asterixis cause like accumulation of uraemic toxins affecting the brain.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic bleeding tendency (platelet dysfunction) is best treated acutely by:", "a": "Fresh frozen plasma", "b": "Dialysis (removes uraemic toxins), desmopressin (DDAVP), and conjugated oestrogens", "c": "Platelet transfusion alone", "d": "Vitamin K", "ans": "B", "e": "Dialysis (removes uraemic toxins) and desmopressin (DDAVP) best treat uraemic bleeding tendency; characteristic combined approach addresses underlying mechanism and provides immediate haemostasis.<br><br>Standard uraemic bleeding management: dialysis (removes uraemic toxins responsible for platelet dysfunction), desmopressin (DDAVP, 0.3 mcg/kg IV, releases von Willebrand factor for immediate but transient effect), conjugated oestrogens (longer-acting), cryoprecipitate for severe active bleeding, addressing anaemia (Hb over 10 g/dL improves haemostasis).<br><br>Fresh frozen plasma (option A); Platelet transfusion alone (option C); Vitamin K (option D), none being uraemic bleeding tendency management like dialysis and desmopressin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The BUN level at which uraemic symptoms typically appear and dialysis is considered is approximately:", "a": ">100 mg/dL (often >70–100 mg/dL with symptoms)", "b": ">150 mg/dL always", "c": ">50 mg/dL", "d": ">30 mg/dL", "ans": "A", "e": "Over 100 mg/dL BUN typically produces uraemic symptoms necessitating dialysis; characteristic threshold often combined with clinical features guides decisions.<br><br>Standard uraemic symptoms: anorexia, nausea, vomiting, fatigue, weakness, pruritus, confusion, asterixis, pericarditis, bleeding tendency. BUN levels correlate roughly with severity but individual variation significant.<br><br>>150 mg/dL always (option B) is not the correct choice; >50 mg/dL (option C) is not the correct choice; >30 mg/dL (option D) is not the correct choice, none being uraemic symptoms BUN threshold like over 100 mg/dL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic frost, a late sign of severe uraemia indicating urgent dialysis, is caused by:", "a": "Bile pigments", "b": "Urea crystallizing on skin surface as sweat evaporates", "c": "Phosphate deposits", "d": "Calcium deposits on skin", "ans": "B", "e": "Urea crystallising on skin surface as sweat evaporates causes uraemic frost; characteristic late sign of severe uraemia indicates need for urgent dialysis.<br><br>Standard uraemic frost features: white powder-like deposits on skin, occurs when BUN extremely elevated, sweat contains urea which crystallises after water evaporation. Combined with addressing through urgent dialysis (rarely seen in modern era with timely RRT initiation), addressing severe uraemia.<br><br>Bile pigments (option A); Phosphate deposits (option C); Calcium deposits on skin (option D), none being uraemic frost mechanism like urea crystallising on skin surface as sweat evaporates.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which gastrointestinal manifestation of uraemia is a common indication prompting initiation of dialysis?", "a": "Constipation", "b": "Diarrhoea", "c": "Haematemesis from varices", "d": "Intractable nausea, vomiting, and anorexia due to uraemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Intractable nausea, vomiting, and anorexia due to uraemia are common GI manifestation requiring dialysis; characteristic uraemic toxins affect GI tract causing severe symptoms.<br><br>Standard uraemic GI features: anorexia (often earliest), nausea, vomiting, hiccups, metallic taste, uraemic gastritis (mucosal erosions), uraemic colitis, ileus, malnutrition. Combined with addressing through dialysis (resolves most symptoms within days to weeks), nutritional support, addressing through antiemetics for symptomatic relief.<br><br>Constipation (option A); Diarrhoea (option B); Haematemesis from varices (option C), none being uraemic GI manifestation requiring dialysis like intractable nausea, vomiting, and anorexia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uraemic pleuritis differs from uraemic pericarditis in that:", "a": "It is more common", "b": "It presents with pleural friction rub and pleural effusion in uraemia", "c": "It is not an indication for dialysis", "d": "It is caused by infection exclusively", "ans": "B", "e": "Pleural friction rub and pleural effusion differentiate uraemic pleuritis from uraemic pericarditis; characteristic pleural involvement produces different clinical features though similar mechanism.<br><br>Standard uraemic pleuritis features: less common than uraemic pericarditis, pleural friction rub, pleuritic chest pain, pleural effusion. Combined with addressing through urgent dialysis (similar to pericarditis), thoracentesis if large effusion.<br><br>It is more common (option A); It is not an indication for dialysis (option C); It is caused by infection exclusively (option D), none being uraemic pleuritis differentiation like pleural friction rub and pleural effusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The standard frequency of conventional haemodialysis for ESRD patients is:", "a": "Three sessions per week, each lasting 3–5 hours", "b": "Two sessions per week of 6 hours each", "c": "Five sessions per week of 2 hours each", "d": "Daily sessions of 2 hours", "ans": "A", "e": "Three sessions per week, each lasting 3-5 hours is standard frequency of conventional haemodialysis; characteristic schedule provides adequate solute and fluid clearance.<br><br>Standard conventional haemodialysis: 4 hours per session, 3 sessions per week, achieves Kt/V over 1.2 per session in most patients. Combined with addressing through alternatives.<br><br>Two sessions per week of 6 hours each (option B); Five sessions per week of 2 hours each (option C); Daily sessions of 2 hours (option D), none being conventional haemodialysis frequency like three sessions per week, each 3-5 hours.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Incremental dialysis refers to:", "a": "Dialysis with increasing membrane surface area over time", "b": "Starting dialysis at maximum frequency immediately", "c": "Starting with fewer/shorter sessions and increasing frequency as residual renal function declines", "d": "Dialysis performed only during emergencies", "ans": "C", "e": "Starting with fewer/shorter sessions and increasing as residual function declines describes incremental dialysis; characteristic approach preserves residual renal function while providing adequate clearance.<br><br>Standard incremental features: 1-2 sessions per week initially in patients with significant residual renal function, increasing as residual function declines.<br><br>Dialysis with increasing membrane surface area over time (option A); Starting dialysis at maximum frequency immediately (option B); Dialysis performed only during emergencies (option D), none being incremental dialysis definition like starting with fewer/shorter sessions and increasing as residual function declines.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In patients with significant residual renal function, incremental haemodialysis may begin with:", "a": "One to two sessions per week", "b": "Five sessions per week", "c": "Daily nocturnal dialysis", "d": "Three sessions per week always", "ans": "A", "e": "One to two sessions per week is incremental dialysis schedule with significant residual renal function; characteristic reduced frequency preserves remaining kidney function.<br><br>Standard incremental dialysis indications: significant residual renal function, stable clinical status, no major complications, willingness for close monitoring. Combined with addressing through addressing modifiable factors, regular reassessment, increasing frequency as residual function declines.<br><br>Five sessions per week (option B); Daily nocturnal dialysis (option C); Three sessions per week always (option D), none being incremental dialysis initial schedule like one to two sessions per week.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Nocturnal haemodialysis (NHD) typically involves:", "a": "Three sessions per week of 4 hours during the day", "b": "Daily sessions of 3 hours at night", "c": "Five to six nights per week of 6–8 hours overnight", "d": "Two nights per week of 10 hours", "ans": "C", "e": "Five to six nights per week of 6-8 hours overnight describes nocturnal haemodialysis; characteristic longer slower sessions during sleep provide improved clearance and outcomes.<br><br>Standard NHD features: home-based, longer sessions (6-8 hours), slower blood flow, improved clearance of middle molecules.<br><br>Three sessions per week of 4 hours during the day (option A); Daily sessions of 3 hours at night (option B); Two nights per week of 10 hours (option D), none being nocturnal haemodialysis schedule like five to six nights per week of 6-8 hours overnight.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which dialysis schedule has been shown to provide better cardiovascular outcomes and blood pressure control compared to conventional three-times-weekly haemodialysis?", "a": "Monthly long dialysis sessions", "b": "Frequent (daily or nocturnal) haemodialysis", "c": "Peritoneal dialysis exclusively", "d": "Twice weekly conventional dialysis", "ans": "B", "e": "Frequent (daily or nocturnal) haemodialysis provides better volume and BP control than conventional schedule; characteristic increased dialysis frequency or duration improves outcomes.<br><br>Standard frequent haemodialysis benefits: improved BP control, improved left ventricular hypertrophy, fewer intradialytic complications, better quality of life, less restricted diet, better phosphate control. Combined with addressing through challenges (vascular access wear, patient/family burden, cost).<br><br>Monthly long dialysis sessions (option A); Peritoneal dialysis exclusively (option C); Twice weekly conventional dialysis (option D), none being better volume and BP control schedule like frequent haemodialysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In Continuous Ambulatory Peritoneal Dialysis (CAPD), exchanges are performed:", "a": "Four exchanges per day (approximately every 4–6 hours) manually by the patient", "b": "Once daily in hospital", "c": "Three times per week by a machine overnight", "d": "Twice daily with 8 hours dwell time each", "ans": "A", "e": "Four exchanges per day characterise CAPD; characteristic continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis maintains continuous fluid in peritoneal cavity with periodic exchanges.<br><br>Standard CAPD features: 4 manual exchanges per day, dialysate dwells in peritoneal cavity for 4-6 hours, each exchange takes 30-40 minutes, patient-administered at home.<br><br>Once daily in hospital (option B); Three times per week by a machine overnight (option C); Twice daily with 8 hours dwell time each (option D), none being CAPD exchange frequency like four exchanges per day.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Adequacy of dialysis dose is assessed by Kt/V. The minimum recommended Kt/V per session for thrice-weekly haemodialysis is:", "a": "1.5", "b": "1.2", "c": "0.8", "d": "2.0", "ans": "B", "e": "1.2 is minimum target single-pool Kt/V for adequacy of dialysis dose per session; characteristic threshold ensures adequate urea clearance for maintenance haemodialysis.<br><br>Standard Kt/V interpretation: K (dialyser urea clearance), t (treatment time), V (urea distribution volume), target single-pool Kt/V over 1.2 per session (3 sessions/week). Combined with addressing through equilibrated Kt/V (eKt/V) target over 1.05, URR (urea reduction ratio) target over 65 percent.<br><br>1.5 (option A); 0.8 (option C) is not the correct choice; 2.0 (option D) is not the correct choice, none being minimum single-pool Kt/V target like 1.2.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 6-year-old boy presents with periorbital puffiness, frothy urine and no haematuria. Renal biopsy shows normal light microscopy but effacement of foot processes on electron microscopy. Which is the MOST appropriate first-line treatment?", "a": "Tacrolimus", "b": "Cyclophosphamide", "c": "Oral prednisolone", "d": "Mycophenolate mofetil", "ans": "C", "e": "Oral prednisolone treats 6-year-old with periorbital puffiness, foamy urine; characteristic paediatric nephrotic syndrome from minimal change disease responds excellent to corticosteroids (80-90 percent remission).<br><br>Standard regimen: prednisolone 60 mg/m2/day for 4-6 weeks, then alternate-day for 2-5 months. Combined with addressing relapses (additional courses, alternative agents for steroid-dependent or steroid-resistant cases: cyclophosphamide, ciclosporin, tacrolimus, rituximab).<br><br>Tacrolimus (option A) is not the correct choice; Cyclophosphamide (option B) is not the correct choice; Mycophenolate mofetil (option D) is not the correct choice, none being paediatric nephrotic syndrome first-line like oral prednisolone.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 35-year-old man presents with haematuria, proteinuria and upper respiratory tract infection simultaneously (synpharyngitic haematuria). Biopsy shows mesangial IgA deposits. Which complement pathway is activated?", "a": "Classical pathway", "b": "Lectin pathway", "c": "All three equally", "d": "Alternative pathway", "ans": "D", "e": "Alternative pathway complement activation characterises 35-year-old with haematuria, proteinuria, low C3, normal C4; characteristic dense deposit disease (MPGN type II) involves C3 nephritic factor.<br><br>Standard MPGN type II features: C3 nephritic factor stabilises C3 convertase, persistent alternative pathway activation, dense intramembranous deposits on EM, low C3 with normal C4. Combined with addressing through eculizumab in some cases, treating underlying causes, supportive care.<br><br>Classical pathway (option A); Lectin pathway (option B); All three equally (option C), none being low C3 normal C4 complement pathway like alternative pathway.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 28-year-old woman with SLE develops nephrotic syndrome. Renal biopsy shows “wire loop” lesions and subendothelial deposits. Which WHO/ISN class of lupus nephritis is this?", "a": "Class IV", "b": "Class III", "c": "Class V", "d": "Class II", "ans": "A", "e": "Class IV (diffuse proliferative) characterises 28-year-old with SLE and nephrotic syndrome with biopsy showing diffuse endocapillary proliferation; characteristic most severe and common form requires aggressive immunosuppression.<br><br>Standard lupus nephritis ISN/RPS classification: Class I (minimal mesangial), Class II, Class III (focal), Class IV, Class V (membranous), Class VI (advanced sclerosis). Treatment Class IV: corticosteroids plus mycophenolate or cyclophosphamide.<br><br>Class III (option B); Class V (option C) is membranous (different histology); Class II (option D) is mesangial proliferative (less severe), none being diffuse proliferative lupus nephritis class like Class IV.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient presents with rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN). Biopsy shows crescents in >50% of glomeruli with linear IgG deposits along GBM. Which antibody is responsible?", "a": "Anti-streptolysin O", "b": "Anti-GBM antibody", "c": "ANCA (c-ANCA)", "d": "Anti-dsDNA", "ans": "B", "e": "Anti-GBM antibody fits RPGN patient with linear IgG deposits on immunofluorescence; characteristic antibodies against alpha-3 chain of type IV collagen produce linear pattern along GBM.<br><br>Standard anti-GBM disease features: positive anti-GBM antibody titre (ELISA), biopsy showing linear IgG along GBM, crescentic glomerulonephritis. Pulmonary involvement (Goodpasture syndrome with haemoptysis) in 50-60 percent.<br><br>Anti-streptolysin O (option A) is not the correct choice; ANCA (c-ANCA) (option C) is not the correct choice; Anti-dsDNA (option D) is not the correct choice, none being RPGN with linear IgG diagnostic test like anti-GBM antibody.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 45-year-old man presents with haemoptysis and haematuria. c-ANCA is positive. Biopsy shows pauci-immune crescentic GN with no immune deposits. Diagnosis is:", "a": "Microscopic polyangiitis", "b": "Churg-Strauss syndrome", "c": "Goodpasture syndrome", "d": "Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener’s)", "ans": "D", "e": "Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener's) fits 45-year-old with haemoptysis, haematuria, and c-ANCA positive; characteristic upper and lower respiratory tract involvement with crescentic glomerulonephritis.<br><br>Standard GPA features: upper respiratory, lower respiratory (cavitating pulmonary nodules, alveolar haemorrhage), renal (RPGN with crescents), c-ANCA/PR3 positive. Treatment: corticosteroids plus cyclophosphamide or rituximab.<br><br>Microscopic polyangiitis (option A) is p-ANCA positive (not c-ANCA); Churg-Strauss syndrome (option B) is not the correct choice; Goodpasture syndrome (option C) has anti-GBM antibodies not c-ANCA, none being c-ANCA positive vasculitis with haemoptysis and haematuria like granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis typically occurs after pharyngeal infection within:", "a": "1–3 days", "b": "3–6 months", "c": "1–3 weeks", "d": "6–8 weeks", "ans": "C", "e": "1-3 weeks latent period characterises post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis after streptococcal infection; characteristic immune complex deposition typically develops 10-21 days after pharyngitis or skin infection.<br><br>Standard PSGN features: nephritic syndrome, elevated ASO titre or anti-DNase B, low C3, subepithelial humps on EM. Treatment: supportive care, addressing infection, prognosis usually good in children.<br><br>1–3 days (option A) is not the correct choice; 3–6 months (option B) is not the correct choice; 6–8 weeks (option D) is not the correct choice, none being post-streptococcal GN latent period like 1-3 weeks.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In post-streptococcal GN, which complement component is characteristically LOW?", "a": "C3 low, C4 normal", "b": "C3 and C4 both low", "c": "C4 low, C3 normal", "d": "Both C3 and C4 normal", "ans": "A", "e": "C3 low, C4 normal characterises post-streptococcal GN complement pattern; characteristic alternative pathway activation through immune complex deposition lowers C3 without affecting C4.<br><br>Standard PSGN features: 10-21 days after streptococcal infection, nephritic syndrome, elevated ASO/anti-DNase B, low C3, subepithelial humps on EM. Combined with other glomerulonephritides with low complement: MPGN, lupus nephritis, endocarditis-associated.<br><br>C3 and C4 both low (option B); C4 low, C3 normal (option C); Both C3 and C4 normal (option D) is IgA nephropathy or anti-GBM disease pattern, none being PSGN complement pattern like C3 low, C4 normal.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 50-year-old man with hepatitis B presents with nephrotic syndrome. Biopsy shows “spike and dome” pattern on silver stain with subepithelial deposits. Diagnosis:", "a": "Membranoproliferative GN", "b": "Membranous nephropathy", "c": "Minimal change disease", "d": "FSGS", "ans": "B", "e": "Membranous nephropathy fits 50-year-old with hepatitis B presenting with nephrotic syndrome; characteristic hepatitis B-associated secondary membranous nephropathy through immune complex deposition.<br><br>Standard secondary membranous nephropathy causes: hepatitis B and C, autoimmune diseases (lupus), malignancy (lung, colon, breast, prostate), drugs (NSAIDs, gold, penicillamine). Primary membranous: anti-PLA2R antibody. Biopsy: subepithelial deposits with spike-and-dome on silver stain.<br><br>Membranoproliferative GN (option A) is not the correct choice; Minimal change disease (option C) is more common in children; FSGS (option D) is not the correct choice, none being hepatitis B-associated nephrotic syndrome like membranous nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which glomerulonephritis shows “tram-track” appearance on PAS stain?", "a": "Membranoproliferative GN (MPGN)", "b": "IgA nephropathy", "c": "Minimal change disease", "d": "Membranous nephropathy", "ans": "A", "e": "Membranoproliferative GN (MPGN) shows tram-track appearance on biopsy; characteristic double-contour basement membrane from mesangial cell interposition produces tram-track.<br><br>Standard MPGN features: tram-track appearance (silver stain), mesangial proliferation, immune complex deposition. Combined with addressing through secondary causes (hepatitis C, lupus, cryoglobulinaemia, MGUS).<br><br>IgA nephropathy (option B) is not the correct choice; Minimal change disease (option C) shows normal light microscopy with foot process effacement; Membranous nephropathy (option D) shows spike and dome appearance, none being tram-track biopsy appearance like membranoproliferative GN.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with MPGN has low C3 AND low C4. This pattern suggests activation of:", "a": "Terminal complement only", "b": "Classical pathway", "c": "Alternative pathway only", "d": "Lectin pathway only", "ans": "B", "e": "Classical pathway activation characterises MPGN with low C3 AND low C4; characteristic immune complex deposition activates classical complement pathway consuming both C3 and C4.<br><br>Standard MPGN type I features: immune complex-mediated, subendothelial deposits, both C3 and C4 low, secondary causes. Combined with MPGN type II: C3 nephritic factor, alternative pathway, low C3 with normal C4.<br><br>Terminal complement only (option A); Alternative pathway only (option C); Lectin pathway only (option D) is not the correct choice, none being MPGN with low C3 and C4 pathway like classical pathway.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "RIFLE criteria classifies AKI. The “I” (Injury) category is defined as:", "a": "Creatinine increase ×1.5 or UO <0.3 ml/kg/hr for 24 hrs", "b": "Creatinine increase ×1.5 or UO <0.5 ml/kg/hr for 6 hrs", "c": "Creatinine increase ×2 or UO <0.5 ml/kg/hr for 12 hrs", "d": "Creatinine increase ×3 or UO <0.3 ml/kg/hr for 24 hrs", "ans": "C", "e": "Creatinine increase x2 or UO under 0.5 mL/kg/hour for 12 hours defines RIFLE 'I' (Injury) category; characteristic moderate severity AKI staging.<br><br>Standard RIFLE criteria: Risk, Injury, Failure, Loss (over 4 weeks), ESRD (over 3 months).<br><br>Creatinine increase ×1.5 or UO <0.3 ml/kg/hr for 24 hrs (option A); Creatinine increase ×1.5 or UO <0.5 ml/kg/hr for 6 hrs (option B); Creatinine increase ×3 or UO <0.3 ml/kg/hr for 24 hrs (option D), none being RIFLE Injury category like creatinine increase x2 or UO under 0.5 mL/kg/hour for 12 hours.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient post-major surgery develops oliguria. Urine sodium is 8 mEq/L, urine osmolality 620 mOsm/kg, FENa 0.3%. Diagnosis:", "a": "Acute interstitial nephritis", "b": "Pre-renal AKI", "c": "Acute tubular necrosis", "d": "Renal vein thrombosis", "ans": "B", "e": "Pre-renal AKI fits post-major surgery oliguric patient with bland urine sediment; characteristic volume depletion or hypoperfusion produces oliguria without intrinsic tubular damage.<br><br>Standard pre-renal AKI features: FeNa under 1 percent, urine sodium under 20 mEq/L, urine osmolality over 500 mOsm/kg, BUN/Cr ratio over 20, bland urine sediment with hyaline casts. Treatment: fluid resuscitation, addressing cause, avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>Acute interstitial nephritis (option A); Acute tubular necrosis (option C); Renal vein thrombosis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being post-surgery oliguria with bland sediment like pre-renal AKI.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "FENa (Fractional Excretion of Sodium) formula is:", "a": "Urine Cr / Plasma Cr × 100", "b": "Urine Na / Plasma Na × 100", "c": "(Urine Na × Plasma Cr) / (Plasma Na × Urine Cr) × 100", "d": "(Plasma Na × Urine Cr) / (Urine Na × Plasma Cr) × 100", "ans": "C", "e": "(Urine Na x plasma Cr)/(plasma Na x urine Cr) x 100 is FeNa formula; characteristic calculation quantifies fractional excretion of filtered sodium in AKI workup.<br><br>Standard FeNa interpretation: under 1 percent in pre-renal azotemia, over 2 percent in ATN.<br><br>Urine Cr / Plasma Cr × 100 (option A); Urine Na / Plasma Na × 100 (option B); (Plasma Na × Urine Cr) / (Urine Na × Plasma Cr) × 100 (option D), none being FeNa formula like (urine Na x plasma Cr)/(plasma Na x urine Cr) x 100.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient on gentamicin develops AKI. Urinalysis shows muddy brown granular casts. This indicates:", "a": "Acute tubular necrosis", "b": "Pre-renal AKI", "c": "Glomerulonephritis", "d": "Acute interstitial nephritis", "ans": "A", "e": "Acute tubular necrosis fits patient on gentamicin with AKI and muddy brown casts; characteristic aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity produces direct tubular injury with classic urinary findings.<br><br>Standard aminoglycoside ATN features: typically non-oliguric, risk factors. Prevention: once-daily dosing, trough monitoring (gentamicin under 2 mg/L), dose adjustment.<br><br>Pre-renal AKI (option B) is not the correct choice; Glomerulonephritis (option C) features RBC casts and dysmorphic RBCs; Acute interstitial nephritis (option D) features WBC casts and eosinophiluria, none being gentamicin AKI with muddy brown casts like acute tubular necrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient on penicillin develops fever, rash, eosinophilia and AKI. Urinalysis shows WBC casts and eosinophiluria. Diagnosis:", "a": "Acute tubular necrosis", "b": "Prerenal AKI", "c": "Acute interstitial nephritis", "d": "Rapidly progressive GN", "ans": "C", "e": "Acute interstitial nephritis fits patient on penicillin with fever, rash, eosinophilia, creatinine rise; characteristic classic AIN triad with antibiotic exposure.<br><br>Standard AIN diagnosis: clinical features, urinalysis, urinary eosinophils on Hansel stain (specific but not sensitive), biopsy confirmation if unclear. Treatment: discontinue drug, corticosteroids if non-resolving.<br><br>Acute tubular necrosis (option A) features muddy brown casts; Prerenal AKI (option B) is not the correct choice; Rapidly progressive GN (option D) is not the correct choice, none being penicillin AIN with classic triad like acute interstitial nephritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hepatorenal syndrome (HRS) Type 1 is defined by:", "a": "Doubling of creatinine to >2.5 mg/dL within 2 weeks", "b": "AKI with normal liver function", "c": "Creatinine >1.5 mg/dL with diuretic resistance", "d": "Gradual creatinine rise over months", "ans": "A", "e": "Doubling of creatinine to over 2.5 mg/dL within 2 weeks defines hepatorenal syndrome type 1; characteristic rapid renal deterioration in cirrhosis with portal hypertension.<br><br>Standard HRS type 1 features: rapid decline, severe liver disease, ascites, low urine sodium, FeNa under 1 percent, no response to volume. Treatment: terlipressin plus albumin.<br><br>AKI with normal liver function (option B); Creatinine >1.5 mg/dL with diuretic resistance (option C); Gradual creatinine rise over months (option D), none being hepatorenal syndrome type 1 definition like doubling of creatinine to over 2.5 mg/dL within 2 weeks.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In hepatorenal syndrome, FENa is characteristically:", "a": ">2%", "b": "<1% (often <0.1%)", "c": "1–2%", "d": "Variable", "ans": "B", "e": "Under 1 percent (often under 0.1 percent) characterises FeNa in hepatorenal syndrome; characteristic intense renal vasoconstriction with avid sodium reabsorption produces very low FeNa.<br><br>Standard HRS features: cirrhosis with portal hypertension, ascites, low urine sodium (under 10 mEq/L), FeNa under 1 percent, no improvement with volume challenge, no parenchymal renal disease. Type 1: rapid.<br><br>>2% (option A) suggests ATN (not HRS); 1–2% (option C) is not the correct choice; Variable (option D) is not the correct choice, none being HRS FeNa characteristic like under 1 percent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which cast is pathognomonic of chronic kidney disease?", "a": "Granular cast", "b": "Red cell cast", "c": "Waxy broad cast", "d": "White cell cast", "ans": "C", "e": "Waxy broad casts are pathognomonic of chronic kidney disease; characteristic broad waxy casts form in dilated tubules of chronically diseased kidneys with stasis.<br><br>Standard waxy cast features: broad, refractile, with sharp edges, formed in dilated tubules with prolonged stasis, indicate advanced CKD. Combined with other CKD findings: small kidneys on ultrasound, anaemia, hyperphosphataemia with secondary hyperparathyroidism, hypocalcaemia, renal osteodystrophy.<br><br>Granular cast (option A); Red cell cast (option B); White cell cast (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD pathognomonic cast like waxy broad cast.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 22-year-old develops AKI after crush injury in road traffic accident. Urine appears dark brown. Dipstick positive for blood but no RBCs on microscopy. Cause of AKI:", "a": "Myoglobinuria from rhabdomyolysis", "b": "Concentrated urine", "c": "Bilirubin in urine", "d": "Haemoglobinuria from haemolysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Myoglobinuria from rhabdomyolysis fits 22-year-old AKI after crush injury with positive dipstick for blood but no RBCs; characteristic free myoglobin causes positive blood dipstick without intact RBCs.<br><br>Standard rhabdomyolysis diagnosis: elevated CK (over 5000 IU/L), positive urine dipstick for blood without RBCs, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia (early). Treatment: aggressive isotonic saline, urine alkalinisation, addressing hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Concentrated urine (option B); Bilirubin in urine (option C); Haemoglobinuria from haemolysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being crush injury AKI with positive blood dipstick but no RBCs like myoglobinuria from rhabdomyolysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Management of rhabdomyolysis-induced AKI includes:", "a": "Aggressive IV fluid restriction", "b": "Early dialysis always", "c": "Aggressive IV normal saline to maintain urine output >200–300 ml/hr", "d": "Sodium bicarbonate alone", "ans": "C", "e": "Aggressive IV normal saline to maintain urine output 200-300 mL/hour manages rhabdomyolysis-induced AKI; characteristic dilution of nephrotoxic pigments and prevention of tubular obstruction.<br><br>Standard rhabdomyolysis treatment: aggressive isotonic saline, urine alkalinisation, addressing hyperkalaemia, monitoring CK trend, avoiding nephrotoxins.<br><br>Aggressive IV fluid restriction (option A) is not the correct choice; Early dialysis always (option B) is not the correct choice; Sodium bicarbonate alone (option D) is not the correct choice, none being rhabdomyolysis-induced AKI management like aggressive IV saline to maintain urine output 200-300 mL/hour.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 65-year-old diabetic hypertensive man presents with creatinine 4.2 mg/dL, K⁺ 6.8 mEq/L, HCO₃ 14 mEq/L, pH 7.18 and ECG showing peaked T waves and widened QRS. BP 180/110 mmHg. Urine output 80 ml in last 8 hours. What is the MOST urgent immediate intervention?", "a": "Oral sodium polystyrene sulfonate", "b": "IV calcium gluconate", "c": "IV insulin + dextrose", "d": "Emergency haemodialysis", "ans": "B", "e": "IV calcium gluconate is first intervention for 65-year-old diabetic hypertensive with CKD and peaked T waves on ECG; characteristic immediate cardiac membrane stabilisation antagonises hyperkalaemia effects.<br><br>Standard emergency hyperkalaemia management: calcium gluconate, insulin plus glucose, salbutamol nebulisation, sodium bicarbonate if acidotic, kayexalate or dialysis (removes K from body).<br><br>Oral sodium polystyrene sulfonate (option A); IV insulin + dextrose (option C) is not the correct choice; Emergency haemodialysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD with peaked T waves first intervention like IV calcium gluconate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 30-year-old woman presents with frothy urine, bilateral leg swelling and serum albumin of 1.8 g/dL. 24-hour urine protein is 6.2 g. She has a DVT in her right leg. What is the MOST likely underlying mechanism of DVT?", "a": "Immobility", "b": "Polycythaemia", "c": "Loss of antithrombin III in urine causing hypercoagulable state", "d": "Hyperviscosity from high proteins", "ans": "C", "e": "Loss of antithrombin III in urine causing hypercoagulability explains 30-year-old with nephrotic syndrome at risk of renal vein thrombosis; characteristic urinary loss of natural anticoagulants produces hypercoagulable state.<br><br>Standard nephrotic hypercoagulability mechanisms: loss of antithrombin III, protein C, protein S in urine; increased hepatic synthesis of fibrinogen and clotting factors; platelet hyperaggregability. Highest risk in membranous nephropathy.<br><br>Immobility (option A); Polycythaemia (option B) is not nephrotic feature; Hyperviscosity from high proteins (option D) is not the correct choice, none being nephrotic hypercoagulability mechanism like loss of antithrombin III in urine.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 55-year-old man with known myeloma presents with AKI, hypercalcaemia (Ca²⁺ 13.5 mg/dL) and proteinuria that does NOT show on urine dipstick. What type of protein is being lost?", "a": "Albumin", "b": "Bence Jones protein (immunoglobulin light chains)", "c": "Beta-2 microglobulin", "d": "Transferrin", "ans": "B", "e": "Bence Jones protein (immunoglobulin light chains) fits 55-year-old with myeloma and AKI with normal dipstick protein but high 24-hour urine protein; characteristic discrepancy reflects light chains not detected by dipstick.<br><br>Standard myeloma kidney features: urinary dipstick detects albumin (not light chains), 24-hour urine quantification shows high protein, urine protein electrophoresis (monoclonal spike), free light chain assay. Combined with biopsy showing cast nephropathy.<br><br>Albumin (option A); Beta-2 microglobulin (option C); Transferrin (option D) is not the correct choice, none being myeloma dipstick-negative high 24h protein like Bence Jones protein.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 40-year-old man with known HIV on HAART presents with nephrotic syndrome. Biopsy shows collapse of glomerular capillary tufts with podocyte hypertrophy. Electron microscopy shows tubuloreticular inclusions. Diagnosis:", "a": "Membranous nephropathy", "b": "Diabetic nephropathy", "c": "HIV-associated nephropathy (HIVAN)", "d": "Minimal change disease", "ans": "C", "e": "HIV-associated nephropathy (HIVAN) fits 40-year-old with HIV on HAART presenting with proteinuria, hypertension, and FSGS on biopsy; characteristic collapsing variant of FSGS in HIV patients with predilection for African ancestry.<br><br>Standard HIVAN features: collapsing FSGS variant, severe proteinuria, hypertension, progressive renal dysfunction, predilection for patients of African descent (APOL1 risk variants). Treatment: HAART (essential), ACE inhibitors/ARBs, addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>Membranous nephropathy (option A); Diabetic nephropathy (option B) features Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules; Minimal change disease (option D) is not the correct choice, none being HIV-associated FSGS like HIV-associated nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 70-year-old woman is started on NSAIDs for arthritis. She develops AKI. Her baseline creatinine was 1.0 mg/dL and now is 2.8 mg/dL. The mechanism of NSAID-induced AKI is:", "a": "Direct tubular toxicity", "b": "Obstruction of collecting ducts", "c": "Interstitial fibrosis", "d": "Inhibition of prostaglandin-mediated afferent arteriolar dilation causing reduced GFR", "ans": "D", "e": "Inhibition of prostaglandin-mediated afferent arteriolar vasodilation causes AKI in 70-year-old on NSAIDs; characteristic loss of compensatory vasodilation in elderly with renal disease produces functional renal impairment.<br><br>Standard NSAID nephrotoxicity mechanisms: inhibition of cyclooxygenase reduces prostaglandin synthesis, loss of afferent arteriolar vasodilation in volume-depleted or CKD patients, acute interstitial nephritis, papillary necrosis (chronic use), sodium and water retention.<br><br>Direct tubular toxicity (option A); Obstruction of collecting ducts (option B); Interstitial fibrosis (option C) is not the correct choice, none being elderly NSAID AKI mechanism like inhibition of prostaglandin-mediated afferent arteriolar vasodilation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 25-year-old man presents with recurrent haematuria after every upper respiratory infection. His father had renal failure at age 40. Renal biopsy shows thinning and splitting of GBM with “basket-weave” pattern on electron microscopy. Diagnosis:", "a": "MPGN", "b": "Thin basement membrane disease", "c": "Alport syndrome", "d": "IgA nephropathy", "ans": "C", "e": "Alport syndrome fits 25-year-old with recurrent haematuria after URTIs, sensorineural deafness, family history of renal failure; characteristic type IV collagen defect produces glomerular bleeding and basement membrane abnormalities.<br><br>Standard Alport features: X-linked dominant most common, persistent microscopic haematuria, episodic macroscopic haematuria after URTI, progressive proteinuria, ESRD in 2nd-4th decade. Extra-renal: sensorineural deafness, anterior lenticonus, perimacular flecks.<br><br>MPGN (option A); Thin basement membrane disease (option B) is benign familial haematuria without deafness; IgA nephropathy (option D) is synpharyngitic but lacks deafness, none being haematuria post-URTI with sensorineural deafness like Alport syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 48-year-old woman presents with flank pain, haematuria and a palpable abdominal mass. CT shows a large renal mass with areas of necrosis. She also has polycythaemia. The most likely paraneoplastic mechanism of polycythaemia:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "High altitude adaptation", "c": "Bone marrow infiltration", "d": "Ectopic EPO production by renal cell carcinoma", "ans": "D", "e": "Ectopic EPO production by renal cell carcinoma fits 48-year-old with flank pain, haematuria, polycythaemia; characteristic paraneoplastic EPO production causes erythrocytosis (versus typical CKD anaemia).<br><br>Standard RCC features: classic triad in 10 percent, paraneoplastic syndromes. Treatment: surgical resection (radical nephrectomy), targeted therapy for metastatic disease.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is not the correct choice; High altitude adaptation (option B) is not the correct choice; Bone marrow infiltration (option C) is not the correct choice, none being flank pain with polycythaemia like ectopic EPO production by renal cell carcinoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient develops oliguria after contrast-induced nephropathy (CIN). The best preventive strategy proven to reduce CIN is:", "a": "N-acetylcysteine", "b": "IV sodium bicarbonate alone", "c": "Adequate pre- and post-procedure IV hydration with normal saline", "d": "Prophylactic dialysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Adequate pre- and post-procedure IV hydration with normal saline prevents contrast-induced nephropathy oliguria; characteristic volume expansion before and after contrast reduces nephrotoxicity.<br><br>Standard CIN prevention: isotonic saline 1 mL/kg/hour for 6-12 hours before and after contrast, minimising contrast volume, avoiding nephrotoxins, using iso-osmolar or low-osmolar contrast. N-acetylcysteine and sodium bicarbonate not proven beneficial.<br><br>N-acetylcysteine (option A); IV sodium bicarbonate alone (option B); Prophylactic dialysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CIN oliguria prevention like adequate pre- and post-procedure IV hydration with normal saline.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with CKD on ACE inhibitor develops sudden worsening of renal function. Renal artery Doppler shows high resistance waveform bilaterally. Most likely diagnosis:", "a": "Acute tubular necrosis", "b": "Acute interstitial nephritis", "c": "Renal vein thrombosis", "d": "Bilateral renal artery stenosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Bilateral renal artery stenosis fits CKD patient on ACE inhibitor with sudden worsening renal function and AKI; characteristic ACE inhibition removes angiotensin II-mediated efferent arteriolar constriction which is essential for GFR in stenotic kidneys.<br><br>Standard bilateral RAS features: unexplained CKD, refractory hypertension, AKI on ACE inhibitor/ARB, abdominal bruit, flash pulmonary oedema, asymmetric kidney sizes. Diagnosis: Doppler ultrasound, CT/MR angiography, renal artery angiography.<br><br>Acute tubular necrosis (option A); Acute interstitial nephritis (option B); Renal vein thrombosis (option C), none being ACE inhibitor-induced AKI cause like bilateral renal artery stenosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 60-year-old man presents with hypertension, haematuria and palpable bilateral flank masses. CT shows multiple bilateral cysts replacing renal parenchyma. He also mentions a subarachnoid haemorrhage in his brother. Most likely associated intracranial finding:", "a": "Subdural hygroma", "b": "Berry (saccular) aneurysm", "c": "Meningioma", "d": "AVM", "ans": "B", "e": "Berry (saccular) aneurysm fits 60-year-old with hypertension, haematuria, palpable kidneys, family history of stroke; characteristic ADPKD association with intracranial aneurysms.<br><br>Standard ADPKD features: PKD1 (85 percent) or PKD2 (15 percent), bilateral renal cysts, extrarenal manifestations (hepatic cysts, intracranial aneurysms in 5-10 percent, mitral valve prolapse). Treatment: BP control, tolvaptan.<br><br>Subdural hygroma (option A) is not the correct choice; Meningioma (option C) is not the correct choice; AVM (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ADPKD intracranial association like berry (saccular) aneurysm.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient has Na⁺ 118 mEq/L, serum osmolality 245 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality 520 mOsm/kg, urine Na⁺ 55 mEq/L. Patient is euvolaemic. Diagnosis:", "a": "SIADH", "b": "Cerebral salt wasting", "c": "Psychogenic polydipsia", "d": "Hypothyroidism-induced hyponatraemia", "ans": "A", "e": "SIADH fits patient with Na 118, serum osmolality 245, high urine osmolality 600, high urine sodium 50; characteristic euvolaemic hyponatraemia with inappropriately concentrated urine and elevated urinary sodium.<br><br>Standard SIADH criteria: euvolaemic hyponatraemia, plasma osmolality under 275 mOsm/kg, urine osmolality over 100 mOsm/kg, urine sodium over 30 mEq/L, normal thyroid and adrenal function. Causes: drugs, CNS disorders, lung disease, malignancy.<br><br>Cerebral salt wasting (option B); Psychogenic polydipsia (option C); Hypothyroidism-induced hyponatraemia (option D), none being euvolaemic hyponatraemia with concentrated urine and high urine Na like SIADH.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Treatment of SIADH includes all EXCEPT:", "a": "Tolvaptan (V2 receptor antagonist)", "b": "Desmopressin (DDAVP)", "c": "Hypertonic saline in severe symptomatic cases", "d": "Fluid restriction", "ans": "B", "e": "Desmopressin (DDAVP) is NOT used for SIADH treatment; characteristic ADH analogue would worsen SIADH (already excess ADH effect). DDAVP is for diabetes insipidus.<br><br>Standard SIADH treatment: fluid restriction, oral salt tablets, loop diuretics (furosemide), demeclocycline, vasopressin receptor antagonists (vaptans - tolvaptan, conivaptan), 3 percent hypertonic saline for severe symptomatic hyponatraemia.<br><br>Tolvaptan (V2 receptor antagonist) (option A) is not the correct choice; Hypertonic saline in severe symptomatic cases (option C) is not the correct choice; Fluid restriction (option D) IS first-line SIADH treatment, none being NOT SIADH treatment like desmopressin (DDAVP).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Addison’s disease presents with hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia. The mechanism is:", "a": "Renin deficiency", "b": "Cortisol excess causing water retention", "c": "Aldosterone deficiency — Na⁺ wasting and K⁺ retention by kidneys", "d": "Excess ADH secretion", "ans": "C", "e": "Aldosterone deficiency causing sodium wasting and potassium retention fits Addison's disease with hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia; characteristic adrenal insufficiency reduces mineralocorticoid effect.<br><br>Standard Addison's features: primary adrenal insufficiency, hyperpigmentation (high ACTH), hyponatraemia, hyperkalaemia, hypoglycaemia, hypotension, fatigue. Diagnosis: low cortisol, high ACTH, positive ACTH stimulation test.<br><br>Renin deficiency (option A) is not the correct choice; Cortisol excess causing water retention (option B) is not the correct choice; Excess ADH secretion (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Addison's hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia mechanism like aldosterone deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient presents with weakness, polyuria and hypertension. Labs: K⁺ 2.8 mEq/L, Na⁺ 148 mEq/L, metabolic alkalosis, low renin, high aldosterone. CT shows left adrenal adenoma. Diagnosis:", "a": "Conn’s syndrome (Primary hyperaldosteronism)", "b": "Renal artery stenosis", "c": "Cushing’s syndrome", "d": "Phaeochromocytoma", "ans": "A", "e": "Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism) fits patient with weakness, polyuria, hypertension, hypokalaemia, metabolic alkalosis; characteristic excess aldosterone produces sodium retention, potassium wasting, hypertension.<br><br>Standard Conn's syndrome features: refractory hypertension, hypokalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, low renin, high aldosterone (or normal aldosterone with very low renin). Causes: aldosterone-producing adenoma, bilateral adrenal hyperplasia.<br><br>Renal artery stenosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Cushing’s syndrome (option C) is not the correct choice; Phaeochromocytoma (option D) is not the correct choice, none being hypertension with hypokalaemia and metabolic alkalosis like Conn's syndrome.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In type 1 RTA (distal), the urine pH during acidosis is:", "a": "Exactly 7.0", "b": ">5.5 (inappropriately alkaline)", "c": "Variable depending on diet", "d": "<5.3", "ans": "B", "e": "Over 5.5 (inappropriately alkaline) urine pH during acidosis characterises type 1 (distal) RTA; characteristic inability to acidify urine despite systemic acidosis reflects distal H+ secretion defect.<br><br>Standard type 1 (distal) RTA features: hyperchloraemic non-anion gap metabolic acidosis, urine pH over 5.5 despite acidosis, hypokalaemia, kidney stones, nephrocalcinosis, osteomalacia. Treatment: bicarbonate replacement (oral), addressing underlying cause.<br><br>Exactly 7.0 (option A); Variable depending on diet (option C); <5.3 (option D) is not the correct choice, none being type 1 RTA urine pH during acidosis like over 5.5 (inappropriately alkaline).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Type 4 RTA is associated with:", "a": "Amphotericin B toxicity", "b": "Fanconi syndrome", "c": "Sjögren syndrome", "d": "Hyporeninism-hypoaldosteronism (commonly in diabetic nephropathy)", "ans": "D", "e": "Hyporeninism-hypoaldosteronism (commonly in diabetes) is associated with type 4 RTA; characteristic reduced aldosterone production or response impairs distal nephron sodium-potassium exchange.<br><br>Standard type 4 RTA features: hyperchloraemic non-anion gap metabolic acidosis, hyperkalaemia, urine pH variable, associated with diabetes mellitus (most common), CKD, sickle cell disease, lupus nephritis, drugs. Treatment: fludrocortisone, addressing hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Amphotericin B toxicity (option A); Fanconi syndrome (option B) is not the correct choice; Sjögren syndrome (option C) is not the correct choice, none being type 4 RTA association like hyporeninism-hypoaldosteronism (commonly in diabetes).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with chronic diarrhoea develops metabolic acidosis. Urine anion gap is NEGATIVE. This indicates:", "a": "Lactic acidosis", "b": "Type 1 RTA", "c": "Gastrointestinal bicarbonate loss (extrarenal cause) with appropriate renal NH₄⁺ excretion", "d": "Renal cause of acidosis", "ans": "C", "e": "Gastrointestinal bicarbonate loss (extrarenal cause) explains metabolic acidosis with hyperchloraemia in chronic diarrhoea; characteristic loss of bicarbonate-rich intestinal fluid produces non-anion gap acidosis with compensatory chloride retention.<br><br>Standard normal anion gap metabolic acidosis causes (USEDCARP): Ureteroenteric fistula, Saline infusion, Endocrine, Diarrhoea, Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors, Ammonium chloride, Renal tubular acidosis (types 1, 2), Pancreaticoduodenal fistula. Combined with addressing underlying cause, bicarbonate replacement.<br><br>Lactic acidosis (option A); Type 1 RTA (option B); Renal cause of acidosis (option D), none being chronic diarrhoea acidosis cause like gastrointestinal bicarbonate loss.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient on lithium develops nephrogenic diabetes insipidus. The mechanism is:", "a": "Destruction of hypothalamic nuclei", "b": "Autoimmune destruction of posterior pituitary", "c": "Excess renin secretion", "d": "Lithium blocks ADH action on V2 receptors in collecting duct, preventing aquaporin-2 insertion", "ans": "D", "e": "Lithium blocks ADH action on V2 receptors in collecting duct causing nephrogenic diabetes insipidus; characteristic inhibition of aquaporin-2 insertion impairs water reabsorption.<br><br>Standard lithium-induced nephrogenic DI features: polyuria, polydipsia, dilute urine despite hypernatraemia, no response to desmopressin. Mechanism: lithium accumulates in collecting duct cells via ENaC, inhibits adenylyl cyclase, reduces aquaporin-2 expression.<br><br>Destruction of hypothalamic nuclei (option A); Autoimmune destruction of posterior pituitary (option B); Excess renin secretion (option C), none being lithium nephrogenic DI mechanism like blocks ADH action on V2 receptors in collecting duct.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient has pH 7.28, PaCO₂ 20 mmHg, HCO₃ 9 mEq/L. Expected PaCO₂ compensation using Winter’s formula:", "a": "20 mmHg", "b": "12 mmHg", "c": "17 mmHg", "d": "25 mmHg", "ans": "A", "e": "20 mmHg expected PaCO2 fits pH 7.28, HCO3 9 in metabolic acidosis; characteristic Winters formula calculation predicts respiratory compensation (1.5 x HCO3 + 8 = 21.5 mmHg).<br><br>Standard Winters formula for metabolic acidosis: expected PaCO2 = (1.5 x HCO3) + 8 +/- 2. For HCO3 9: (1.5 x 9) + 8 = 21.5 mmHg (range 19.5-23.5).<br><br>12 mmHg (option B); 17 mmHg (option C); 25 mmHg (option D) is not the correct choice, none being expected PaCO2 for metabolic acidosis with HCO3 9 like 20 mmHg.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient has pH 7.50, PaCO₂ 48 mmHg, HCO₃ 36 mEq/L, K⁺ 2.9 mEq/L. Most likely diagnosis:", "a": "Mixed respiratory and metabolic alkalosis", "b": "Primary respiratory alkalosis", "c": "Compensated respiratory acidosis", "d": "Metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation", "ans": "D", "e": "Metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation fits pH 7.50, PaCO2 48, HCO3 36, K 3.0; characteristic primary metabolic alkalosis with appropriate respiratory hypoventilation.<br><br>Standard metabolic alkalosis features: pH over 7.45, HCO3 over 26, compensatory hypoventilation. Common causes: vomiting/NG suction (loss of HCl), diuretic use, Conn's syndrome, Cushing's, hypokalaemia.<br><br>Mixed respiratory and metabolic alkalosis (option A); Primary respiratory alkalosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Compensated respiratory acidosis (option C) is not the correct choice, none being pH 7.50, HCO3 36, low K acid-base disorder like metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Fanconi syndrome involves dysfunction of the proximal tubule causing urinary loss of all EXCEPT:", "a": "Glucose (despite normal blood glucose)", "b": "Potassium (hyperkalaemia)", "c": "Uric acid", "d": "Phosphate", "ans": "B", "e": "Potassium (hyperkalaemia) is NOT Fanconi syndrome feature; characteristic Fanconi syndrome features proximal tubular dysfunction with potassium wasting (hypokalaemia), not hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Standard Fanconi syndrome features: generalised proximal tubular dysfunction, glycosuria, aminoaciduria, phosphaturia (hypophosphataemia), bicarbonaturia (type 2 RTA), uricosuria (hypouricaemia), proteinuria, potassium wasting (hypokalaemia). Causes: cystinosis, Wilson disease, multiple myeloma, tenofovir, heavy metals.<br><br>Glucose (despite normal blood glucose) (option A) is not the correct choice; Uric acid (option C) is not the correct choice; Phosphate (option D) IS Fanconi syndrome feature (phosphaturia), none being NOT Fanconi syndrome feature like potassium (hyperkalaemia).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which drug most commonly causes Fanconi syndrome in HIV patients on HAART?", "a": "Tenofovir", "b": "Efavirenz", "c": "Emtricitabine", "d": "Lopinavir", "ans": "A", "e": "Tenofovir most commonly causes Fanconi syndrome in HIV patients; characteristic nucleotide analogue accumulates in proximal tubular cells producing dose-dependent toxicity.<br><br>Standard tenofovir nephrotoxicity features: Fanconi syndrome (proximal tubulopathy), AKI, decline in eGFR. Risk factors: high dose, prolonged use, concurrent nephrotoxins, advanced HIV. Prevention: tenofovir alafenamide instead of TDF (less nephrotoxic).<br><br>Efavirenz (option B) causes CNS effects (not Fanconi); Emtricitabine (option C) is not the correct choice; Lopinavir (option D) is not the correct choice, none being HIV Fanconi syndrome cause like tenofovir.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with sickle cell disease develops inability to concentrate urine and papillary necrosis. The mechanism is:", "a": "Iron deposition in tubules", "b": "Sickling in vasa recta of renal medulla causing infarction", "c": "Immune complex deposition", "d": "Complement activation", "ans": "B", "e": "Sickling in vasa recta of renal medulla causing infarction explains sickle cell disease patient with inability to concentrate urine; characteristic medullary hypoxia and hypertonicity promote sickling, infarction, papillary necrosis.<br><br>Standard sickle cell nephropathy features: hyposthenuria, microscopic and macroscopic haematuria, renal papillary necrosis, hyposthenuria, FSGS in adults, renal medullary carcinoma. Treatment: hydration, hydroxyurea, addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>Iron deposition in tubules (option A); Immune complex deposition (option C); Complement activation (option D), none being sickle cell concentrating defect mechanism like sickling in vasa recta of renal medulla causing infarction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Analgesic nephropathy characteristically causes:", "a": "Membranous nephropathy", "b": "Glomerulosclerosis", "c": "Thin basement membrane disease", "d": "Renal papillary necrosis with interstitial nephritis", "ans": "D", "e": "Renal papillary necrosis with interstitial nephritis characterises analgesic nephropathy; characteristic chronic high-dose analgesic use produces medullary damage and chronic interstitial inflammation.<br><br>Standard analgesic nephropathy features: long-term combined analgesic use, papillary necrosis, chronic interstitial nephritis, reduced renal medullary blood flow, increased urothelial malignancy risk. Treatment: discontinue analgesics, supportive care.<br><br>Membranous nephropathy (option A) is not the correct choice; Glomerulosclerosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Thin basement membrane disease (option C) is not the correct choice, none being analgesic nephropathy characteristic like renal papillary necrosis with interstitial nephritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Myeloma cast nephropathy (myeloma kidney) results from:", "a": "Hypercalcaemia-induced nephrocalcinosis", "b": "Light chain precipitation in distal tubules forming obstructing casts with giant cell reaction", "c": "Heavy chain deposition disease", "d": "Amyloid deposition in glomeruli", "ans": "B", "e": "Light chain precipitation in distal tubules forming casts causes myeloma cast nephropathy; characteristic Bence-Jones proteins combine with Tamm-Horsfall protein producing characteristic casts and tubular obstruction.<br><br>Standard myeloma kidney mechanism: free light chains filtered, precipitate with Tamm-Horsfall protein in distal tubules forming dense casts. Treatment: chemotherapy (bortezomib), plasmapheresis for severe AKI.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia-induced nephrocalcinosis (option A); Heavy chain deposition disease (option C); Amyloid deposition in glomeruli (option D), none being myeloma cast nephropathy mechanism like light chain precipitation in distal tubules forming casts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 25-year-old woman with hypertension has renal artery stenosis on angiography showing “string of beads” appearance. Diagnosis:", "a": "Takayasu arteritis", "b": "Polyarteritis nodosa", "c": "Atherosclerotic renal artery stenosis", "d": "Fibromuscular dysplasia", "ans": "D", "e": "Fibromuscular dysplasia fits 25-year-old woman with hypertension and renal artery 'string of beads' appearance; characteristic non-atherosclerotic vascular disease predominantly affects young women.<br><br>Standard fibromuscular dysplasia features: middle/distal renal artery involvement, characteristic 'string of beads' appearance on angiography, women aged 20-50, may affect carotid and other arteries. Treatment: percutaneous transluminal angioplasty (often curative), antihypertensives.<br><br>Takayasu arteritis (option A), branches); Polyarteritis nodosa (option B); Atherosclerotic renal artery stenosis (option C) affects older patients with cardiovascular risk factors, none being young woman with string of beads RAS like fibromuscular dysplasia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Renovascular hypertension due to renal artery stenosis is best initially investigated by:", "a": "MRI without contrast", "b": "Renal angiography", "c": "Duplex Doppler ultrasound of renal arteries", "d": "Captopril-enhanced renal scan", "ans": "C", "e": "Duplex Doppler ultrasound of renal arteries best screens for renovascular hypertension; characteristic non-invasive imaging avoids contrast nephrotoxicity while providing functional and anatomical assessment.<br><br>Standard renovascular hypertension screening: Doppler ultrasound, CT angiography, MR angiography, captopril renal scan (functional assessment). Confirmatory: catheter angiography (gold standard but invasive).<br><br>MRI without contrast (option A) is not the correct choice; Renal angiography (option B) is not the correct choice; Captopril-enhanced renal scan (option D) is not the correct choice, none being renovascular hypertension screening like duplex Doppler ultrasound of renal arteries.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Thrombotic microangiopathy causing AKI is seen in all EXCEPT:", "a": "Minimal change disease", "b": "TTP", "c": "HUS", "d": "Malignant hypertension", "ans": "A", "e": "Minimal change disease does NOT cause thrombotic microangiopathy with AKI; characteristic podocyte disease with foot process effacement features nephrotic syndrome without TMA.<br><br>Standard TMA causes with AKI: thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura, haemolytic uraemic syndrome, malignant hypertension, scleroderma renal crisis, drugs (calcineurin inhibitors, anti-VEGF), pregnancy-related (HELLP, postpartum), antiphospholipid syndrome.<br><br>TTP (option B) is not the correct choice; HUS (option C) is not the correct choice; Malignant hypertension (option D) IS TMA cause, none being NOT thrombotic microangiopathy AKI cause like minimal change disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A child develops bloody diarrhoea followed by oliguria, haemolytic anaemia and thrombocytopenia. Peripheral smear shows schistocytes. Most likely causative organism:", "a": "Campylobacter jejuni", "b": "E. coli O157:H7", "c": "Salmonella typhi", "d": "Shigella sonnei", "ans": "B", "e": "E. coli O157:H7 (Shiga-toxin producing) causes typical haemolytic uraemic syndrome in child with bloody diarrhoea, oliguria, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia; characteristic shiga toxin damages endothelium triggering microvascular thrombi.<br><br>Standard typical HUS features: prodromal bloody diarrhoea, 5-10 days later develops triad. Treatment: supportive care, avoid antibiotics (may worsen toxin release), addressing complications.<br><br>Campylobacter jejuni (option A) is not the correct choice; Salmonella typhi (option C) is not the correct choice; Shigella sonnei (option D) is not the correct choice, none being typical HUS pathogen like E. coli O157:H7.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Scleroderma renal crisis is characterized by:", "a": "Gradual onset hypertension over years", "b": "Nephrotic syndrome", "c": "Haematuria with RBC casts", "d": "Abrupt severe hypertension with AKI and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Abrupt severe hypertension with AKI and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia characterise scleroderma renal crisis; characteristic onion-skin appearance of small arteries on biopsy reflects intimal proliferation.<br><br>Standard scleroderma renal crisis features: malignant hypertension (often new onset), AKI, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, encephalopathy. Risk factors: diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis, anti-RNA polymerase III antibodies, recent corticosteroid use, early disease.<br><br>Gradual onset hypertension over years (option A); Nephrotic syndrome (option B); Haematuria with RBC casts (option C), none being scleroderma renal crisis characteristic like abrupt severe hypertension with AKI and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common type of renal calculus is:", "a": "Calcium oxalate stone", "b": "Struvite stone", "c": "Cystine stone", "d": "Uric acid stone", "ans": "A", "e": "Calcium oxalate stone is most common type of renal calculus; characteristic 75-80 percent of stones are calcium-based with envelope-shaped or dumbbell crystals.<br><br>Standard calcium oxalate stone features: radio-opaque on X-ray, hypercalciuria or hyperoxaluria common causes, idiopathic majority. Treatment: hydration (over 2.5 L/day), dietary modifications, thiazide diuretics (reduce urinary calcium), potassium citrate.<br><br>Struvite stone (option B) is not the correct choice; Cystine stone (option C) is not the correct choice; Uric acid stone (option D) is not the correct choice, none being most common renal calculus like calcium oxalate stone.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with recurrent UTIs caused by urease-producing organisms develops large staghorn calculi. Stone type:", "a": "Cystine", "b": "Struvite", "c": "Calcium oxalate", "d": "Uric acid", "ans": "B", "e": "Struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate) stones form with urease-producing organisms; characteristic Proteus mirabilis, Klebsiella, Staphylococcus saprophyticus produce ammonia raising urine pH allowing struvite crystallisation.<br><br>Standard struvite stone features: alkaline urine, staghorn calculi, more common in women, complication of chronic UTI. Treatment: complete stone removal, urease inhibitors (acetohydroxamic acid), addressing underlying infection.<br><br>Cystine (option A) is genetic disorder (not urease); Calcium oxalate (option C) is not urease-related stone type; Uric acid (option D) is acidic urine stone (not urease), none being urease-related stone type like struvite.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Uric acid stones are unique because they are:", "a": "Radiolucent on plain X-ray but visible on CT", "b": "Radiopaque on plain X-ray", "c": "Always associated with gout", "d": "Only visible on ultrasound", "ans": "A", "e": "Radiolucent on plain X-ray but visible on CT is unique feature of uric acid stones; characteristic lack of calcium content makes them invisible on conventional radiography while CT detects all stone types.<br><br>Standard uric acid stone features: form in acidic urine (pH under 5.5), risk factors. Treatment: hydration, urine alkalinisation, allopurinol or febuxostat, dietary modification.<br><br>Radiopaque on plain X-ray (option B); Always associated with gout (option C); Only visible on ultrasound (option D), none being uric acid stone unique feature like radiolucent on plain X-ray but visible on CT.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with Crohn’s disease and terminal ileal resection develops calcium oxalate stones. The mechanism is:", "a": "Increased dietary oxalate intake", "b": "Alkaline urine", "c": "Low urine citrate", "d": "Enteric hyperoxaluria", "ans": "D", "e": "Enteric hyperoxaluria fits Crohn's disease patient with terminal ileal resection developing calcium oxalate stones; characteristic fat malabsorption allows free oxalate absorption from colon (calcium bound to fat instead of oxalate).<br><br>Standard enteric hyperoxaluria mechanism: bile salt malabsorption (Crohn's, gastric bypass), calcium binds free fatty acids, free oxalate absorbed in colon. Treatment: low-oxalate diet, calcium with meals, cholestyramine.<br><br>Increased dietary oxalate intake (option A); Alkaline urine (option B); Low urine citrate (option C), none being post-ileal resection calcium oxalate stones like enteric hyperoxaluria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Cystinuria is caused by a defect in transport of which amino acids?", "a": "COLA (Cystine, Ornithine, Lysine, Arginine)", "b": "Branched chain amino acids", "c": "Aromatic amino acids", "d": "Tryptophan only", "ans": "A", "e": "COLA (cystine, ornithine, lysine, arginine) transport defect causes cystinuria; characteristic mutation in SLC3A1 or SLC7A9 genes impairs reabsorption of these dibasic amino acids in proximal tubule.<br><br>Standard cystinuria features: autosomal recessive, hexagonal crystals in urine, recurrent cystine stones, positive cyanide-nitroprusside test. Treatment: high fluid intake (over 3 L/day), urine alkalinisation, low sodium and methionine diet, tiopronin or D-penicillamine (binds cystine).<br><br>Branched chain amino acids (option B); Aromatic amino acids (option C); Tryptophan only (option D) is not the correct choice, none being cystinuria transport defect like COLA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Kt/V is a measure of dialysis adequacy. “K” stands for:", "a": "Kidney function", "b": "Potassium clearance", "c": "Kilogram of patient weight", "d": "Dialyser clearance of urea", "ans": "D", "e": "Dialyser clearance of urea is what 'K' stands for in Kt/V measurement of dialysis adequacy; characteristic mathematical model quantifies fractional urea clearance per session.<br><br>Standard Kt/V components: K, t, V (urea distribution volume in mL, approximates total body water). Target single-pool Kt/V over 1.2 per session for 3 sessions/week.<br><br>Kidney function (option A) is not the correct choice; Potassium clearance (option B) is not the correct choice; Kilogram of patient weight (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Kt/V 'K' meaning like dialyser clearance of urea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient on haemodialysis develops hypotension during a session. The MOST common cause is:", "a": "Excessive ultrafiltration rate causing intravascular volume depletion", "b": "Dialysate contamination", "c": "Air embolism", "d": "Membrane reaction", "ans": "A", "e": "Excessive ultrafiltration rate causing intravascular volume depletion causes intradialytic hypotension; characteristic rapid fluid removal exceeds plasma refilling rate from interstitium.<br><br>Standard intradialytic hypotension features: occurs in 10-30 percent of haemodialysis sessions, more common with high interdialytic weight gain, prolonged hypotension associated with worse outcomes. Prevention: avoiding excessive weight gain between sessions, addressing dry weight, longer/slower sessions, sodium modelling, midodrine pre-dialysis, cool dialysate.<br><br>Dialysate contamination (option B); Air embolism (option C); Membrane reaction (option D), none being intradialytic hypotension cause like excessive ultrafiltration rate causing intravascular volume depletion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Dialysis disequilibrium syndrome occurs due to:", "a": "Air embolism", "b": "Haemolysis during dialysis", "c": "Rapid removal of urea causing cerebral oedema", "d": "Electrolyte imbalance post-dialysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Rapid removal of urea causing cerebral oedema causes dialysis disequilibrium syndrome; characteristic osmotic gradient develops between blood (rapidly cleared) and brain (slower equilibration).<br><br>Standard DDS features: headache, nausea, vomiting, confusion, seizures, coma in severe cases. Mechanism: rapid removal of urea from blood while brain urea slower to equilibrate, creating osmotic gradient drawing water into brain.<br><br>Air embolism (option A); Haemolysis during dialysis (option B); Electrolyte imbalance post-dialysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being dialysis disequilibrium syndrome like rapid removal of urea causing cerebral oedema.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which of the following is an absolute contraindication to peritoneal dialysis?", "a": "Obliterated peritoneal cavity due to previous extensive abdominal surgery", "b": "Elderly age", "c": "Blindness", "d": "Diabetes mellitus", "ans": "A", "e": "Obliterated peritoneal cavity due to previous extensive surgery is absolute contraindication to peritoneal dialysis; characteristic loss of peritoneal surface area precludes effective dialysis.<br><br>Standard absolute PD contraindications: obliterated peritoneal cavity (extensive adhesions), large abdominal hernias (unrepaired), peritoneal fibrosis, large abdominal wall defects, severe inflammatory bowel disease (active), patient or family unable to perform exchanges, lack of suitable home environment. Combined with addressing alternatives.<br><br>Elderly age (option B); Blindness (option C); Diabetes mellitus (option D), none being absolute PD contraindication like obliterated peritoneal cavity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The most common organism causing peritonitis in CAPD patients is:", "a": "Pseudomonas aeruginosa", "b": "E. coli", "c": "Candida albicans", "d": "Staphylococcus epidermidis", "ans": "D", "e": "Staphylococcus epidermidis is most common organism causing peritonitis in CAPD patients; characteristic skin commensal contaminates catheter exit site during exchanges.<br><br>Standard CAPD peritonitis features: cloudy dialysate effluent (dialysate WBC over 100/microL with over 50 percent neutrophils), abdominal pain, fever. Common organisms: coagulase-negative staphylococci (S epidermidis most common), S aureus, gram-negative bacteria, fungi (Candida).<br><br>Pseudomonas aeruginosa (option A) is less common but problematic; E. coli (option B) is less common than staphylococcal; Candida albicans (option C) is not the correct choice, none being most common CAPD peritonitis organism like Staphylococcus epidermidis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient on long-term haemodialysis develops carpal tunnel syndrome and amyloid arthropathy. The deposited protein is:", "a": "Beta-2 microglobulin", "b": "Transthyretin", "c": "AL amyloid", "d": "Serum amyloid A", "ans": "A", "e": "Beta-2 microglobulin causes carpal tunnel syndrome in long-term haemodialysis; characteristic dialysis-related amyloidosis from beta-2 microglobulin accumulation in joints, bones, soft tissues.<br><br>Standard dialysis-related amyloidosis features: long-term dialysis (over 10 years), carpal tunnel syndrome (most common), destructive spondyloarthropathy, bone cysts, soft tissue masses. Mechanism: beta-2 microglobulin (11 kDa) poorly removed by low-flux dialysis, accumulates and deposits as amyloid.<br><br>Transthyretin (option B); AL amyloid (option C) is not the correct choice; Serum amyloid A (option D) is not the correct choice, none being long-term haemodialysis CTS cause like beta-2 microglobulin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The preferred vascular access for long-term haemodialysis in order of preference is:", "a": "CVC > AVG > AVF", "b": "AVG > AVF > CVC", "c": "CVC > AVF > AVG", "d": "AVF > AVG > tunnelled CVC", "ans": "D", "e": "AVF over AVG over tunnelled CVC describes preferred vascular access hierarchy for long-term haemodialysis; characteristic native fistula provides best longevity and lowest complications.<br><br>Standard access hierarchy: AVF, AVG, tunnelled CVC. Combined with vein preservation in CKD patients, early access creation.<br><br>CVC > AVG > AVF (option A) is not the correct choice; AVG > AVF > CVC (option B) is not the correct choice; CVC > AVF > AVG (option C) is not the correct choice, none being preferred long-term haemodialysis access hierarchy like AVF over AVG over tunnelled CVC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Hyperacute rejection of a renal transplant occurs within minutes to hours due to:", "a": "T-cell mediated cytotoxicity", "b": "NK cell activity", "c": "Pre-formed recipient antibodies against donor HLA", "d": "Complement deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Pre-formed recipient antibodies against donor HLA cause hyperacute rejection of renal transplant within minutes to hours; characteristic immediate immune attack on transplanted kidney.<br><br>Standard hyperacute rejection features: occurs within minutes to hours of transplantation, mediated by pre-formed antibodies, causes immediate thrombosis and necrosis. Prevention: cross-match testing pre-transplant, ABO compatibility, desensitisation protocols for sensitised patients.<br><br>T-cell mediated cytotoxicity (option A); NK cell activity (option B) is not the correct choice; Complement deficiency (option D) is not the correct choice, none being hyperacute rejection mechanism like pre-formed recipient antibodies against donor HLA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Acute rejection of renal transplant typically occurs within:", "a": "Days to 3 months post-transplant", "b": "Minutes to hours", "c": ">5 years post-transplant", "d": "1–5 years post-transplant", "ans": "A", "e": "Days to 3 months post-transplant is typical timing of acute rejection; characteristic T-cell mediated immune response develops as immunosuppression takes effect.<br><br>Standard acute rejection types: T-cell mediated rejection, antibody-mediated rejection. Treatment: pulse corticosteroids (cellular), plasmapheresis plus IVIG plus rituximab (antibody-mediated).<br><br>Minutes to hours (option B) is not the correct choice; >5 years post-transplant (option C) is not the correct choice; 1–5 years post-transplant (option D) is not the correct choice, none being acute rejection typical timing like days to 3 months post-transplant.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Calcineurin inhibitors used in transplant cause nephrotoxicity through:", "a": "Immune complex deposition", "b": "Direct tubular toxicity", "c": "Interstitial fibrosis only", "d": "Afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction causing ischaemic nephropathy", "ans": "D", "e": "Afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction causing ischaemic injury is principal calcineurin inhibitor nephrotoxicity mechanism; characteristic vasoconstriction reduces renal perfusion contributing to acute and chronic injury.<br><br>Standard calcineurin inhibitor nephrotoxicity: acute, chronic. Combined with monitoring drug levels, dose adjustment, switching agents if severe.<br><br>Immune complex deposition (option A) is not principal mechanism; Direct tubular toxicity (option B) is not the correct choice; Interstitial fibrosis only (option C) is not the correct choice, none being calcineurin inhibitor nephrotoxicity mechanism like afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction causing ischaemic injury.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A renal transplant patient on cyclosporine develops gingival hyperplasia and hirsutism. Alternative immunosuppressant that avoids these side effects:", "a": "Tacrolimus", "b": "Azathioprine", "c": "Mycophenolate", "d": "Sirolimus", "ans": "A", "e": "Switching to tacrolimus addresses ciclosporin-induced gingival hyperplasia in renal transplant patient; characteristic tacrolimus lacks gingival hyperplasia side effect while providing similar immunosuppression.<br><br>Standard ciclosporin side effects: gingival hyperplasia, hirsutism, hypertension, hyperkalaemia, hypomagnesaemia, nephrotoxicity, neurotoxicity, glucose intolerance. Tacrolimus alternative: similar nephrotoxicity but lacks gingival hyperplasia and hirsutism, more potent immunosuppression, may cause more diabetes.<br><br>Azathioprine (option B); Mycophenolate (option C) is antimetabolite (not calcineurin inhibitor substitute); Sirolimus (option D) is mTOR inhibitor (different class with own side effects), none being ciclosporin gingival hyperplasia substitute like tacrolimus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "In CKD, the sequence of events in mineral bone disorder is:", "a": "High PTH → low phosphate → high calcium", "b": "Low Ca → high PTH → high phosphate → low Vitamin D", "c": "Low GFR → phosphate retention → low active Vit D → low Ca → high PTH → renal osteodystrophy", "d": "Low Vit D → low PTH → high phosphate", "ans": "C", "e": "Low GFR producing phosphate retention then low active vitamin D then hypocalcaemia then secondary hyperparathyroidism describes mineral bone disorder sequence in CKD.<br><br>Standard CKD-MBD mechanism: declining GFR reduces phosphate excretion, elevated FGF-23 suppresses 1-alpha-hydroxylase reducing calcitriol, hypocalcaemia stimulates PTH (secondary hyperparathyroidism) increasing bone resorption. Combined with addressing through phosphate binders and calcitriol replacement.<br><br>High GFR causing PTH elevation (option A) is incorrect direction; Vitamin D toxicity causing hypercalcaemia (option B) is opposite; Increased calcium absorption from gut (option D) is opposite, none being CKD-MBD sequence.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "X-ray of hands in a CKD patient shows subperiosteal bone resorption at radial aspect of middle phalanges. This is characteristic of:", "a": "Paget’s disease", "b": "Osteomalacia", "c": "Osteoporosis", "d": "Secondary hyperparathyroidism", "ans": "D", "e": "Secondary hyperparathyroidism explains subperiosteal bone resorption on hand X-ray in CKD patient; characteristic excess PTH stimulates osteoclast activity producing characteristic radiographic findings.<br><br>Standard radiographic features of secondary hyperparathyroidism: subperiosteal bone resorption, salt-and-pepper skull, brown tumours (focal lytic lesions), pseudofractures, chondrocalcinosis. Treatment: phosphate binders, active vitamin D analogues, cinacalcet, parathyroidectomy in severe refractory cases.<br><br>Paget’s disease (option A); Osteomalacia (option B) is not the correct choice; Osteoporosis (option C) shows generalised low bone density (different pattern), none being subperiosteal bone resorption cause in CKD like secondary hyperparathyroidism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Cardiovascular mortality in ESRD patients on dialysis is approximately how many times higher than the general population?", "a": "2–3 times", "b": "Same as general population", "c": "10–20 times", "d": "5–10 times", "ans": "C", "e": "10-20 times higher than general population is cardiovascular mortality in ESRD patients on dialysis; characteristic accelerated cardiovascular disease from uraemic vasculopathy and traditional risk factors.<br><br>Standard ESRD cardiovascular features: ischaemic heart disease, sudden cardiac death, heart failure, pericarditis, valvular calcification. Combined with addressing through BP control, statins, addressing anaemia, phosphate control.<br><br>2–3 times (option A) is not the correct choice; Same as general population (option B) is incorrect (markedly elevated in ESRD); 5–10 times (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ESRD cardiovascular mortality elevation like 10-20 times.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Which antihypertensive is CONTRAINDICATED in bilateral renal artery stenosis?", "a": "Amlodipine", "b": "ACE inhibitors/ARBs", "c": "Metoprolol", "d": "Hydralazine", "ans": "B", "e": "ACE inhibitors/ARBs are contraindicated in bilateral renal artery stenosis; characteristic removal of angiotensin II-mediated efferent arteriolar constriction precipitates AKI in stenotic kidneys.<br><br>Standard ACE inhibitor/ARB contraindications: bilateral renal artery stenosis, pregnancy (teratogenic), severe hyperkalaemia, history of angioedema. Combined with addressing through alternative antihypertensives (calcium channel blockers, beta blockers, alpha blockers, central acting agents, diuretics).<br><br>Amlodipine (option A) is not the correct choice; Metoprolol (option C) is not the correct choice; Hydralazine (option D) is not the correct choice, none being bilateral RAS contraindicated antihypertensive like ACE inhibitors/ARBs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A CKD patient on ACE inhibitor develops a 30% rise in creatinine after starting the drug. The appropriate action is:", "a": "Immediately stop ACE inhibitor", "b": "Double the dose", "c": "Add ARB", "d": "Accept rise up to 30% and continue monitoring", "ans": "D", "e": "Accept rise up to 30 percent and continue monitoring is appropriate for CKD patient on ACE inhibitor with creatinine rise; characteristic predictable haemodynamic effect on intraglomerular pressure does not require discontinuation.<br><br>Standard ACE inhibitor management: creatinine rise up to 30 percent acceptable, continue with monitoring, hold if rise over 30 percent (consider bilateral RAS). Monitor potassium weekly.<br><br>Immediately stop ACE inhibitor (option A); Double the dose (option B); Add ARB (option C), none being ACE inhibitor 30 percent creatinine rise management like accept and continue monitoring.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "SGLT-2 inhibitors are nephroprotective in CKD because they:", "a": "Increase GFR directly", "b": "Reduce intraglomerular hypertension via tubuloglomerular feedback", "c": "Increase erythropoietin production", "d": "Block aldosterone receptors", "ans": "B", "e": "Reduce intraglomerular hypertension via tubuloglomerular feedback explains SGLT-2 inhibitor nephroprotection in CKD; characteristic blocking proximal tubule glucose reabsorption increases distal sodium delivery activating tubuloglomerular feedback.<br><br>Standard SGLT-2 inhibitor renal mechanism: blocks proximal glucose reabsorption, increased distal sodium delivery to macula densa triggers tubuloglomerular feedback with afferent vasoconstriction, reduces intraglomerular pressure. Combined with addressing through reduced proteinuria, addressing modifiable factors.<br><br>Increase GFR directly (option A); Increase erythropoietin production (option C); Block aldosterone receptors (option D), none being SGLT-2 inhibitor nephroprotection like reduce intraglomerular hypertension via tubuloglomerular feedback.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A dialysis patient develops sudden onset chest pain with pericardial rub and diffuse ST elevation. Management:", "a": "Pericardiocentesis immediately", "b": "IV thrombolytics", "c": "Primary PCI", "d": "Urgent haemodialysis", "ans": "D", "e": "Urgent haemodialysis manages dialysis patient with sudden chest pain and pericardial friction rub; characteristic uraemic pericarditis from inadequate dialysis or new uraemia requires intensified renal replacement therapy.<br><br>Standard uraemic pericarditis features: friction rub, chest pain, ECG changes, pericardial effusion. Treatment: urgent daily haemodialysis for at least 1-2 weeks until resolution, addressing through addressing tamponade if develops.<br><br>Pericardiocentesis immediately (option A); IV thrombolytics (option B) is not the correct choice; Primary PCI (option C) is not the correct choice, none being uraemic pericarditis in dialysis patient management like urgent haemodialysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The trade-off hypothesis in CKD refers to:", "a": "Trading protein restriction for quality of life", "b": "Trading dialysis for transplant", "c": "PTH rise maintaining phosphate balance at expense of bone disease", "d": "Trading GFR loss for BP control", "ans": "C", "e": "PTH rise maintaining phosphate balance at expense of bone describes trade-off hypothesis in CKD; characteristic adaptive PTH elevation maintains phosphate homeostasis while contributing to renal osteodystrophy.<br><br>Standard trade-off hypothesis: declining GFR reduces phosphate excretion, hyperphosphataemia develops, PTH rises to maintain phosphate excretion. Trade-off is bone resorption and renal osteodystrophy.<br><br>Trading protein restriction for quality of life (option A); Trading dialysis for transplant (option B); Trading GFR loss for BP control (option D), none being CKD trade-off hypothesis like PTH rise maintaining phosphate balance at expense of bone.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Erythropoietin resistance in dialysis patients is most commonly caused by:", "a": "Folate deficiency", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Vitamin B12 deficiency", "d": "Antibodies to EPO", "ans": "B", "e": "Iron deficiency commonly causes erythropoietin resistance in dialysis patients; characteristic inadequate iron stores limit response to ESA therapy.<br><br>Standard ESA resistance causes: iron deficiency, inflammation (CRP elevated, hepcidin-mediated iron blockade), inadequate dialysis, hyperparathyroidism, malnutrition, vitamin deficiencies (folate, B12), aluminium toxicity, malignancy. Management: addressing underlying cause, IV iron supplementation.<br><br>Folate deficiency (option A) is less common cause than iron deficiency; Vitamin B12 deficiency (option C) is less common cause than iron deficiency; Antibodies to EPO (option D) is not the correct choice, none being ESA resistance common cause like iron deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A 45-year-old woman with sinusitis, cavitating lung nodules and positive c-ANCA with rising creatinine. Most appropriate treatment:", "a": "Oral steroids alone", "b": "Plasma exchange alone", "c": "Rituximab monotherapy", "d": "IV methylprednisolone + cyclophosphamide", "ans": "D", "e": "IV methylprednisolone plus cyclophosphamide treats 45-year-old with sinusitis, cavitating lung nodules, RPGN, c-ANCA positive (granulomatosis with polyangiitis); characteristic induction immunosuppression for ANCA-associated vasculitis.<br><br>Standard GPA treatment: induction with pulse methylprednisolone plus prednisolone, plus cyclophosphamide (oral or IV pulse) or rituximab (alternative). Maintenance with azathioprine, methotrexate, mycophenolate, or rituximab.<br><br>Oral steroids alone (option A) is not the correct choice; Plasma exchange alone (option B) is not the correct choice; Rituximab monotherapy (option C) is not the correct choice, none being ANCA-associated vasculitis induction treatment like IV methylprednisolone plus cyclophosphamide.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with anti-GBM disease and pulmonary haemorrhage requires additional treatment:", "a": "IV immunoglobulin", "b": "Rituximab", "c": "Plasma exchange", "d": "Splenectomy", "ans": "C", "e": "Plasma exchange treats anti-GBM disease with pulmonary haemorrhage; characteristic removal of pathogenic antibodies from circulation reduces immunological damage to kidneys and lungs.<br><br>Standard anti-GBM disease treatment: urgent plasmapheresis (daily or alternate-day exchanges until anti-GBM antibodies undetectable), corticosteroids (pulse methylprednisolone then prednisolone), cyclophosphamide. Combined with addressing pulmonary haemorrhage (oxygen, mechanical ventilation if needed).<br><br>IV immunoglobulin (option A) is not the correct choice; Rituximab (option B) is not the correct choice; Splenectomy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being anti-GBM disease with pulmonary haemorrhage treatment like plasma exchange.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "A patient with ADPKD has a 4 mm berry aneurysm. Best management:", "a": "Immediate clipping", "b": "Urgent coiling", "c": "No follow-up", "d": "Conservative with BP control and monitoring", "ans": "D", "e": "Conservative with BP control and monitoring is best for ADPKD patient with 4 mm berry aneurysm; characteristic small unruptured aneurysm below intervention threshold managed with risk factor modification.<br><br>Standard berry aneurysm management in ADPKD: 5-10 percent prevalence of intracranial aneurysms, screening with MRA in patients with family history of intracranial aneurysm or subarachnoid haemorrhage. Conservative management: aneurysms under 7-10 mm, no high-risk features.<br><br>Immediate clipping (option A); Urgent coiling (option B); No follow-up (option C), none being ADPKD 4 mm berry aneurysm management like conservative with BP control and monitoring.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "CKD stage 4 patient undergoing angiography — best prevention of contrast nephropathy:", "a": "Sodium bicarbonate superior", "b": "Prophylactic dialysis", "c": "IV isotonic saline hydration", "d": "N-acetylcysteine", "ans": "C", "e": "IV isotonic saline hydration best prevents contrast nephropathy in CKD stage 4 patient undergoing angiography; characteristic volume expansion before and after contrast reduces nephrotoxicity.<br><br>Standard CIN prevention: isotonic saline 1 mL/kg/hour for 6-12 hours before and 6-12 hours after contrast, minimising contrast volume, avoiding nephrotoxins, using iso-osmolar or low-osmolar contrast. N-acetylcysteine and sodium bicarbonate not proven beneficial in large trials.<br><br>Sodium bicarbonate superior (option A); Prophylactic dialysis (option B); N-acetylcysteine (option D) is not the correct choice, none being CKD CIN prevention like IV isotonic saline hydration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Diffuse proliferative lupus nephritis most appropriate induction therapy:", "a": "Rituximab first line", "b": "Prednisolone alone", "c": "Hydroxychloroquine alone", "d": "Mycophenolate + steroids OR cyclophosphamide + steroids", "ans": "D", "e": "Mycophenolate plus steroids OR cyclophosphamide plus steroids treats diffuse proliferative lupus nephritis (Class IV); characteristic combination immunosuppression addresses severe glomerular inflammation.<br><br>Standard Class IV lupus nephritis treatment: induction with mycophenolate mofetil OR cyclophosphamide PLUS corticosteroids (pulse methylprednisolone then prednisolone). Maintenance with mycophenolate or azathioprine.<br><br>Rituximab first line (option A) is not the correct choice; Prednisolone alone (option B) is not the correct choice; Hydroxychloroquine alone (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Class IV lupus nephritis induction like mycophenolate plus steroids OR cyclophosphamide plus steroids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules indicate:", "a": "MPGN", "b": "Amyloidosis", "c": "Diabetic nephropathy", "d": "Light chain deposition disease", "ans": "C", "e": "Diabetic nephropathy is indicated by Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules; characteristic nodular glomerulosclerosis with mesangial expansion and hyalinosis reflects long-standing hyperglycaemia.<br><br>Standard diabetic nephropathy features: hyperfiltration (early), microalbuminuria (30-300 mg/day), macroalbuminuria (over 300 mg/day), nephrotic-range proteinuria, declining GFR, Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules on biopsy (specific finding), GBM thickening, mesangial expansion. Treatment: glycaemic control, BP control, ACE inhibitors/ARBs, SGLT-2 inhibitors.<br><br>MPGN (option A) is not the correct choice; Amyloidosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Light chain deposition disease (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules indication like diabetic nephropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "The first detectable sign of diabetic nephropathy is:", "a": "Microalbuminuria", "b": "Reduced GFR", "c": "Overt proteinuria", "d": "Hypertension", "ans": "A", "e": "Microalbuminuria is first detectable sign of diabetic nephropathy; characteristic urinary albumin 30-300 mg/day reflects early glomerular damage before overt clinical features.<br><br>Standard diabetic nephropathy stages: hyperfiltration (asymptomatic), microalbuminuria (30-300 mg/day or albumin/creatinine ratio 30-300 mg/g), macroalbuminuria (over 300 mg/day), nephrotic-range proteinuria, declining GFR, ESRD. Screening: annual albumin/creatinine ratio in all diabetics.<br><br>Reduced GFR (option B) is not the correct choice; Overt proteinuria (option C) is not the correct choice; Hypertension (option D) is not the correct choice, none being diabetic nephropathy first detectable sign like microalbuminuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Congo red apple-green birefringence indicates:", "a": "Fibrillary GN", "b": "Light chain deposition disease", "c": "Renal amyloidosis", "d": "Cryoglobulinaemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Renal amyloidosis is indicated by Congo red apple-green birefringence; characteristic stain detects amyloid deposits in tissue.<br><br>Standard renal amyloidosis features: nephrotic syndrome, AL amyloidosis, AA amyloidosis. Diagnosis: Congo red stain showing apple-green birefringence under polarised light, immunohistochemistry or mass spectrometry to characterise type.<br><br>Fibrillary GN (option A) is not the correct choice; Light chain deposition disease (option B) is not the correct choice; Cryoglobulinaemia (option D) is not the correct choice, none being Congo red apple-green birefringence indication like renal amyloidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Best test to characterize amyloid type:", "a": "Congo red alone", "b": "Immunohistochemistry or mass spectrometry", "c": "Serum electrophoresis", "d": "Bone marrow biopsy", "ans": "B", "e": "Immunohistochemistry or mass spectrometry best characterise amyloid type; characteristic protein identification distinguishes AL (light chain) from AA (secondary) and other rare types.<br><br>Standard amyloid characterisation: immunohistochemistry, mass spectrometry. Combined with addressing through treatment by type (AL: bortezomib-based chemotherapy, autologous stem cell transplant; AA: addressing underlying inflammation).<br><br>Congo red alone (option A) is not the correct choice; Serum electrophoresis (option C) is not the correct choice; Bone marrow biopsy (option D) is not the correct choice, none being amyloid type characterisation like immunohistochemistry or mass spectrometry.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Renal handling of uric acid:", "a": "Only secreted", "b": "No renal handling", "c": "Filtered, reabsorbed, secreted, re-reabsorbed", "d": "Only filtered", "ans": "C", "e": "Filtered, reabsorbed, secreted, re-reabsorbed describes renal handling of uric acid; characteristic complex bidirectional transport produces net urate excretion of approximately 10 percent of filtered load.<br><br>Standard urate handling: 100 percent filtered at glomerulus, 99 percent reabsorbed in proximal tubule, 50 percent secreted back into tubule (ABCG2, MRP4), 40 percent re-reabsorbed, net 10 percent excreted. Combined with addressing through urate-lowering drugs: xanthine oxidase inhibitors, uricosurics.<br><br>Only secreted (option A); No renal handling (option B); Only filtered (option D), none being uric acid renal handling like filtered, reabsorbed, secreted, re-reabsorbed.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Loop diuretics act by blocking:", "a": "Na-Cl cotransporter", "b": "Aldosterone receptor", "c": "Carbonic anhydrase", "d": "Na-K-2Cl cotransporter", "ans": "D", "e": "Na-K-2Cl cotransporter is blocked by loop diuretics in thick ascending limb of loop of Henle; characteristic mechanism produces potent diuresis by preventing NaCl reabsorption in this high-capacity segment.<br><br>Standard loop diuretics: block NKCC2 in thick ascending limb, reduce NaCl reabsorption (most potent diuretics), disrupt corticomedullary gradient, increase urinary calcium and magnesium excretion. Indications: heart failure, hypertension, hypercalcaemia, fluid overload.<br><br>Na-Cl cotransporter (option A) is not the correct choice; Aldosterone receptor (option B) is spironolactone target; Carbonic anhydrase (option C) is acetazolamide target, none being loop diuretic target like Na-K-2Cl cotransporter.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Spironolactone causes hyperkalaemia because it:", "a": "Inhibits Na-K ATPase", "b": "Increases proximal K reabsorption", "c": "Blocks aldosterone receptor in collecting duct", "d": "Reduces GFR", "ans": "C", "e": "Blocks aldosterone receptor in collecting duct causes spironolactone-induced hyperkalaemia; characteristic mineralocorticoid receptor antagonism prevents sodium-potassium exchange.<br><br>Standard spironolactone features: aldosterone receptor antagonist (competitive), reduces sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion in collecting duct, weak potassium-sparing diuretic, antihypertensive, heart failure (mortality benefit), hyperaldosteronism. Side effects: hyperkalaemia, gynaecomastia, menstrual irregularities.<br><br>Inhibits Na-K ATPase (option A) is not the correct choice; Increases proximal K reabsorption (option B) is not the correct choice; Reduces GFR (option D) is not the correct choice, none being spironolactone hyperkalaemia mechanism like blocks aldosterone receptor in collecting duct.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Thiazides ineffective in CKD because:", "a": "Require functioning distal tubule; ineffective when GFR <30", "b": "Absorption altered", "c": "Cause AKI", "d": "Increase aldosterone", "ans": "A", "e": "Require functioning distal tubule and become ineffective when GFR very low explains why thiazides are ineffective in CKD; characteristic dependence on tubular delivery and function limits efficacy at low GFR.<br><br>Standard thiazide diuretic features: block NCCT in distal convoluted tubule, effective at GFR over 30 mL/min, ineffective below. Alternatives in advanced CKD: loop diuretics, combination with metolazone for synergy.<br><br>Absorption altered (option B); Cause AKI (option C); Increase aldosterone (option D), none being thiazide ineffective in CKD reason like requires functioning distal tubule and ineffective at very low GFR.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Acetazolamide mechanism:", "a": "Aldosterone blockade", "b": "NKCC2 blockade", "c": "Carbonic anhydrase inhibition causing bicarbonaturia", "d": "ADH inhibition", "ans": "C", "e": "Carbonic anhydrase inhibition causing bicarbonaturia is acetazolamide mechanism; characteristic blockade of bicarbonate reabsorption in proximal tubule produces mild diuresis and metabolic acidosis.<br><br>Standard acetazolamide features: carbonic anhydrase inhibitor, weak diuretic, causes bicarbonaturia. Indications: glaucoma (reduces aqueous humour production), altitude sickness (prevents and treats), urinary alkalinisation (uric acid stones), pseudotumour cerebri, metabolic alkalosis.<br><br>Aldosterone blockade (option A) is not the correct choice; NKCC2 blockade (option B) is not the correct choice; ADH inhibition (option D) is not the correct choice, none being acetazolamide mechanism like carbonic anhydrase inhibition causing bicarbonaturia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "NSAIDs in CKD cause all EXCEPT:", "a": "Reduced GFR", "b": "Increased renal blood flow", "c": "Sodium retention", "d": "Hyperkalaemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Increased renal blood flow is NOT NSAID effect in CKD; characteristic NSAIDs decrease renal blood flow through prostaglandin inhibition, worsening renal function in vulnerable patients.<br><br>Standard NSAID effects in CKD: decreased renal blood flow, AKI, acute interstitial nephritis, papillary necrosis (chronic use), sodium and water retention (worsens hypertension and oedema), hyperkalaemia.<br><br>Reduced GFR (option A) is not the correct choice; Sodium retention (option C) is not the correct choice; Hyperkalaemia (option D) IS NSAID effect in CKD, none being NOT NSAID effect in CKD like increased renal blood flow.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Free water clearance formula:", "a": "GFR × (1−reabsorption)", "b": "UNa/PNa", "c": "Urine volume − (Urine volume × Uosm/Posm)", "d": "Uosm/Posm", "ans": "C", "e": "Urine volume minus (urine volume x Uosm/Posm) is free water clearance formula; characteristic calculation quantifies water excretion independent of solute clearance.<br><br>Standard free water clearance interpretation: positive value indicates net water excretion, negative value indicates net water reabsorption, zero indicates osmotic clearance matches urine flow. Applications: assessing renal water handling, differentiating SIADH vs other hyponatraemia causes, evaluating diabetes insipidus.<br><br>GFR × (1−reabsorption) (option A); UNa/PNa (option B); Uosm/Posm (option D) is not the correct choice, none being free water clearance formula like urine volume minus (urine volume x Uosm/Posm).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Gold standard for GFR measurement:", "a": "CKD-EPI", "b": "Inulin clearance", "c": "Creatinine", "d": "Cystatin C", "ans": "B", "e": "Inulin clearance is gold standard for GFR measurement; characteristic freely filtered substance not reabsorbed, secreted, or metabolised provides accurate GFR estimation.<br><br>Standard inulin clearance features: continuous infusion required, requires timed urine collection, technically challenging and expensive, used in research settings. Combined with practical alternatives: iothalamate clearance, iohexol clearance (radiocontrast cleared by GFR), 51Cr-EDTA, 99mTc-DTPA.<br><br>CKD-EPI (option A) is not the correct choice; Creatinine (option C) is not the correct choice; Cystatin C (option D) is not the correct choice, none being GFR measurement gold standard like inulin clearance.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Cystatin C superior to creatinine in:", "a": "AKI only", "b": "Children only", "c": "Elderly/low muscle mass patients", "d": "Normal muscle mass", "ans": "C", "e": "Elderly and low muscle mass patients benefit from cystatin C over creatinine for GFR estimation; characteristic cystatin C is not dependent on muscle mass providing better accuracy in these populations.<br><br>Standard cystatin C features: produced by all nucleated cells at constant rate, freely filtered, less dependent on age, sex, muscle mass. Useful in elderly, amputees, malnourished, paediatric, chronic disease.<br><br>AKI only (option A); Children only (option B); Normal muscle mass (option D), none being cystatin C over creatinine indication like elderly/low muscle mass patients.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Renal biopsy contraindicated in all EXCEPT:", "a": "Solitary kidney", "b": "Bleeding diathesis", "c": "Uncontrolled hypertension", "d": "Adult nephrotic syndrome needing diagnosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Adult nephrotic syndrome needing diagnosis is NOT contraindication to renal biopsy; characteristic indication for biopsy to determine specific glomerular disease guiding treatment.<br><br>Standard renal biopsy contraindications: solitary kidney (relative), uncontrolled hypertension, bleeding diathesis (correctable), severe anaemia, active UTI, very small kidneys, severe obesity, anticoagulation. Indications: unexplained AKI, adult nephrotic/nephritic syndrome, suspected systemic disease with renal involvement.<br><br>Solitary kidney (option A); Bleeding diathesis (option B); Uncontrolled hypertension (option C), none being NOT renal biopsy contraindication like adult nephrotic syndrome needing diagnosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Filling defect in renal pelvis with malignant cytology:", "a": "Wilms tumour", "b": "Angiomyolipoma", "c": "Transitional cell carcinoma", "d": "RCC", "ans": "C", "e": "Transitional cell carcinoma fits filling defect in renal pelvis with malignant cytology; characteristic urothelial carcinoma can occur anywhere along urinary tract (renal pelvis, ureter, bladder).<br><br>Standard transitional cell carcinoma features: most common upper tract urothelial cancer, risk factors, painless haematuria, filling defects on imaging, urinary cytology may show malignant cells. Treatment: nephroureterectomy (radical), surveillance for bladder recurrence.<br><br>Wilms tumour (option A); Angiomyolipoma (option B); RCC (option D) is not the correct choice, none being renal pelvis filling defect with malignant cytology like transitional cell carcinoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Wilms tumour associated syndrome:", "a": "Beckwith-Wiedemann only", "b": "Tuberous sclerosis", "c": "Von Hippel-Lindau", "d": "WAGR syndrome", "ans": "D", "e": "WAGR syndrome is associated with Wilms tumour; characteristic Wilms tumour, Aniridia, Genitourinary anomalies, mental Retardation due to 11p13 deletion (WT1 and PAX6 genes).<br><br>Standard Wilms tumour-associated syndromes: WAGR syndrome (11p13 deletion), Denys-Drash syndrome, Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome. Combined with addressing through screening (abdominal ultrasound every 3 months in high-risk syndromes until age 7-8).<br><br>Beckwith-Wiedemann only (option A) is not the correct choice; Tuberous sclerosis (option B) is not the correct choice; Von Hippel-Lindau (option C) is not the correct choice, none being Wilms tumour associated syndrome like WAGR.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Most common renal tumour in adults:", "a": "TCC", "b": "Wilms tumour", "c": "Renal cell carcinoma", "d": "Oncocytoma", "ans": "C", "e": "Renal cell carcinoma is most common renal tumour in adults; characteristic adenocarcinoma of renal tubular epithelium (most commonly clear cell variant) accounts for 90 percent of adult renal cancers.<br><br>Standard RCC features: classic triad in 10 percent, paraneoplastic syndromes, risk factors. Treatment: surgical resection (partial or radical nephrectomy), targeted therapy for metastatic.<br><br>TCC (option A) is not the correct choice; Wilms tumour (option B) is paediatric renal malignancy; Oncocytoma (option D) is benign tumour, none being most common adult renal tumour like renal cell carcinoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Severe hypertension with papilloedema and renal TMA:", "a": "Hypertensive emergency (malignant hypertension)", "b": "Stroke", "c": "SAH", "d": "Hypertensive urgency", "ans": "A", "e": "Hypertensive emergency (malignant hypertension) fits severe hypertension with papilloedema and renal thrombotic microangiopathy; characteristic accelerated BP elevation causes end-organ damage including retinopathy and renal failure.<br><br>Standard malignant hypertension features: severe BP elevation, retinal haemorrhages and papilloedema, AKI, thrombotic microangiopathy, encephalopathy, cardiac complications. Treatment: gradual BP reduction, IV antihypertensives (labetalol, nicardipine, sodium nitroprusside, hydralazine).<br><br>Stroke (option B) is not the correct choice; SAH (option C) is not the correct choice; Hypertensive urgency (option D) is not the correct choice, none being severe hypertension with papilloedema and renal TMA like hypertensive emergency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Safest opioid in renal failure:", "a": "Morphine", "b": "Tramadol", "c": "Fentanyl", "d": "Codeine", "ans": "C", "e": "Fentanyl is safest opioid in renal failure; characteristic hepatic metabolism with no active renal-cleared metabolites avoids accumulation in CKD.<br><br>Standard opioid use in CKD: fentanyl, methadone, hydromorphone, avoid morphine and codeine (active metabolites - morphine-6-glucuronide accumulates causing prolonged sedation, respiratory depression), avoid tramadol (lowers seizure threshold).<br><br>Morphine (option A) has active metabolite (morphine-6-glucuronide) accumulating in renal failure; Tramadol (option B) is poorly tolerated in renal failure (seizure risk); Codeine (option D) is metabolised to morphine (similar accumulation issue), none being safest opioid in renal failure like fentanyl.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
{"t": "Nephrology", "q": "Severe hyperkalaemia with sine wave ECG — correct management sequence:", "a": "Kayexalate → Insulin → Calcium → Dialysis", "b": "Calcium → Shift K⁺ → Remove K⁺", "c": "Dialysis only", "d": "Bicarbonate → Calcium → Dialysis", "ans": "B", "e": "Calcium then shift K+ then remove K+ describes correct management sequence for severe hyperkalaemia with sine wave ECG; characteristic urgent intervention prioritises cardiac stabilisation before potassium removal.<br><br>Standard severe hyperkalaemia management: calcium gluconate IV, shift potassium, remove potassium.<br><br>Kayexalate → Insulin → Calcium → Dialysis (option A) is not the correct choice; Dialysis only (option C) is not the correct choice; Bicarbonate → Calcium → Dialysis (option D) is not the correct choice, none being severe hyperkalaemia with sine wave ECG management like calcium then shift K+ then remove K+.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}
];
